<HEAD>More Than 226,000 Vietnamese Refugees Have Arrived In Malaysia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 From 1975 to this March, 226,091 Vietnamese boat people have landed in <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>, an official said today. The influx of Vietnamese refugees began in 1975 after <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces withdrew from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> and it fell to communist forces from <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>. Of the 226,091 refugees, 217,812 resettled in other countries, including 128,000 in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commissioner </ORGANIZATION> for Refugees for <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Brunei </LOCATION>. In the first three months of this year, 2,921 boat people reached <LOCATION> Malaysian </LOCATION> shores, higher than the 1,702 for the same period last year, he said. <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> told reporters the increase was due, in part, to <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>'s decision to forbid boats of refugees to land on its shores. The boat people generally land on the east coasts of <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> by cutting across the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>.
