<HEAD>Young Electrician Became Bethlehem's First Martyr In Uprising</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOCELYN NOVECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BETHLEHEM, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Salim </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaar </PERSON> always liked fixing things. He spent the last afternoon of his life laying new tiles on the family porch and wiring new lights. He planned to finish the job the next day, after a morning of throwing stones at <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> soldiers. But a soldier thought he saw a firebomb in <PERSON> Salim </PERSON>'s hand, and the next time <PERSON> Salim </PERSON> crossed the porch he was carried, with a bullet hole in his head. On an afternoon two weeks later, members of the family sat at home sipping strong Arab coffee and talking about the shy, 23-year-old electrician, <LOCATION> Bethlehem </LOCATION>'s first martyr of the Arab rebellion that began nearly five months ago in the Israeli-occupied lands. `` This uprising changes everyone,'' said <PERSON> Salim </PERSON>'s father, <PERSON> Khalil </PERSON>. `` It turns a sane man into a crazy man. It turns a shy man into an angry man.'' The clearest evidence of the change in <LOCATION> Salim </LOCATION> is in his diary, a frayed notepad from a souvenir shop lovingly preserved by his family. It speaks of his growing desperation. `` I do n't dream about toys anymore, mother,'' <PERSON> Salim </PERSON> wrote in an entry directed to his mother, <PERSON> Fatmah </PERSON>, several weeks before his death. `` When they killed my friends I grew up a thousand years.'' When the violence began Dec. 8, <PERSON> Salim </PERSON> was a good-natured young man devoted to his job, who often stopped at the homes of neighbors after work to see if anything needed fixing, his family says. `` People appreciated him, and his work made him happy,'' said his brother <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON>, 21. `` He did n't have any great ambitions.'' <PERSON> Salim </PERSON> was happy at his family's home, and had added a room to it where he could settle one day with a wife. He filled the new closets with books on electricity, and moved into the room only weeks before he died. His possessions do not seem those of a man driven to die for a cause. They reveal instead a young man who liked music _ Turkish singers and traditional Arab tunes _ and was an amateur photographer who filling albums with pictures of his friends. Friends and family said <PERSON> Salim </PERSON> began to change when the `` intefadah,'' Arabic for uprising, came to the towns and refugee camps near <LOCATION> Bethlehem </LOCATION>, taking the lives of young Palestinians like himself. `` <PERSON> Salim </PERSON> was affected by what was going on,'' said a cousin, <PERSON> Mussa </PERSON>. `` He had many friends who went to prison and it became obvious to him that one day he, too, would go to jail. So he wanted to prepare himself.'' He began spending free time at the nearby Dheishe refugee camp, talking to Palestinians who had been in jail and visiting the families of prisoners to offer emotional support. In the diary, <PERSON> Salim </PERSON> sounds alternately desperate and defiant. `` What's a human being worth without a homeland, without a flag, without an address?'' he wrote, and later: `` The enemy planes can raid our camps and kill our children, but can not kill our will to fight.'' The entry for Friday, April 1, the night before his death, was the most striking: `` If my friends come back without me, mother, do n't cry. Every tear in your eyes is oil to light a lamp of freedom.'' <PERSON> Salim </PERSON> was in a good mood that Saturday morning, his family said. He took a shower, donned khaki trousers and a sweater, kissed his mother and said: `` If I come back, I wo n't be late.'' He and his brother, <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON>, set off to join friends in <LOCATION> Bethlehem </LOCATION>'s market, gathering stones along the way. They became part of a group in central <LOCATION> Manger </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION>, where Israeli soldiers were stationed. `` When it's over, you go back home. I'll go to a friend's house,'' <PERSON> Salim </PERSON> told <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON>, anticipating the house-to-house search that often followed protests According to the army account of the morning's events, a soldier thought he saw a firebomb in <PERSON> Salim </PERSON>'s hand, but the family called that `` absurd.'' What no-one disputes is that <PERSON> Salim </PERSON> was killed instantly by a bullet that went through his right cheek and out the back of his neck. His parents, still in mourning clothes two weeks later, became defiant in their grief when asked if they would stop their seven other children from joining protests. `` We all have the right to demonstrate for what we believe in,'' <PERSON> Fatmah </PERSON> said. `` I will never take that from my children.'' <PERSON> Khalil </PERSON> nodded and added: `` Besides, <PERSON> Salim </PERSON> is not really dead. He lives on as a hero for our town.''
</TEXT>
