<HEAD>Contras In `Liberated Zone' Say They Won't Lay Down Arms</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs.</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 The writer, a photographer for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>, accompanied the Contra rebels for two days. Here is his account:
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MAURICIO OROZCO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PUNTA GORDA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Commander <PERSON> Halcon </PERSON> and his band of Nicaraguan rebels move freely around what they call their `` liberated zone'' in the jungles near the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> coast. They are willing to talk peace but wo n't lay down their arms. `` We have received orders from our high command to stop shooting,'' <PERSON> Halcon </PERSON> said as he sat under a tree while his men rested nearby. `` But we are not dropping our guard. The enemy can not be trusted.'' A peasant widow provided food and coffee to his company of young rebels, including several women. <PERSON> Halcon </PERSON>, a former Sandinista who fought against the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> of late strongman President <PERSON> Anastasio </PERSON> <PERSON> Somoza </PERSON>, and his troops are in the jungles of <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zelaya </LOCATION> province near the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> coast. They are part of the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nicarguan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>, or <ORGANIZATION> FDN </ORGANIZATION>, the main Contra force which has fought to overthrow the Sandinista government. The area is one of seven set up under a 60-day cease-fire agreement between the U.S.-backed Contras and the Sandinista. Under the agreement, the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> have promised not to attack Contra troops congregating in the areas. `` They do n't come here anyway,'' <PERSON> Halcon </PERSON> said. `` We liberated this zone a long time ago.'' Looking around at his troops, <PERSON> Halcon </PERSON> said, `` There is no one here among us against his will.'' `` The people know we are not mercenaries,'' he said. Journalists traveled with the group for a day, visiting different camps where they met groups of rebels. <PERSON> Halcon </PERSON> said he commands three companies of 100 men each in the rugged eastern zone. Sandinista army troops evacuated many of the residents from the mountainous region two years ago in an effort to remove the rebels' `` social base'' but some people refused to leave They often help the Contras and provide food. They do the same for the Sandinista army when it moves in. Some cattle still roam the area and <LOCATION> Contra </LOCATION> groups use abandoned farms. <PERSON> Halcon </PERSON> and his men appeared to be well-armed and in good spirits. They had enough medicine and beef and plenty of U.S.-made candy to eat. At night they danced to tapes of Mexican `` ranchera'' music, then slept in hammocks made of silky parachute cloth. The commander said the last air drop of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> supplies to the group came a month ago. Under the cease-fire that took effect April 1, rebels may receive humanitarian aid through neutral international organizations once they are settled in the designated zones. Details of the truce are still being worked out in talks which will resume Thursday. <PERSON> Halcon </PERSON> said he had received two letters from the regional commander of the Sandinista army asking him to meet with the government represntatives `` in an effort to achieve peace.'' He said he was waiting for further instructions from Contra headquarters. There have already been several meetings of army and rebel groups on the field since the cease-fire went into effect. `` We will do whatever our leaders tell us,'' <PERSON> Halcon </PERSON> said. `` If we had a complete cease-fire, it would be the most beautiful thing. We have been fighting among Nicaraguans for too long. But we are armed campesinos and we are willing to fight ... and we are not going to lay down our arms unless there is a definitive cease-fire.'' `` We will lay down our arms when the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> lay down theirs, when there is a democratic government in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>.''
