<HEAD>Police Crack Down On Manila's Red Light District</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The police chief is vowing to close down <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>'s honky-tonk district, which he claims had made it the `` Sin Capital of <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>.'' His targets are nightspots in the neighborhood known as the city's `` tourist belt,'' where scantily clad girls bump and grind to disco music and _ for a price _ go out with male customers. Although the <LOCATION> Ermita </LOCATION> district pumps millions of dollars each year into the city's economy, authorities have called for replacing the nightspots with more wholesome family entertainment. `` Now, we are known internationally as the center of the flesh trade, the <LOCATION> Sin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>,'' Brig. Gen. <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Lim </PERSON>, the capital's police chief, said recently. `` When we hear of this reference, all of us feel a furious sense of outrage, for we all know that we do n't deserve such notoriety.'' However, bar owners say the crackdown will cause worse problems, add to economic hardship and advance the spread of sexual disease. Last month, police began raiding bars and discos in the city's <LOCATION> Ermita </LOCATION> district They have rounded up more than 2,000 barmaids, known as `` hospitality girls,'' and detained dozens of foreigners who operate some of more than 505 bars, restaurants, discos, nightclubs and brothels in <LOCATION> Ermita </LOCATION>'s 10-block strip. President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> has backed the raids, saying `` what we should guard against is sacrificing the dignity and honor of the Filipino woman.'' But in a country with many economic problems, sex is big business. <PERSON> Lim </PERSON> said he expects bar owners _ mostly Americans, Australians, West Germans, Japanese and Filipinos _ to fight back by waging a smear campaign against him and his police force. `` They are employing all tricks to stop us so they can earn bundles and bundles of money,'' <PERSON> Lim </PERSON> said. `` They are capitalizing on our women.'' Indeed, an typical Ermita bar earns about $ 715 dollars on a regular day. The bigger establishments average about $ 1,666 daily. But <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Compuesto </PERSON>, general manager of the <ORGANIZATION> Hollywood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Show </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Palace </ORGANIZATION>, said the raids have been hurting the once-thriving entertainment industry, cutting daily earnings by as much as 70 percent. Moreover, <PERSON> Ronnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Rueda </PERSON>, operations manager of a leading club called Firehouse, said closing bars will force tens of thousands of <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> prostitutes to go underground. She says that will make it difficult to trace carriers of acquired immune deficiency syndrome and venereal diseases. <PERSON> Lim </PERSON> said 80 percent of 2,000 women picked up in the raids have been found suffering from venereal disease. The <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> said at least 50 Filipinos, mostly hospitality girls, have been infected with the AIDS virus, but none has developed its active symptoms. `` The problem of venereal disease will spread out because the women will become freelancers. They will hang around hotels and restaurants,'' <PERSON> Rueda </PERSON> said. `` Who will manage them and check them for diseases?'' <PERSON> Compuesto </PERSON> said his group has offered to help police by closing some establishments and ridding the area of free-lance prostitutes. But he says their offer has been ignored. `` If they are really trying to cure the problem of morality, this campaign should be nationwide,'' Compuesto said. `` How can they solve immorality, prostitution or drug abuse if they are only concentrating on Ermita?'' Other critics say closing <PERSON> Ermita </PERSON>'s seedy establishments would force some displaced workers into a life of crime. `` If you're starving and you're the only breadwinner in the family, I think there is nothing else to do,'' said <PERSON> Kit </PERSON> <PERSON> Samson </PERSON>, a disc jockey <PERSON> Compuesto </PERSON> said most bar girls are earning more than the $ 3 minimum daily wage of factory workers, not counting what they earn once they leave the bars with customers. `` Thousands of people do n't have jobs. We have jobs that we enjoy, but now they want to get it from us,'' Compuesto said. `` What kind of logic is that?'' `` It's really a hypocrisy of people to say that when tourists come to the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, they just want to see the sights in <LOCATION> Tagaytay </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Baguio </LOCATION> or some other part of the country,'' Compuesto said. `` They need entertainment.''
