<FIRST>r p PM-PentagonVeep Bjt   04-26 0756</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pentagon Veep, Bjt,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON WIRE: A Double-Duty Vice President for the Democrats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Imagine it: newspaper stories next year that begin with the words, `` Vice President and Secretary of Defense <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> said today that ...'' There would be a lot of ifs to be surmounted if <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>'s senior Democratic senator were in a position to assume such a jawbreaking and unprecedented dual title. <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> would have to win the Democratic presidential nomination, ask <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> to be his running mate, offer him the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> as an inducement to accept, and then win the fall campaign. But the idea is being floated _ apparently seriously _ by such leading Democrats as former <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Robb </PERSON>. Others say <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> as a prominent Southerner and respected defense expert would so strengthen a <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> ticket that he should be promised he could be secretary of state or national security adviser _ if he also agrees to run for vice president. <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> has said that no matter what inducements might be offered, his interest in the vice presidency is just about one on a scale of 10. But he has never said never. No vice president has ever served simultaneously as secretary of defense. No vice president has ever served simultaneously as a member of a president's <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION>. But a number of people who became vice president had previously served in presidential cabinets. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Calhoun </PERSON> served as vice president in one period and as secretary of state at another. Presidents have appointed vice presidents to task forces on one subject or another. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> named Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to head a task force on drugs and narcotics. President <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> named his vice president, <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, to head a task force on space exploration. Other vice presidents have had a strong influence on their administrations. But that has been the rare exception rather than the rule. While not barred by the Constitution, a vice president simultaneously serving as secretary of defense might well discover a thicket of unexpected conflicts. While the vice president has his job by election, a cabinet officer must be confirmed by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. The only job specifically assigned the vice president by the Constitution is to serve as president of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. Unexpected strains might arise if the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> were asked to confirm its own presiding office to serve as well in a Cabinet post. In the role of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s presiding officer, the vice president's only real power is his ability to cast tie-breaking votes at moments of legislative impasse. Some senators might demand that a vice president who was also the secretary of defense abstain from breaking a tie on closely divided defense issues directly affecting his department. Such a decision would deprive the administration of its ability to decide the issue in its favor by breaking the tie. Since 1981 <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has broken seven ties, five of them on defense issues. Secretaries of defense routinely testify before congressional committees in defense of military budgets. There is some potential awkwardness in a situation when the witness is also president of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. Concern might also be triggered if it became necessary for an elected vice president also serving as secretary of defense to travel with a president to an overseas conference. That would place both the president and vice president out of the country at the same time. And that might become a more worrisome situation if the country they were visiting were the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Naming <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> the national security adviser might create fewer such problems since the person who fills that post is not confirmed by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. The vice presidency has not always been a happy post for the person who held the job. Many have complained it consists of little more than attending the funerals of foreign leaders. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, the nation's first vice president, had some thoughts on his job which he shared with his colleagues on the eve of a visit to their chamber by President <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` Gentlemen, I feel great difficulty -LRB- in -RRB- how to act,'' <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> said. `` I am possessed of two separate powers. I am vice president. In this I am nothing, but I may be everything. `` But I am president also of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. When the president comes into the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, what shall I be?'' Some politicians are still thinking about what a vice president shall be, at least when <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>'s name comes up for discussion.
</TEXT>
