<HEAD>Bush Set To Lock In Nomination With Delegates Picked Today</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has had a virtual lock on the Republican presidential nomination since late March, but today's <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> primary should make it a mathematical certainty The contest, in which <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> only faces token opposition from former television evangelist <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON>, should raise his delegate total to more than the 1,139 needed for nomination at the GOP convention in August in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>. Savoring the situation on the eve of that vote, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told an airport rally in <LOCATION> Scranton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, on Monday: `` We got a break in this primary process. ... I'm glad it's gone my way.'' The vice president noted that due to his overwhelming lead in the race for the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> nomination, the campaign spotlight has been mostly on the Democratic contenders. But he said he was n't complaining `` The news is being dominated by the Jackson-Dukakis fight. That's the way it should be,' said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. `` I would n't trade places.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> predicted that the general election `` is going to be hard fought; it's going to be close.'' The vice president was campaigning today in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, both of which hold primaries a week from today. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was attending a rally in <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, addressing the <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasters </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION> and holding an airport rally in <LOCATION> Evansville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> tells audiences he'll still campaign through to the end of the primary season and `` ca n't wait'' to debate the Democratic nominee, who he has predicted will be <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. Even so, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> remains vague on the terms for such events. `` I'm not going to let some outside group, even within my own party, set the agenda,'' he told reporters in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>. `` I'll appoint somebody who knows about setting up debates'' and who could work with Democrats in coming up with a process agreeable to both parties, he said. On another subject, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> that he fully backs President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s vow to veto trade legislation nearing a final congressional vote. However, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he hoped that some other way could be found to notify workers of impending plant closings. The bill _ which <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has said he would sign if he were president _ contains a provision requiring 60 days advance when plants are to be shut down. `` Maybe there's a compassionate way to give notice to a worker and his family. But it has nothing to do with the trade bill,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` I know it's an emotional issue but -LRB- the bill -RRB- interferes with our ability to compete.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> did acknowledge that there were still areas of <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> and elsewhere that had not shared fully in the economic recovery that is now in its sixth year. But he criticized Democrats, saying they `` talk about despair and agony.'' `` You're going to see a clear choice'' in the general election, he said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has had a huge lead for the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> nomination since his remarkable 17-state sweep in the March 8 Super Tuesday contests, a lead he solidified with the withdrawal from the race on March 29 of Sen. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, his only remaining major rival. <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> is still technically a candidate but has ceased active campaigning, saying there is no way <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> can be denied the nomination. He has a scant 31 delegates, to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s 1,081. At his campaign appearance Monday at the Scranton-Wilkes-Barre airport, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was confronted by about two dozen protesters. `` I'm glad to see the -LRB- <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> supporters here, or maybe the <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> supporters,'' he said. Of the Democrats, he said: `` I will welcome them in debate, I will welcome taking on their ticket and we will beat them in the fall.''
