<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lando </PERSON> <PERSON> Zech </PERSON> says he agrees with a congressional study recommending that the agency improve its internal investigations. He made the statement Monday as his agency released a study by the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> that said the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> needs to ensure that its investigations are done professionally and competently. `` The commission will give careful consideration to -LRB- the -RRB- entire report in our continuing efforts to assure that we carry out our investigative responsibilities fairly and efficiently,'' <PERSON> Zech </PERSON> said. In the study, <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said `` the important mission and critical safety role of the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> require that it possess a first-rate investigative capability.'' <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>, the investigative wing of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, said the study was based on review of three investigations made within the nuclear agency. <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said that in two cases, the work done by the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION>'s Office of Inspector and Auditor was not thorough enough One case involved allegations by an <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> inspector that superiors had pressured him to change findings in 1986 about safety conditions at the <ORGANIZATION> Comanche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steam </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Station </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. The other involved alleged improper discussions in 1986 between <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Stello </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION>'s executive director of operations, and <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, head of the <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Authority </LOCATION>'s NRC-regulated nuclear program. <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said its review supported the findings of <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> investigators who said neither matter was improper. But in both cases <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said that <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> investigators had not interviewed individuals with key roles. The third case looked into <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION>'s probe of how a copy of an internal <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> document turned up in 1985 in the files of the <ORGANIZATION> Louisiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Light </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>'s Waterford III plant _ along with a memo from <ORGANIZATION> LPL </ORGANIZATION>'s holding company saying the document had been `` received from sources inside'' the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said notations on the copy indicated it was duplicated from the file copy in the office of <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> Commissioner <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>, who was in charge of investigating the alleged leak. <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> was critical of the `` very limited'' investigation made by <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>, but <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said it was unable to determine how the copy reached the regulated utility. `` A properly conducted investigation might have provided <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> with the identity'' of the leaker, according to <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>. The case, <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said, `` demonstrated that a regulated utility secured unauthorized access to <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> documents. The ability to obtain such materials could impact on the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION>'s enforcement program, licensing functions and regulatory procedures.'' `` The <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> should assure that its investigators conduct their work in a competent manner using professional standards,'' said <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>, adding that there is a lack of coordination between the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investigations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> of Inspector and Auditor
