<SECOND>PM-Arms Treaty,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>GOP Leaders Try To Find Way To Assure May INF Ratification</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Republicans are trying to make sure the medium-range missile treaty is ratified before President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> meets Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> on May 29, but the majority leader says Democrats wo n't be rushed. Senate Minority Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, R-Kan., appealed on Monday for swift action on the treaty He said the president deserves to be accommodated on his wish not to go to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> empty-handed. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has said it is important for the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> to ratify the treaty before he meets <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> because there is little chance the two sides will make further arms control progress unless the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> has acted favorably. But Majority Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> said he refused `` to be rushed or harried'' on the matter before remaining problems are cleared away. <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> said he will not call up the treaty for debate before May 9. He added he may not do so then unless it can be shown the Soviets agree with the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> position that the pact bans medium-range `` futuristic'' weapons such as those using laser rays or particle beam generators. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> and other Republicans huddled Monday with White House chief of staff <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> and national security adviser <PERSON> Colin </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> to devise a strategy to deal with <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>'s concerns and get the treaty debate started. <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> replied: `` I want to accommodate the president too, and will accommodate the president where I can. ... But that is not my first responsibility. ... That is not my first objective. `` I'm going to accommodate the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and our responsibilities under the Constitution first, before the accommodation of anybody else or any other office.'' The treaty is silent on future weapons, but <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> negotiators contend the pact bans all weapons with ranges of from 300 miles to 3,400 miles, no matter how they are armed.
