<HEAD>Oil Rig Fire Cuts Brazilian Production By 11 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three ships were fighting a fire on <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s largest offshore oil rig, and the state oil company, <ORGANIZATION> Petrobas </ORGANIZATION>, said the blaze has caused an 11 percent drop in the nation's petroleum output. <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinto </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Petrobras </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, said the fire broke out Sunday when gas leaked from the Enchova platform in the <LOCATION> Campos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Basin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s richest oil-producing region, 120 miles east of <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> De </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Janeiro </LOCATION>. The 250 workers on the oil rig were safely evacuated to a ship, he said. Three ships on Monday continued to spray the platform with water in an effort to put out the fire, the spokesman said. <PERSON> Enchova </PERSON> and four connected fields were shut down, halting the production of 71,000 barrels of oil and 2 million cubic meters of gas per day, <PERSON> Pinto </PERSON> said. The campos basin offshore fields produce 60 percent of the nation's oil output of 615,000 barrels a day and 40 percent of the 17 million cubic meters of gas. <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> imports about 45 percent of the oil it uses.
