<TEXT>
 It was story time for 28 toddlers and the choice was an old favorite, `` The Very Hungry Caterpillar.'' But the storyteller was a newcomer to the Discovery School _ <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, the front-runner in today's <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> primary. He was a hit with the preschool set. Monday was a day of big crowds and loud cheers for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, and the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor was trying out a relaxed campaign style. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> held a big lead over rival <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, and about all aides had to wonder about was how big a delegate victory he could win in the state. `` I look forward to working with you and to winning with you tomorrow,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> told about 500 people in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> on the eve of the primary. In his final day of campaigning before the <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> vote, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was at ease and ready to quip. `` I saw a Bush sign around here some place,'' he asked 1,000 gathered on the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scranton </ORGANIZATION> campus. `` You know, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is the only guy who had a baseball league named after him. Then he asked if the crowd held any fans of the <ORGANIZATION> Baltimore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orioles </ORGANIZATION> _ the team with the worst record in baseball at the moment. `` Where are the <ORGANIZATION> Orioles </ORGANIZATION> fans around here? You know if you're an Orioles fan you have to be headed for a career in social work or something. You have to be very charitable,'' he said. But <LOCATION> Scranton </LOCATION> brought <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> face-to-face with some of the most strident demonstrators of the campaign thus far. Fifty anti-abortion protesters sought to form a gantlet for the c