<FIRST>r w PM-FarmExports     04-26 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Exports,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trade Barriers Hamper US Sales Abroad</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Belgians crave crawdads but have yet to sample catfish, while Saudi Arabians find American rice so much to their liking that they package rice from <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> to make it look as if it came from here, the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> says. Those are a few of the useful bits of knowledge for Americans who want to export food products compiled by the department in a recent 204-page book called `` Trade Policies and Market Opportunities for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Farm Exports.'' It tells of quotas, tariffs, surcharges, health and sanitary rules and other restrictions that plague American exporters to more than 100 countries. The April issue of the department's magazine, `` Foreign Agriculture,'' gives an account of the report. For example, wine ca n't be advertised in <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> _ governments there want to hold down drinking. In <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, it's margarine that ca n't be advertised because the government wants to protect French dairy farmers from competition on their sales of butter <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> wo n't buy almonds at all because it's protecting its meager stock of foreign exchange. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> wo n't buy tallow for religious reasons: the cows it is made from are sacred to Hindus. <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> is said to know too little about <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> tallow to order it. None of the 12 countries in the European Community will buy foreign meat if it's mixed with soy protein _ they say it's to protect consumers. There's no duty in <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> on imports of that American rice the Saudis like so much. <LOCATION> Bahrain </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> neighbor, buys rice almost entirely from <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. The book makes no judgment on whether the obstacles are fair or unfair, an issue much discussed in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> during the current debate on the trade bill. `` Virtually every country provides support and protection to agriculture in some degree,'' it explains. `` In some cases this is done primarily through policies that raise prices to consumers by protecting the domestic market; in other cases, assistance is provided through subsidies financed by the taxpayer.'' In some cases, the countries do not believe that their actions constitute barriers. In other cases, the book implies that American producers could do more to sell their products. Under the heading `` reason for the barrier'' a frequent explanation is `` lack of awareness.'' That is the cause it gives for low sales in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> not only of American catfish and crayfish _ which are lumped together _ but also grapefruit juice, frozen potatoes, wood panel products, hardwoods from temperate climates and beer. <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> is also noted as a country where lack of awareness of the American product keeps down the sale of catfish. The book says nothing about the Belgian appetite for crayfish, which is considerable.
</TEXT>
