<HEAD>Tug Of War Over Trade Bill Under Way in Senate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A tug of war is under way in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> as sponsors of a 1,000-page trade bill move to line up enough votes to show they could override a threatened presidential veto. `` You let this bill go down the tubes and I'll tell you where the champagne corks will be popping,'' <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, told senators Monday. `` They'll be popping in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and they'll be popping in <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>.'' The bill is expected to clear the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> with votes to spare. But from there it heads for the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and, evidently, a presidential veto. The question is whether it will receives the two-thirds support it would need to override a veto. Sponsors and the administration are looking for any wavering votes they can still find. Major provisions of the bill would streamline the system under which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> imposes import curbs to punish international trade violations and aid industries threatened by foreign competition. Other provisions range from billions of dollars in new agricultural subsidies to repeal of the windfall profits tax on oil companies. The administration has saved most of its fire lately for a provision that would require all but the smallest employers to give 60-day notice of plant closings and large-scale layoffs. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> had been set to vote today, but with neither side satisfied that it had done everything possible, leaders said they might wait until Wednesday. As the showdown neared, lawmakers and congressional staffers on both sides said the outcome appeared too close to call. Democrats were expected to vote for the bill overwhelmingly while Republicans were divided on whether to stand by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration in hopes of getting a slimmed-down version later. `` It's close,'' <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> told reporters. `` It was an uphill battle, but now it's a tossup.'' The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> approved the measure 312-107 on Thursday, more than enough to override a veto. `` I know this is an election year and the majority party may be looking for a campaign issue rather than a trade bill, but I am confident the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> could pass a better bill if this one is rejected,'' Sen. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stafford </PERSON>, R-Vt., said Democratic leaders have been saying it would be tough to bring another trade bill onto the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> leaves <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to campaign full time this fall. For one thing, they say, bringing such a bill onto the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor without something like the year of committee consideration that shaped the current version could make the new one a target for an array of amendments that in themselves could torpedo the measure. As dubious as they have been about a stripped-down trade bill, however, Democratic leaders have left the door open a crack for such an effort if <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s veto is sustained. One of the first items to go in any new bill could be the plant-closings provision. Business groups say it would dry up capital for investment and frighten off customers, but it has strong backing from labor. Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Danforth </PERSON>, R-Mo., told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> `` high officials of the administration'' had told him that portions of the bill `` are acceptable to the administration. `` We pulled off the hat trick, we pulled off the miracle,'' <PERSON> Danforth </PERSON> said. `` The administration now says that while it's not perfect it is something that the president would be willing to sign without plant closings.''
