<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lawyers for <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON> and his Iran-Contra co-defendants are on a collision course with the judge, as they argue for dismissal of the case on grounds that evidence was gathered illegally. A pre-trial hearing Monday began on a sour note for the defense team, when <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Gerhard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> ruled lawyers for North and two other defendants violated his ground rules for the hearing, and would be barred from presenting any witnesses. From that point the proceeding rolled downhill for the defense lawyers, as <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> rebuffed their request to question the top prosecutors _ and grand jury witnesses _ about their exposure to testimony given to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> under a grant of immunity. Nor would <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> permit the defense to immediately review instructions given by independent counsel <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> and his staff to grand jurors, when they were advised in their secret proceedings to avoid news accounts of the congressional hearings. `` I have a great sense of unfairness for my client,'' complained <PERSON> North </PERSON> lawyer <PERSON> Brendan </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> as the hearing dragged on. <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> responded moments later, `` I do n't think lawyers should run'' the hearing. `` I should.'' Nonetheless, <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> made no final ruling on <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>'s charge of `` enormous taint'' in the case, and the judge scheduled another hearing for Wednesday. If <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> finds after that hearing questions remain about the validity of the prosecution evidence, he can order further hearings on the subject that could push back the judge's initial hope for a July trial date. <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> is barred from using a witness' immunized testimony to prosecute that witness, except for perjury. However, the judge said it would still be possible to have a trial even if some evidence were obtained improperly, because the `` tainted'' evidence and certain witnesses could be barred from the case. Three defendants testified before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> last summer under immunity grants: <PERSON> North </PERSON>, the former <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> staffer who directed the once-secret operations that sent arms to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, and to the Nicaraguan Contra rebels when such assistance was prohibited by law; his boss at the time, National Security Adviser <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON>; and businessman <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON>, who handled the millions of dollars in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> arms sales profits that were stashed in Swiss bank accounts. <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON>'s partner, retired <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Secord </PERSON>, is the fourth defendant but his leadoff testimony at the congressional hearings was given without an immunity grant. The defendants are charged with conspiring to use <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> arms sales profits illegally to aid the Contras, and to cover up their actions. They also are accused of theft of government property, obstruction of government inquiries, making false statements, and destruction of documents. While Monday's proceedings were under way, defense lawyers filed a notice that they would appeal <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON>'s pre-trial rulings that went against them. The judge had invited them to do so during the hearing, saying the defense objections `` stand out like the Statue of Liberty.'' `` Go ahead and have your romp upstairs -LRB- in the appeals court -RRB-,'' <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> said. The only witness Monday was <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>, who testified about his repeated written and oral instructors to his staff, to witnesses and to grand jurors to avoid being influenced by immunized testimony. He said his evidence was gathered independently, and filed weekly with the court. <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> did admit, however, that one of his assistants, <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Todd </PERSON>, has voluntarily withdrawn from aspects of the case because of possible exposure to immunized testimony. `` I do n't know anything about the conditions'' that prompted <PERSON> Todd </PERSON>'s decision, <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> said. `` He did n't want to taint me. I do n't know whether he was tainted or not. <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> hammered again and again at <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>'s admission that he did n't know whether everyone complied with his orders. Compliance, <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> said, sometimes required a degree of common sense. The prosecutor sarcastically told <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> `` there was no discussion of how quickly you could turn off the television'' if a report on the congressional hearings came on. And when <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> pointed out that comedy shows such as `` Saturday Night Live'' made references to immunized testimony, <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> said he had no idea whether those receiving his instructions turned off the programs. But <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> said each of his assistants knows `` he's jeopardizing the investigation if he's careless.'' <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stern </PERSON>, a former federal judge and veteran prosecutor representing <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> on the immunity issue, said he can show `` every bit of the evidence was independently derived.'' `` The extensive procedures of insulation are just extras and are really not needed,'' <PERSON> Stern </P