 in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> appears to have assuaged the concerns of some <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> supporters who were upset by his comment on <ORGANIZATION> CBS-TV </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Face the Nation'' that as president he would not meet with <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>. <PERSON> Jabara </PERSON> accused <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> of `` caving in'' to Jewish groups, and said many members of his group were dismayed by the TV interview. But the transcript of a subsequent interview that was printed in the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> seemed to `` clear up any misunderstandings,'' <PERSON> Jabara </PERSON> said. In that interview, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> pointed out there is a law, which he said should be changed, prohibiting <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials from talking to the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> because the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> does not recognize <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. He said the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> is `` by far the most representative organization of the Palestinian people'' and should be represented at the negotiating table. The developments were important to many Arab-Americans, who have long looked to <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> as their voice in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> political world. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s relationship with the Arabs goes back to 1979 when as a private but well-known citizen he visited the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> on a fact-finding tour and was photographed embracing <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>. That picture still angers many American Jews. But the Arabs see <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> as a leader who is interested in the rights of their people as well as the security of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. For many years <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has held that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy against negotiating with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> is counterproductive. His support for establishment of a <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> homeland also has endeared him to the Arabs. But he also contends the Arab states and Palestinians must recognize <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s right to exist. During <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s 1984 presidential campaign, his Arab ties created a stir when it was disclosed that his Chicago-based civil rights organization had received $ 200,000 from the <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>, a group of <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> governments. The contributions to the education-oriented PUSH for Excellence and the PUSH Foundation caused controversy, especially among Jewish groups who contended <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was too dependent on Arab money. <PERSON> Zogby </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Arab-American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, said Arab-Americans, who number an estimated 2 million throughout the country mostly concentrated in about a dozen cities, had achieved finanical and social security but felt excluded politically until <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s 1984 presidential race. `` <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> brought them into the process and they do n't forget that.'' He acknowledged <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s televised comments two weeks ago caused, `` an initial round of concern.'' But he said <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> support again was pouring in by the time the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> campaign ended April 19, and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> had savaged <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> as being anti-Israeli. After the `` Face the Nation'' interview, some members of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arab-Americans </ORGANIZATION> raised que