<HEAD>Jackson Makes Election-Eve Appeal At Harrisburg Rally</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL BLOOD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Democratic presidential candidate <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> made an election-eve appeal for support in today's <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> primary, telling a chanting crowd at a rally: `` This room is full of hope today. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> came to the state capital for a meeting with Gov. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> and staged a rally that drew a crowd of 2,000. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was holding meetings in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> this morning with a <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official and members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, and heading later to <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, which holds its primary a week from today. At the <LOCATION> Harrisburg </LOCATION> rally, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> stressed the themes that have been the cornerstone of his campaign: reversing <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration economic policies, fighting drug abuse, and bringing more Americans into the political process. `` This room is full of hope today. A great dimension of our campaign is to keep hope alive. Our mission is to keep <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> strong and make <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> better,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> told the crowd. `` In this room today are farmers and workers; the black, the white, the brown, the red, the yellow, the middle class, the lower class ... We the people have come together to find common ground,'' he said. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s campaign stop in <LOCATION> Harrisburg </LOCATION> was one of several he made across <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> Monday, the day before the state's 2.8 million Democrats were going to the polls to voice their preference for the party's presidential nominee. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> also made appearances in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, where much of his support is rooted. In <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was questioned repeatedly about a statement he made Sunday regarding negotiation with terrorists. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said Monday he could conceive of situations where he would grant safe passage to hostage-takers, saying `` I choose negotiation over blind bloody confrontation.'' He rejected what he called `` material concessions'' to terrorists but did not rule out political accommodation `` If we are going to deter terrorism, we must address the underlying causes of terrorism,'' he said after an appearance at a high school in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>. `` Terrorism does not emerge out of the blue.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said Sunday he disagreed with <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' position that `` we should not negotiate with terrorists.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said, `` I disagree with that; if I could get the hostages out, I'd do it.'' <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Phyllis </PERSON> <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> said Monday the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government will `` talk to anyone, to any group, to any government about the well-being and release of the Americans still held hostage in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>.'' But she added, `` We will not make concessions to terrorists or compromise our fundamental principles.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, who polls say is lagging behind <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> in today's contest, has been campaigning heavily in urban areas in recent days. A poll released Monday by <ORGANIZATION> KYW-TV </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> KDKA-TV </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> showed <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> led <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> by 26 percentage points, with 57 percent for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, 31 percent for <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and 12 percent undecided. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> arrived at the <LOCATION> Harrisburg </LOCATION> rally behind schedule. The wait, however, did not dampen the spirits of those attending the rally, and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was greeted at the podium by thunderous applause and shouts of encouragement. `` I seek to lead our nation beyond racism, beyond sexism, beyond anti-Semitism, beyond escapism and beyond war. We must make <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> better and keep <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> strong,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said to cheers. He called for more spending to fight drug abuse. `` You just do n't say no to a $ 150 billion-a-year industry,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said, referring to First Lady <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s advice that youngsters `` just say no'' to drugs. `` If you want to fight a war you've got to have a budget,'' he said. Following his address, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> met briefly with <PERSON> Casey </PERSON>, also a Democrat, who has not endorsed a presidential candidate. `` We're very impressed with the ideas he's expressed for investing in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, infrastructure investment programs and the war on drugs ...'' <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Reginald </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Hershey </LOCATION> resident who attended the <LOCATION> Harrisburg </LOCATION> rally, said he was impressed with <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s concern for all residents. `` We have a chance to make history. Even if his nomination fails on the convention floor, we have made history,'' he said.
