<FIRST>r w PM-House-Genocide     04-26 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-House-Genocide,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Approves Penalties for Genocide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 House action has taken the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on its way to becoming a full participant in international agreements aimed at preventing genocide. By a voice vote, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> on Monday approved largely symbolic legislation setting stiff penalties for the crime of genocide. The legislation, which is backed by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, must also be ratified by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. Although the International Convention on the Prevention and Punishment of the Crime of Genocide was adopted by the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> and signed by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1948, it was not ratified by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> until 1986. The international accords are aimed at preventing and punishing attempts to destroy, in whole or in major part, a national, ethnic, religious, racial or religious group. Since the convention itself contains no mechanism to punish violators, the nations which have signed and ratified it it are required to pass anti-genocide laws. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration officials contend that full implementation of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> participation in the genocide convention will remove an international human rights embarrassment. A report on the bill issued by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> quoted Assistant Secretary of State <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Schifter </PERSON> on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> position: `` Most of us will agree that genocide is not likely to take place within the borders of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Schifter </PERSON> said. `` Our action on this convention is above all a symbolic act. `` It underlines our role of leadership in the free world on behalf of the cause of human rights.'' The bill sets prison sentences ranging from 20 years to life for people convicted of such offenses and sets fines of up to $ 1 milliion. It also provides for a prison term of up to five years and a fine of up to $ 500,000 for people convicted of inciting others to undertake acts of genocide. Those penalties would apply to crimes of genocide committed by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> nationals or which are committed within the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The legislation also suspends the statute of limitations for prosecutions on allegations of genocide.
</TEXT>
