<TEXT>
 <PERSON> DeAndra </PERSON> <PERSON> Anrig </PERSON>, the 8-year-old `` kite crusader'' who soared for 100 feet at the end of a kite string last month, still has her head in the clouds, her mother says. `` It's amazing. The -LRB- attention -RRB- still has n't died down,'' said <PERSON> Debbie </PERSON> <PERSON> Anrig </PERSON>. `` This child has just eaten it up.'' On March 20, <PERSON> DeAndra </PERSON> was flying her 12-foot kite at Shoreline Park in Mountain View when a plane landing at <LOCATION> Palo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> caught the kite's 200-pound test line and carried the child 10 feet into the air. She flew for 100 feet, let go as she approached a clump of trees and fell to the ground, sustaining minor injuries. Since then, talk shows keep discussing her adventure and stories have appeared in newspapers nationwide. Fan mail also continues to pour in from all over the country. <PERSON> DeAndra </PERSON> _ or <PERSON> Andi </PERSON>, as family and friends call her _ is so well-known that some of it is delivered without an address. `` All it says is <PERSON> DeAndra </PERSON> <PERSON> Anrig </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Dublin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Anrig </PERSON> said. `` The postman knows who it is.'' Some letters, she says, are addressed to `` The Kite Crusader'' and `` The Little Flying Girl.'' The only bad thing is that <PERSON> Andi </PERSON>'s 4-year-old brother, <PERSON> Dean </PERSON>, feels a little left out, Mrs. <PERSON> Anrig </PERSON> said. But the Anrigs have promised him a kite of his own. <PERSON> Andi </PERSON> herself plans to fly kites again, but not near airplanes.
