<HEAD>Prime Minister Heads For Washington; Keeps Eye On Manitoba
Election</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Money figures are in U.S. dollars.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<HEAD>By JEFF BRADLEY</HEAD>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When Prime Minister <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> visits <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for his summit with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, he'll be keeping an eye on the results of a provincial election back home. <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON>, who arrives in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> tonight, is trying to decide soon when to call a federal election. The choice of a new government today in <LOCATION> Manitoba </LOCATION>, a blue-collar industrial province in central <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, may show the way. <LOCATION> Manitoba </LOCATION> has been controlled by the socialist <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> for 15 of the past 19 years, but all polls indicate <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> will win the election, after narrowly losing to the socialists in 1986. <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> has 16 months to go in his five-year term, but it is traditional for Canadian leaders to set an early election date when political omens are favorable. In a weekend interview, <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> said he wanted to clear his government's legislative agenda before calling a ballot. That agenda includes ratification of a comprehensive Free Trade Agreement negotiated with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> last year, passage of the <ORGANIZATION> Meech </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lake </ORGANIZATION> constitutional accord recognizing <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> as a French-speaking `` distinct society,'' a child day care program and the privatization of <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canada </ORGANIZATION>. The FreeTrade Agreement will be discussed at the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> summit. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is expected vote on it this summer, while the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commons </ORGANIZATION> will consider legislation on the agreement next month. Recently, <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> has been making campaign-like stops around the country to test the political waters. His 48-hour <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> visit includes a host of photo opportunities including a 19-gun salute at the White House and separate meetings with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and leaders of both the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. On Wednesday afternoon, he is to address both houses of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. A former lawyer and corporate executive from <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON>, 49, has devoted much of his term to repairing Canada-U.S. relations strained under former <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> Prime Minister <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Trudeau </PERSON>. Despite <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s reluctance to clean up <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> smokestack emissions causing acid rain north of the border, he and <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> agree on key trade and defense issues. According to White House officials, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> spends more time talking with <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> on the telephone than any other world leader. Domestically, <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> has had a stormy time in office in spite of the 140-seat majority he won four years ago in the 282-member House of Commons. He has lost eight Cabinet members in scandals ranging from a defense minister who visited a German strip club to a transport minister tried for fraud. <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> has shepherded <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s economy to the fastest growth among major industrialized countries, with 4 percent inflation and unemployment at a 6 -LCB- - year low of 7.8 percent Now the Conservatives are now neck-and-neck in the polls with the Liberals and New Democrats. <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> nevertheless has a credibility problem and is liked by only about one-third of the electorate, according to polls. In contrast, <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Broadbent </PERSON> gets high marks as <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s most admired politician. <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> dubs his nemesis `` perfection personified.'' `` I do n't know if I'll ever close in on perfection,'' the prime minister said. `` But I do n't have to, to win an election.'' He said when the time comes, voters will not take a chance by electing what would be the country's first socialist government at a federal level. <PERSON> Broadbent </PERSON>'s vulnerable spot is his party's vow to pull <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> out of the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> alliance and to renegotiate the NORAD air defense pact with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> was a charter member of the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> and has 6,900 troops stationed in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> and <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> agreed in 1986 to renew the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aerospace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> pact for five years, protecting the continent against Soviet attack over the North Pole. The New Democrats would bring the troops home and cancel <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON>'s $ 6.5 billion plan to acquire <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s first fleet of nuclear-powered submarines. Aware of the unpopularity of its <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> pledge, the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> softened its stance this month by promising not to start the withdrawal in a first term. <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> ridiculed the change, saying Canadians would never support `` a policy that says we're going to pull out of our most sovereign undertaking with regard to national defense, but by the way, we're not going to do it right now.''
