<HEAD>Cuba Looking To Foreigners To Boost Economy</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TINA SUSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAVANA, Cuba (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In the heat of the <LOCATION> Havana </LOCATION> day, <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bodeguita </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> del </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medio </ORGANIZATION> resembles the steamy cantinas of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, with a bit of the Big Apple thrown in. Like <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Cadillac </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bar </ORGANIZATION>, the walls are covered with graffiti left by visitors who pack the cramped restaurant tucked along a side street of <LOCATION> Old </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Havana </LOCATION>. Like the cafes of <LOCATION> Tijuana </LOCATION>, a sweating chef stirs metal tubs of pork and beans, swatting at an occasional fly and wiping his brow with a dishcloth. But there's a difference. Here, above the din of clattering plates and the strum of the strolling guitarist, you're as apt to hear German, Italian, French and English being spoken as you are to hear Spanish. It's a sound the government loves to hear. With its <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> climate and calm beaches, <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, is a natural lure for tourists. Before the revolution, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> visitors plunked down millions of dollars in the cabarets and casinos of <LOCATION> Havana </LOCATION>. The casinos are closed now and tourists from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> vanished when relations soured between the two countries. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> tourists who spend money in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> are subject to prosecution under the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Trading with the Enemy Act. The communist island nation, largely dependent on Soviet aid and sugar exports, is making an all-out effort to bring in money from elsewhere. From the bustle of <LOCATION> Havana </LOCATION> to the serene beaches of <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, the government is putting up new hotels and renovating old ones in hopes of making tourism its No. 2 earner of hard currency, after sugar, by the year 2000. Numbers are hard to come by _ nobody at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tourism </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, Intur, would talk to an American reporter. But <PERSON> Intur </PERSON>'s vice president, <PERSON> Orosman </PERSON> <PERSON> Quintero </PERSON>, recently told Cuban reporters that in 1987, about 123,000 people from <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> visited <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>. That was an increase of 15 percent over 1986. According to the magazine <LOCATION> Bohemia </LOCATION>, Intur figures from 1986 indicate that 155,795 tourists visited <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, bringing in about $ 97.3 million. Before the revolution, tourism brought in about $ 400 million annually. The Canadian tourism season runs from December through the end of March. But a few could still be found lounging in the 85 degree sun last week at <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Maria </LOCATION> del Mar, a seaside resort 20 miles outside <LOCATION> Havana </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Adelaide </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Aloi </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> said they paid $ 1,000 each for two weeks in <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Maria </LOCATION>, including breakfast and dinner in their hotel and round-trip airfare. Like others interviewed, they praised beaches, weather, <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> hospitality and the feeling of security. `` <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s cheap, but you have to bargain your way through it,'' said <PERSON> Aloi </PERSON>. `` Here, there's nobody coming up to you on the street trying to sell things or get money.'' But they agreed with other tourists who complained about bad hotel food, the poor quality of consumer goods and hotel service that is not up to par with other vacation spots. At the high-rise <LOCATION> Havana </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Libre </LOCATION> in the capital, the plumbing was iffy and there was rarely hot water. It was n't unusual to wait 10 minutes for an elevator, and no one was there to offer assistance when the small refrigerator in one reporter's room started burning one night. `` I personally would n't come back because I like to shop, and there's nothing much to buy,'' said <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> McNulty </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>, interviewed at the <ORGANIZATION> Hotel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantico </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Maria </LOCATION>. `` But this is the place to come if you just want a nice, relaxing vacation.'' <PERSON> Intur </PERSON> says it is trying to improve things for tourists by renovating older hotels, such as the 30-year-old <ORGANIZATION> Havana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Libre </ORGANIZATION>, and putting up new ones in areas such as <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Maria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Varadero </LOCATION>, the island's most popular tourist spot. An airport is being built at <LOCATION> Varadero </LOCATION> so visitors wo n't have to drive the two hours north from <LOCATION> Havana </LOCATION>'s airport, and 10 more hotels are scheduled for completion by 1990. In the capital, 11 hotels are under some form of renovation, according to the Intur magazine Sol de <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>. The Sun Channel, the television station for tourists, offers news, movies and a morning aerobics program in English and Spanish. Last week's feature films included `` Love at First Bite,'' `` A Man and a Woman,'' and `` Sahara.'' <PERSON> Intur </PERSON> also is offering prizes to lure foreigners. Sol de <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> heralded the arrival of a <PERSON> Silvia </PERSON> <PERSON> Proehl </PERSON>, the 100,000 th West German to visit <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> over the past four years She won a free week in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> next year.
