<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> won the <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> presidential caucuses on Monday, overwhelming rival <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and capturing most of the state's 23 delegates to the Democratic National Convention. With 46 percent of the state's 75 legislative districts reporting, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> had 4,104 votes for 71 percent to <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s 1,080 or 19 percent, while 538 voters, or 9 percent, were uncommitted Based on these returns, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> would win 18 national convention delegates and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> would win five. The combined votes for Democrats <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> and <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> totaled 1 percent. The percentage of votes determines how many of the state's 23 delegates each candidate receives. The delegates will not be elected until the state convention in June. Complete statewide returns were not expected until early Tuesday from the balloting in separate caucus meetings held in nearly all of the state's 1,807 voting districts. Although a victory here would reap only a handful of delegates, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> aides said it would give the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor momentum heading into Tuesday's <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> primary. While Democrats declared their presidential preference, Republicans were attending their own caucus meetings to vote their preference for vice president and to say whether they want a western states regional primary similar to the South's Super Tuesday contests on March 8. Republicans had planned a non-binding presidential preference vote, but scrapped the idea after Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> virtually wrapped up the nomination. <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> will send 28 delegates to the Democratic national convention, including five `` super delegates'' chosen as a result of present or past party office. Three of the superdelegates _ national committeewoman <PERSON> Norma </PERSON> <PERSON> Matheson </PERSON>, Rep. <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Owens </PERSON> and state party chairman <PERSON> Randy </PERSON> <PERSON> Horiuchi </PERSON> _ have endorsed <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. The other two are uncommitted. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> also has the endorsement of <PERSON> Matheson </PERSON>'s husband, former Democratic Gov. <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Matheson </PERSON>. None of the candidates has visited <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> personally, but the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign has maintained the strongest presence with a full-time staff. Support for <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> is more difficult to gauge. Two es here are picking up momentum. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> will pick up some delegates,'' <PERSON> Horiuchi </PERSON> predicted. Traditionally between 8 percent and 12 percent of registered voters attend the <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> caucuses.
