<HEAD>Associated Press Holds Annual Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> will speed its <ORGANIZATION> DataStream </ORGANIZATION> news delivery service to about 9,000 words a minute and increase its domestic news staff to deal with what its president calls the `` the new world of news.'' The increase to 9,000 words a minute begins in June, and the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> also will offer new photo and graphic services, <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boccardi </PERSON> told publishers and newspaper editors Monday at the annual AP meeting. The news cooperative also will add 10 to 15 domestic news staffers in 1988 to better serve the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION>'s 1,423 newspaper members, he said. `` The bulk of these will go to our line bureaus, whose state and regional news coverage is so important to you,'' he told the members. `` With membership increasing as it has, the demands on our state bureaus are increasing. And we must meet those needs.'' The worldwide news cooperative is about to move from a speed of about 1,050 words a minute to about 9,000 on its <ORGANIZATION> DataStream </ORGANIZATION> and DataFeature wires. <ORGANIZATION> DataStream </ORGANIZATION> is the AP high-speed news wire. DataFeature is a separate service that delivers supplemental and syndicate copy to member newspapers throughout the system. For newspapers with systems that need slower speeds, the delivery can be reduced, but the higher capacity will avoid crowding that can slow the delivery of copy, much like traffic clogs a highway. `` We are raising the speed limit from 55 miles per hour to 440 miles per hour, and, if that were n't enough, we're widening the AP interstate from four lanes to eight,'' <PERSON> Boccardi </PERSON> said. A new AP electronic darkroom for large newspapers already is serving three members. In June the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> will unveil a PC-based electronic darkroom designed for smaller newspapers, <PERSON> Boccardi </PERSON> said. After the meeting, the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> held its annual luncheon with <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> billionaire <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> <PERSON> Perot </PERSON> as the keynote speaker. <PERSON> Perot </PERSON>, 57, is the founder of <ORGANIZATION> Electronic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> and financed the rescue of two of his employees who were held hostage in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> in 1978. The luncheon was held on the first day of the three-day 102nd Annual Convention of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspaper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. The financier and philanthropist told the more than 1,500 people at the luncheon that business leaders, not politicians, hold much of the blame for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>' declining status in the world. Since the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy depends on tax-paying workers, business leaders should work harder to create more jobs, <PERSON> Perot </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Perot </PERSON> said other countries, especially in the <LOCATION> Asia-Pacific </LOCATION> region, are outpacing the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in education, trade and technology. He said that before the federal government can cure the huge budget deficit, individual Americans must learn not to spend more than they earn. `` The greatest nation in the history of civilization has given up trying to live within its means,'' he said. `` We and not the elected officials are the dwarfs and the wimps.'' Before the luncheon, five <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> correspondents shared their experiences in a panel discussion called `` The World's Hotspots: A Firsthand View.'' Also at the meeting, <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Newhouse </PERSON> of The -LRB- <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION> -RRB- Star-Ledger, and <PERSON> Katherine </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fanning </PERSON> of The Christian Science Monitor were elected to the board of directors of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, and four incumbent directors were re-elected. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ottaway </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald-Record </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Middletown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Maynard </PERSON> of The Tribune of <LOCATION> Oakland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Burgess </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Madison </LOCATION>; and <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Heminger </PERSON> of The Courier in Findlay, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, were elected to new three-year terms on the board. Directors were elected from among 12 nominees at the AP annual meeting. <PERSON> Newhouse </PERSON> and Ms. Fanning were chosen to succeed retiring directors <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> McGee </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> W. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION> -RRB- Daily Mail and <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Marbut </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Corpus </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Christi </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> -RRB- Caller-Times, who had served the maximum of three three-year terms on the board. <PERSON> Newhouse </PERSON> is president of The Star-Ledger, and of <ORGANIZATION> Advance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Newhouse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. He is a director of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspaper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. Ms. Fanning is editor of the Monitor, published in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, and is immediate past president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspaper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Editors </ORGANIZATION>. The voting for directors was based on membership bonds held by the newspapers that make up the cooperative news agency. <PERSON> Heminger </PERSON> was re-elected to the board to represent a city of under 50,000 population. AP bylaws require that there be at least three directors representing newspapers published in cities of less than 50,000 population.
