<HEAD>AP Correspondents Discuss Covering the World's `Hotspots'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON STATON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 News coverage of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is more difficult now because there is more activity and thus more news to report, according to <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Putzel </PERSON>, The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> bureau chief in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. `` Now we cover dissident news conferences, official news conferences, and demonstrations,'' he said. `` We are getting a lot more information. `` For Soviet reporters, it's a whole new ballgame,'' <PERSON> Putzel </PERSON> said. `` They now have to firgure out what's expected of them and how far they can and want to go.'' <PERSON> Putzel </PERSON> and four other <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> correspondents and news executives discussed reporting conditions and press freedoms, among other topics, during a conversation with <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boccardi </PERSON> at The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> annual meeting here Monday. The press is one of the most distinct areas of liberalization in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Renfrew </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> chief of bureau in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>. `` The press is able to moderately criticize the government now,'' he said. `` There has been a change from direct intimidation to more subtle influence,'' he said. `` Current riots in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> have posed difficult problems for the Israeli government, which is a democracy and prides itself on being one,'' said <PERSON> Nick </PERSON> <PERSON> Tatro </PERSON>, the wire service's bureau chief in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>. The government has not used military censorship but has tried to close off stories by putting curfews on towns or declaring military areas closed, he said. <PERSON> Bryna </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> correspondent for the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION>, noted the reopening of <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prensa </ORGANIZATION>, a newspaper in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, last fall. `` La Prensa has published consistently since October except for a brief week at Easter when they ran out of newsprint,'' she said. `` It is a very strong opposition newspaper.'' <PERSON> Terence </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION>'s chief <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> correspondent, said he has the same difficulties in getting access to people he needs to talk with as the foreign correspondents do. `` We only have access to our own booth and to -LRB- White House Press Secretary -RRB- <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>'s office, where the door is usually closed,'' <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON> said. `` We ca n't get to the oval office, or -LRB- White House Chief of Staff -RRB- <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>'s office or the senior staff without an appointment,'' he said. `` It's almost impossible on a spot story to get a call through for comment,'' he said. `` We have better luck talking to people on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> because -LRB- the -RRB- White House staff briefs congressional leaders on major issues.''
