<HEAD>AIDS Issue Surfaces During Discussion On U.S. Bases In Philippines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Filipino negotiators today discussed AIDS and procedures for trying <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> troops in criminal cases. The discussion occurred during talks on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military bases which sources described as difficult and emotional. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> is debating a bill to ban nuclear weapons in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> and to prohibit nuclear-capable military ships from making port calls. The measure is directed at <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military bases. In another development, at least seven people were killed today on <LOCATION> Mactan </LOCATION> island during a gun battle between government troops and <ORGANIZATION> Scout </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rangers </ORGANIZATION> who deserted their unit. Three of the dead were <ORGANIZATION> Scout </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rangers </ORGANIZATION> and four were government soldiers, officials said. Radio stations said a civilian also died. Also today, officials said communist rebels were suspected in the killings of a police captain and an anti-communist vigilante in two separate attacks near the U.S.-run Clark Air Base. After their discussion today, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Filipino negotiators released a joint statement saying they had discussed `` the criminal jurisdiction issue'' and that the Philippine side presented its proposal on purchases of locally manufactured products `` and socio-economic issues.'' There was no elaboration, but sources familiar with the talks said the `` socio-economic issues'' referred to allegations that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops had brought the deadly AIDS virus into the country. The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the talks were `` difficult'' and `` emotional.'' At least 50 Filipino prostitutes have been found carrying the AIDS virus but none has developed symptoms of the disease, which is transmitted primarily through sexual intercourse or contaminated needles and blood products. Most of those found with the virus work in bars near the U.S.-run Clark Air Base and the Subic Bay naval base. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> authorities have promised not to transfer troops carrying the virus to the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. Filipino officials have suggested that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> finance health and rehabilitation programs for AIDS-infected prostitutes working near the bases. The current bases agreement exempts American servicemen from trial by Filipino courts if they allegedly commit crimes while on duty. Sources said Filipino negotiators believe <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> commanders issue duty certificates to their troops too freely in a bid to exempt them from trial by local courts. On April 5, the two sides began a periodic review of the 1947 agreement under which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> maintains six military bases in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. The outcome is expected to influence <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>'s decision whether to allow the bases to remain after their lease expires in 1991. But the talks are taking place amid growing calls for closing the bases, which many Filipinos see as a vestige of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> colonial rule. President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> has promised to honor the agreement but refuses to say whether she will support an extension. Under the new Filipino constitution, any extension must be approved by two-thirds of the 23-member <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, where opposition to the bases is strong. On Monday, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> began debate on a bill to ban nuclear weapons and nuclear-powered ships from the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials say about 40 percent of the warships that call at <LOCATION> Subic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> are nuclear powered. The bill's sponsors say it is directed at the American bases. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials refuse to say whether nuclear weapons are stored in the <LOCATION> Phillipines </LOCATION>. Officials said the battle between government troops and <ORGANIZATION> Scout </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rangers </ORGANIZATION> began when the rangers attacked a checkpoint set up to prevent them from moving from their hideout. About 30 members of the army's elite <ORGANIZATION> Scout </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rangers </ORGANIZATION> deserted in 1986 and moved to <LOCATION> Mactan </LOCATION>, a small island where <LOCATION> Cebu </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s international airport is located The renegade rangers, who the military claims have been involved in smuggling, formed a religious cult that forbids bathing and cutting hair. In the <ORGANIZATION> Clark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> incidents, police said two men armed with .45 - caliber pistols shot and killed <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Medina </PERSON>, 41, deputy police commander of <LOCATION> Mabalacat </LOCATION>, as he drove late Monday near the base. Hours later, a lone gunman killed <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Sabile </PERSON>, 48, while he played cards with friends in <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Sabile </PERSON> was a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Angelino </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Simbulan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brigade </ORGANIZATION>, an anti-communist vigilante group. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> <PERSON> Air </PERSON> <PERSON> Base </PERSON>, a sprawling military facility 50 miles north of <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>, straddles the towns of <LOCATION> Mabalacat </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. In October rebels killed three Americans and a Filipino of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> extraction in attacks outside the base.
