<TEXT>
 King Fahd of <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> today decided to sign an international treaty limiting the spread of nuclear arms, apparently responding to Israeli fears that the kingdom might arm its missiles with nuclear warheads. Information Minister <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Shaer </PERSON> said the decision was made during a Cabinet meeting in the <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> capital of <LOCATION> Riyahd </LOCATION> where other issues also were discussed, the official <ORGANIZATION> Saudi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> reported. It appeared the announcement was designed primarily to reassure the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> that <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> will not try to put nuclear warheads on CSS-2 intermediate-range missiles the kingdom acquired from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. King <PERSON> Fahd </PERSON> wrote President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> recently reportedly assuring him that the warheads on the surface-to-surface missiles are not nuclear. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> has alleged that the missiles constitute a threat to its safety and indicated it might deal a preemptive strike to destroy them. The news agency, monitored in <LOCATION> Bahrain </LOCATION>, said Prince <PERSON> Saud </PERSON> <PERSON> Faisal </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> foreign minister, recommended that the kingdom join the International Nuclear Weapons Non-proliferation Treaty. <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, the world's largest exporter of crude oil, was reported to have obtained from <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> an undisclosed number of CSS-2 missiles capable of reaching virtually any point in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, including <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. Western diplomatic sources have said that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, which arms its own CSS-2s with atomic warheads, has told <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> it will not export nuclear arms. The sources said the <LOCATION> Saudis </LOCATION> refused a request by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to inspect the missiles, which they said were deployed in the <LOCATION> Rub </LOCATION> <LOCATION> al-Khali </LOCATION> desert south of <LOCATION> Riyadh </LOCATION>. Saudi sources said <PERSON> Prince </PERSON> <PERSON> Sultan </PERSON>, the defense minister, approached <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> for the CSS-2s mainly because of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> congressional obstruction of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s approval of the sale of certain types of weapons to the kingdom. They complained that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has been bending to powerful Israeli lobbying against <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> arms sale to <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>. The Saudis feel threatened by <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, which in 1984 began using intermediate-range missiles against its <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> war foe, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. Saudi-Iranian relations hit their lowest point in July, when hundreds of Iranian pilgrims tried to defy a ban on political rallies and were killed in clashes with Saudi riot police in <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION> during the annual pilgrimage season. Gulf-based Arab diplomatic sources have said the Saudis want the CSS-2s as a potential deterrent to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, whose leadership has urged the overthrow of the <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> royal family. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> were the major signers when the nuclear non-proliferation treaty was adopted in 1968. In subsequent years the treaty was signed by scores of other nations. The treaty is aimed at restricting the spread of military nuclear technology. It calls for nuclear powers to abstain from assisting non-nuclear nations in obtaining or making nuclear weapons.
