<HEAD>Tokyo Stock Market Closes At Record High; Dollar Falls Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> stock market had a record high closing today for the third consecutive day, while the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar inched down against the Japanese yen. The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, the market's main index, reached the all time high of 27,339.14 points immediately after Tuesday's opening at 27,323.54. Then profit-taking thwarted the early morning rally causing share prices dip at the close of the morning session. Bullish sentiment in the market, however, drove the shares back up to the day's opening level immediately after the start of the afternoon session, and the market closed the day's trading at 27,246.77, or 33.32 points higher than Monday's close, another record high. `` It was a typical first-day-of-the-month pattern,'' said a trader for a Japanese securities firm, speaking on condition of anonymity. `` Major securities firms customerily push their sales on the first day of the month,'' he added. `` So share prices usually jump up in early morning and then profit-taking usually press it down a bit.'' Shares traded Tuesday will go into the May account. The trader added that the general trend is still upward, but investors took `` wait-and-see attitude'' Tuesday ahead of the release of gross national product figures in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for the first quarter of 1988. This made the recovery of share prices slower than usual. The American gross national product figures will be announced today in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Volume traded in the first section today was estimated at 1 billion shares. Meanwhile, the dollar opened at 124.65 yen in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> and closed at 124.57 yen, down 0.35 yen from Monday's close. It traded in a narrow range of 124.55 yen to 124.70 yen throughout the day. `` The dollar sold in the 125's Monday, so it went back to a comfortable level at around 124.60 yen. Now, it can not seem to be able to go anywhere from there unless some influencing factors emerge,'' said <PERSON> Hiroaki </PERSON> <PERSON> Shukuzawa </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Sumitomo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. `` At this point, 124.55 - 124.70 yen seems to be the neutral range.'' <PERSON> Shukuzawa </PERSON>, a currency dealer at one of the largest bank in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, added that he expects no major effects from the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> gross national product figures on exchange rates in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. `` GNP is not like a trade figure that has immediate effects on exchange rates,'' he said. `` Its effects show up in a much longer term.''
