<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 South Koreans expressed hope that today's legislative elections would help promote democracy, but many also said violent protests could result if widespread vote fraud occurs. `` A lot of problems have surfaced but from a long-term point of view, I think the elections would be a step forward toward democracy,'' <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Soon-im </PERSON>, 43, a housewife in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>, said. Many voters interviewed shared that view but expressed concern that `` widespread corruption'' would heighten political instability before the Olympic Games, opening Sept. 17 in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>. `` I am afraid the elections would cause new problems rather than solve them,'' <PERSON> Kang </PERSON> <PERSON> Han-ik </PERSON>, 21, a college student, said. <PERSON> Kang </PERSON> and many others predicted a flood of lawsuits disputing results of this election, which follows the first direct presidential election in 16 years. In the presidential voting in December, <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> <PERSON> Tae-woo </PERSON> of the governing <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> won with 36 percent of the vote. But opposition charges of rigging in that election won little support from the public, irritated by the opposition's inability to unite. Violence, corrupt campaigning and the alleged use of government influence to help governing party candidates became issues again in this campaign. Since the official 18-day campaign began, no day passed without reports of scuffles among rival party supporters, firebomb attacks on candidates or party offices and other violence. Scores were injured, although exact figures were not available, and 150 people were reported detained by police. Many people interviewed said they were most concerned by reports of widespread efforts to buy votes with meals, gifts and cash. The governing <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> announced it was expelling one candidate after authorities reported finding thousands of envelopes, each stuffed with the equivalent of $ 30 in cash, ready for mailing at a post office. `` I did not receive cash but got a case of soap,'' <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Chung-kil </PERSON>, 34, a taxidriver said. `` People say that only fools would not get gifts. In that sense, I am not a fool.'' A housewife in a relatively wealthy residential area in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> said it was difficult to reject offers of free lunches or dinners, made through personal friends associated with certain candidates. `` I had received at least 10 offers of free sumptuous meals. I have a guilty feeling for not voting for any of the candidates who provided the meals,'' she said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
