<HEAD>City Council Eases Anti-Ugly Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> has eased its `` anti-ugly'' law _ an ordinance aimed at eliminating suburban eyesores _ and will allow residents to air their dirty laundry in public, provided it's not in the front yard. The council on Monday scrapped some provisions of the new law and changed others, bowing to citizen complaints about the ordinance. Among other things, it altered the law to make it enforceable upon citizen complaint and not merely at the whim of someone in City Hall. Laundry still ca n't be aired in the front yard, but is permissible in side yards and on porches and balconies. The council in this <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> area community also eliminated its ban on garbage cans in side yards. The revised law contains most of its original provisions intended to rid neighborhoods of discarded furniture, automobile bodies and other unsightly junk. It bans graffiti, dirt piles, overgrown vegetation or other debris on residential and non-residential property, if such messes can be seen from the street. Violators face fines up to $ 500, and those convicted of breaking the law more than three times within a year could face both a fine and a jail sentence.
