^By BRYAN WILDER</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet forces are beginning to withdraw from eastern <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, where anti-communist guerrillas have taken several posts since the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> accord was signed, Western diplomatic sources said today. The sources, speaking in <LOCATION> Islamabad </LOCATION> on condition of anonymity, said the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> also has begun transporting wrecked vehicles back to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, apparently to prevent them from being salvaged by the insurgents. Under the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> agreement signed April 14, the estimated 115,000 Soviet troops are to start leaving <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> on May 15. Diplomats, quoting reports from their <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> missions, said evidence of the impending pullout is seen in heavy Soviet air traffic in and out of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> airport and the movement of massive Soviet convoys near the capital. One source quoted an unidentified Soviet diplomat in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> as saying Soviet troops are being `` consolidated'' in <LOCATION> Nangarhar </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Paktia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Paktika </LOCATION> provinces, all of which border <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s communist president, <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>, also offered on Monday to withdraw his own troops from posts near the <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> border. He told three small parties loyal to his government that creation of `` a non-military line'' was contingent on agreement with <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and the guerrillas. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, where the insurgents are based, is a conduit for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military aid to the guerrillas. It also houses 3 million refugees of the civil war. Soviet troops intervened in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in late 1979 when they replaced one Marxist