<HEAD>U.S., Soviet Publishers Sign Agreement For Computer Magazine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For two rubles, Soviet personal computer users soon will be able to access information probably beyond the capabilities of their present systems. In the first joint publishing venture between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, officials signed an agreement Monday to publish a Russian-language edition of a major personal computing magazine. `` No magazines of any kind in the <ORGANIZATION> USSR </ORGANIZATION> are based on the concept of a joint venture with another firm, for personal computers or anything else,'' <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Salnicov </PERSON>, director of Radio i <ORGANIZATION> Sviaz </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishers </ORGANIZATION>, said of the business agreement with <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. About 50,000 copies of PC World <ORGANIZATION> USSR </ORGANIZATION> will hit Soviet bookstores and newsstands in late June priced at two rubles, or $ 3.20 at the official exchange rate, said <ORGANIZATION> IDG </ORGANIZATION> president <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> <PERSON> Leblois </PERSON> The magazine will contain about one-third original copy written by a staff of seven Soviet editors and writers. Personal computing is in its infancy in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, which officials said has had trouble manufacturing computers. There are fewer than 100,000 personal computers in the country, but Soviet and <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> officials tout a potential market of 30 million. The liberalization of foreign investment laws, Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policy of glasnost and the recent easing of Western technology export laws are critical to the publication of the new magazine. <PERSON> Leblois </PERSON> said that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> high-tech export regulations were eased in January to allow 16-bit personal computers to be sold to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. He predicted that American, Western European and Japanese computer makers will rush to secure joint production agreements. In keeping with Soviet guidelines on joint ventures adopted in January 1987, the Soviet partner will own 51 percent of the project to <ORGANIZATION> IDG </ORGANIZATION>'s 49 percent. <PERSON> Salnicov </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Volodarsky </PERSON>, chief advisor to the chairman of Goskomizdat, the Soviet state committee on publishing, printing and book trade, signed the agreement at <ORGANIZATION> IDG </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in <LOCATION> Framingham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Leblois </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> IDG </ORGANIZATION> has invested $ 250,000 in the project but expects to recoup that almost immediately through advertising from Western computer makers seeking a foothold in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldman </PERSON>, associate director of the <ORGANIZATION> Russian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, said the principle problem with about 30 joint ventures between the Soviets and foreign companies to date has been the repatriation of hard currency. But <ORGANIZATION> IDG </ORGANIZATION> said PC World <ORGANIZATION> USSR </ORGANIZATION>'s sales will cover all production costs and that its revenues will come from advertising paid for in <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> currencies. Foreign firms typically have had problems getting ruble earnings out of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Salnicov </PERSON> said some foreign language computer journals are available in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> libraries but that Soviet PC users have no information about developments within the country. <ORGANIZATION> IDG </ORGANIZATION> publishes PC World, the second largest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> publication on personal computers with a monthly circulation of about 475,000.
