<SECOND>PM-Demjanjuk-US Reax,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>Family To Continue Fight To Clear Demjanjuk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON>'s family intends to continue its fight to vindicate the retired <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> autoworker who was sentenced to hang after an <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> court determined he was the <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> death-camp guard `` Ivan the Terrible.'' An Israeli panel of judges Monday sentenced <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON>, 68, to death. The three judges ruled a week ago that the former <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> autoworker was responsible for the deaths of thousands of Jews at the <LOCATION> Treblinka </LOCATION> concentration camp in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> during World War II. <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Nishnic </PERSON>, <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON>'s son-in-law, said <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON> `` has been railroaded through the <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> court system.'' <PERSON> Nishnic </PERSON> said the family still believes that <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON> is innocent and would `` fight all the way to the end.'' `` I spoke to Mr. <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON> yesterday. He believes half the world already knows he is not ` <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> the Terrible' and the rest of the world will learn it soon,'' <PERSON> Nishnic </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON> claimed a case of mistaken identity, but some concentration camp survivors identified <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON> as the prison guard who would beat Jews on the way to the gas chamber. The judges ruled that his alibi, that he was a prisoner of war who never was in <LOCATION> Treblinka </LOCATION>, did not stand up to scrutiny. In <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>, lawyer <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Horrigan </PERSON>, who as an assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney represented the government in <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON>'s 1981 denaturalization trial, said the death sentence came as no surprise. `` In the end, they, like every other court or tribunal who looked at the case, were left with little alternative but to find him guilty and impose the only sentence consistent with that finding,'' <PERSON> Horrigan </PERSON> said. `` His alibi was a joke.'' But members of <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>'s Ukrainian community still believed <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON>. `` It has been the unanimous opinion of this parish that <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON> is innocent. That has been the opinion since the beginning,'' said the Rev. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Nakonachny </PERSON>, a priest at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vladimir </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ukrainian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orthodox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, the <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON> family's parish. After the verdict, vandals painted purple circles on <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vladimir </LOCATION>'s, and Jewish organizations in <LOCATION> Akron </LOCATION>, about 40 miles south of <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>, asked for additional police protection because callers were threatening local Jews. Police said a priest at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vladimir </ORGANIZATION>'s told them the purple paint might signify blood on the church. In <LOCATION> Buffalo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON>'s former attorney said he does not think <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON> will be executed. `` The <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> people are the real jury,'' said <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>, who represented <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON> for five years during deportation proceedings and during the beginning of trial. `` While they have doubts I do n't see how the court can go through with it.'' <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> said he was fired last year because <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON>'s family thought he was being `` pro-Jewish'' by refraining from attacking witnesses and using the Talmud to make his points. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Plax </PERSON>, Cleveland-area director for the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jewish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said the sentencing represented `` a sense of relief and closure that the sort of behavior exhibited by ` <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> the Terrible' has been adjudicated. <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Dackiewicz </PERSON>, operating the <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Demjanjuk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION>, said donations to the fund had slackened recently, but calls picked up again Monday. `` The phone calls are from people who have been totally outraged at what happened over there,'' she said. `` They're people from all different backgrounds wanting to donate money and asking what they can do to help.''
