<SECOND>PM-Asbestos Fire,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Sweeps NATO Warehouse, Sending Asbestos Into The Air</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DONNINGTON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A fire at a <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> storage depot gave off a huge cloud of smoke that dusted nearby communities with dangerous asbestos, authorities said. Officials used bullhorns to warn people living just west of Monday's fire to stay inside and avoid stirring up the asbestos powder. The asbestos came from the roof of the burning 10-acre warehouse at the depot in <LOCATION> Donnington </LOCATION> in western <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. A team of 120 local workers put on masks and protective clothing to clean up the worst contaminated areas. Asbestos is a fibrous material used to fireproof and insulate. It has been linked to lung cancer and other diseases, and other building materials have increasingly replaced it. In dust form, asbestos can cause an often fatal lung disease called pneumoconiosis. The warehouse that caught fire is part of a <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> depot employing several thousand people. It is one of the Western defense alliance's biggest storage areas for technical equipment and spare parts for military vehicles. The army said the warehouse contained no ammunition. No cause of the fire was given. The 190 civilian and British army personnel working in the warehouse were evacuated, and there were no reports of injury. The <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> said damage was expected to run into millions of dollars.
