<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two Israeli soldiers and three Arab guerrillas died today in a predawn clash near the border with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, police reported. A police spokesman said the clash began at 3:30 a.m. near the southern village of <LOCATION> Kfar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Shouba </LOCATION> when <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> troops opened fire on a seven-man guerrilla group. The spokesman said the guerrillas were made up of two pro-Soviet groups _ the <ORGANIZATION> Lebanese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Popular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> of <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Habash </PERSON>. A `` fierce clash'' raged for about three hours, said the police spokesman, who can not be named in line with standing regulations. The Israelis `` fired flares at the rate of 20 every five minutes as their helicopter gunships chased the guerrillas in the region,'' he said. The police spokesman said the guerrillas `` apparently -LRB- were -RRB- ambushed before launching a cross-border raid into northern <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Kfar </PERSON> <PERSON> Chuba </PERSON> is a small village about one mile from the Israeli border on the slopes of biblical Mt. <PERSON> Hermon </PERSON> that towers over the region where the borders of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> converge. The village is inside <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s self-designated `` security zone'' that was established when <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> withdrew the bulk of its troops from <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> in 1985.
