<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former President <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> said today that a Democratic presidential ticket with <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> would be `` amazingly attractive'' and enable the party to carry the South. `` Six months ago, to be blunt about it, I would have said ` no','' <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> said on <ORGANIZATION> ABC-TV </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Good Morning America.'' `` But <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has fooled everyone.'' The former president said <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s `` attractiveness and the quality of his campaign has been amazing'' and `` it's much easier to say very honestly that <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> would be amazingly attractive on the ticket compared to what everybody thought he would do before this campaign started.'' <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> said he thought a ticket with <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> on it would win in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> and carry his home state of <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>. `` As you know, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> came in first in <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> as it was,'' he said. <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> did not specify whether he envisioned <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> in the presidential or vice presidential slot. <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, who will attend the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION> as a `` super delegate,'' has refused to endorse any of the party's candidates, but said if someone `` had to bet one way or another,'' <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> would be the most likely nominee Asked if <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> should be the party's vice presidential choice, <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> said it would be improper for him to presume that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> _ not <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> _ would win the nomination. He added that if <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> wins the nomination, `` <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has exhibited in the last year or so a remarkable element of substantiality and common sense and loyalty to the party and attractiveness to a wide range of people and I guess then, in the convention, that whatever happens, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s support will be constructive whether he's on the ticket or not.''
