<SECOND>PM-Worst Nukes,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nader Group Issues List of `Worst' Reactors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An anti-nuclear group's choices for the nation's worst nuclear power plants are largely identical to a list compiled by government regulators in 1986. The group, <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizen </ORGANIZATION>, on Monday named 16 plants as the nation's worst. Thirteen of those plants were also on the <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>'s list. Of the 16, <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizen </ORGANIZATION> named two as worst than the rest. Those plants were Pilgrim, near <LOCATION> Plymouth </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, operated by <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Edison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, and <LOCATION> Rancho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Seco </LOCATION> at <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, operated by the <ORGANIZATION> Sacramento </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Municipal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utility </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION>. Both were closed throughout 1987 at the insistence of the <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> to correct operational and management problems. Local authorities are discussing the sale of Rancho Seco, now operating at 30 percent of full power under recent restart approval granted by the commission, and <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION> voters will decide next month whether to keep it open. `` The similarity between Public Citizen's list and the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION>'s list strongly suggests that these plants are indeed the worst in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizen </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Critical Mass'' project said in its Monday report entitled `` Nuclear Lemons. Public Citizen is an advocacy organization founded by consumer activist <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Nader </PERSON>. Responding, the <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Awareness </ORGANIZATION>, a pro-nuclear trade group, said industry performance is improving, as shown by reductions in unplanned automatic shutdowns of reactors, radiation exposure and lost-time accidents. Spokesman <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Winston </PERSON> said the committee had not had a chance to study the Pulic Citizen report in detail. Public Citizen ranked the nation's 105 operating civilian nuclear power reactors according to 10 criteria such as downtime, operation and maintenance expense and exposure of the workforce to radiation. A reactor was awarded 15 points if it was the worst in a category, 14 if the second worst and so forth. Rankings were made by the number of `` 15 worst'' lists the reactor appeared on, with points used as a tiebreaker. The 16 plants named by Public Citizen are: <LOCATION> Rancho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Seco </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>; Pilgrim, <ORGANIZATION> Plymouth </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Mass </LOCATION>.; Peach Bottom No. 3, <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>; Peach Bottom No. 2, <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>; Fermi No. 2, <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Oyster </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Forked </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>; Sequoyah No. 1, <LOCATION> Chattanooga </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Browns </ORGANIZATION> Ferry No. 2, <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Browns </ORGANIZATION> Ferry No. 3, <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Browns </ORGANIZATION> Ferry No. 1, <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Davis-Besse </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Toledo </LOCATION>; Dresden No. 2, <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>; LaSalle No. 1, <LOCATION> Seneca </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vrain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>; Sequoyah No. 2, <LOCATION> Chattanooga </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, and Byron No. 1, <LOCATION> Rockford </LOCATION>, Ill. The Ranch Seco, Pilgrim, <ORGANIZATION> Sequoyah </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Browns </ORGANIZATION> Ferry plants were all closed throughout 1987. A similar list compiled by the <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> in 1986 originally included <LOCATION> Oyster </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> and the two Cook plant reactors at <LOCATION> Benton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich </LOCATION>. These three were deleted and replaced by the two Peach Bottom reactors. The commission also included the LaSalle No. 2 plant and the <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> Point No. 3 and No. 4 plants near <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, and did not include the Dresden No. 2 and Byron No. 1 plants that appeared on Public Citizen's list.
