<TEXT>
 Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, back from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, is reporting to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> on the slow progress in arms control negotiations with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Schultz </PERSON> was briefing <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> at mid-afternoon. Unless there is an unexpected breakthrough, or a shift in policy, a treaty to halve <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet strategic nuclear weapons is unlikely to be ready for <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and General Secretary <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> to sign when they meet in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> May 29 through June 2. The two sides are far apart on methods to verify cutbacks in mobile missiles and cruise missiles carried on fighter planes and warships. Another obstacle is <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s Strategic Defense Initiative. The Soviets are refusing to sign the treaty unless they have the right to suspend reductions if they conclude that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> anti-missile tests in space violate the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> was unable to bridge the differences in his talks in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> last week with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>. He will see <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> again May 11-12.
