<HEAD>Hail Damages Cars, But Tornado Passes Over</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thunderstorms peppered 10 <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> counties with hail the size of tennis balls, leaving thousands of car owners and car dealerships sizing up dents and cracked windshields. `` It looks horrible,'' <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> McGough </PERSON> said Monday as he surveyed the lot at Capitol Chevrolet in <LOCATION> Montgomery </LOCATION>. `` We've got close to 2,000 vehicles on our lot, and I would say 99 percent of them have some damage,'' <PERSON> McGough </PERSON> said. `` Hail is the worst thing that can happen to an automobile dealership because it dents all your vehicles up.'' <PERSON> McGough </PERSON> said one employee estimated damages at close to $ 500,000. Meanwhile, officials at the <ORGANIZATION> Alabama </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> were relieved that even worse damage was avoided as tornadoes swept across three counties without touching down. Tornado warnings, which mean a tornado has been spotted on radar, were issued in <LOCATION> Montgomery </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Macon </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> counties during the late afternoon. By 7:30 p.m., however, the warnings had been lifted. <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hearn </PERSON>, a spokesman at the Montgomery-based AEMC, said officials received numerous reports of heavy thunderstorms and hailstorms, but that there were no reports of a tornado touching down. In <LOCATION> Lee </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, an ambulance driver called emergency officials to report winds gusting so hard that he could n't control his vehicle. State troopers reported no fatalities or serious injuries related to the storms. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> <PERSON> Hilton </PERSON>, a meteorologist with the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, said the tornado warnings were issued after radar showed several funnel clouds moving toward <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON> at about 60 mph. `` It's like a tornado aloft, but not touching the ground,'' <ORGANIZATION> Hilton </ORGANIZATION> said. <ORGANIZATION> Hilton </ORGANIZATION> said hail from an inch and a half to three inches in diameter is often produced in such a storm. <PERSON> Hearn </PERSON> said the emergency office had heard several descriptions of the size of the hail. `` We've heard anything from tennis-ball sized up to baseball-sized.'' In <LOCATION> Eufaula </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Hearn </PERSON> said, officials reported `` pigeon egg-sized hail.'' `` I think somebody sits around and tries to think up this terminology,'' he said.
