<HEAD>Ruling Sets Dangerous Precedent, Says District Attorney</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS GEORGATOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Jurors who convicted former Mayor <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Hedgecock </PERSON> on perjury and conspiracy charges could be put on trial themselves under an appeals court ruling on jury tampering allegations, a dissenting judge said. Deputy Attorney General <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Foster </PERSON> said Monday he will appeal a ruling by the <ORGANIZATION> 4th </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeal </ORGANIZATION>, which ordered a lower court to hold an evidentiary hearing on jury misconduct and jury tampering allegations. Compelling former <PERSON> Hedgecock </PERSON> jurors to testify in the hearing could create a `` colossal discouragement'' towards jury duty among citizens, said <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Casey </PERSON>, spokesman for the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> district attorney. `` It used to be that jurors were protected from that. The law wanted to protect them from that kind of intimidation and harassment,'' <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> said. `` This certainly transcends the <PERSON> Hedgecock </PERSON> case and we're concerned about it.'' <PERSON> Foster </PERSON> said Monday's ruling was a dangerous precedent because the evidentiary hearing could expose jurors to subpoenas under new trial motions. `` Until now, it seemed fairly clear that you could not bring a juror -LRB- on subpoena -RRB- into a motion for a new trial in a criminal case,'' said <PERSON> Foster </PERSON>, who litigated the appeal for the district attorney's office. `` That's a change in the law and creates a conflict of authority amongst published cases.'' The dissenting judge in the 2-1 ruling agreed. Justice <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Butler </PERSON> said the decision `` authorizes a trial of jurors who return a guilty verdict in a criminal case.'' In the majority opinion, justices said the trial judge failed to properly consider jury misconduct complaints by <PERSON> Hedgecock </PERSON>, who resigned as a convicted felon on Dec. 10, 1985, two months after his conviction. However, the majority opinion added: `` In our view, the evidence fully supports the jury's conclusion that <PERSON> Hedgecock </PERSON> was part of a conspiracy to violate the disclosure requirements of the Political Reform Act and the local campaign finance laws.'' <PERSON> Hedgecock </PERSON>'s conviction stemmed from a campaign finance conspiracy and coverup attempt in which hundreds of thousands of dollars in illegal contributions went unreported on state-mandated disclosure forms. <PERSON> Hedgecock </PERSON>'s lawyer, <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Sevilla </PERSON>, alleged in his appeal that a bailiff made derogatory remarks within earshot of the sequestered jurors, telling one person the former mayor was guilty and that prosecutors would win the case `` hands down.'' The allegations against the bailiff were cited in affidavits by two jurors. The remaining 10 jurors and the bailiff denied the allegations. The justices rejected 23 other issues raised in <ORGANIZATION> Sevilla </ORGANIZATION>'s appeal. <PERSON> Hedgecock </PERSON>, who now works as a local radio talk show host, was convicted in October 1985 on one count of conspiracy and 12 counts of perjury in his second trial. His first trial ended in a mistrial when the jury hung 11-1 in favor of conviction. The charges stemmed from a plot to illegally finance his successful 1983 mayoral campaign with more than $ 350,000 from the now-defunct <ORGANIZATION> J. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> David </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co. investment firm. <PERSON> Hedgecock </PERSON> was sentenced to a year in jail and three years probation and fined $ 1,000, but has remained free pending his appeal. He is vacationing in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> this week.
