<HEAD>World Court Rules Against U.S. Attempt To Shut PLO Mission</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND DE LIGNY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The World Court today ruled against the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>' attempt to shut down the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>'s mission in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. The ruling implicitly condemned the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> move to close the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> mission to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> by supporting the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> position that the dispute must be submitted to independent arbitration. The ruling was the court's second decision against the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in two years. In 1986, the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION>'s judicial arm condemned as a violation of international law the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's support for the rebels fighting <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s Sandinista government. The World Court, officially known as the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION>, has no enforcement powers and depends on voluntary adherence to its rulings. The <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> office dispute emanates from <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> anti-terrorist legislation signed into law by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> last December. The legislation aims at closing the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>'s 14-year-old observer mission to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. The law classifies the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> as a `` terrorist organization,'' and bars it from operating on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> territory. The <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>'s information office in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> was closed down prior to the passage of the legislation. The attempt to shut down the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> Mission in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> has been condemned by all <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> member nations except the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, as well as by the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> administration. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> also opposed the law. Briefs on the case have been filed by the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government, as well as by <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Although their contents are confidential, the East German and Syrian briefs are widely considered to support the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> position. Because only sovereign states and <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> bodies are entitled to bring cases before the court, the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> was unable to plead its case before the 15-judge panel. At the request of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, Secretary General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> filed the court case March 9 in the form of a request for a legal opinion on whether the dispute is subject to arbitration. The so-called Headquarters Agreement, a 1947 pact between the <ORGANIZATION> Truman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION>, specifies that disputes are subject to arbitration by a three-member panel. Under that treaty, diplomats of <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> member nations and organizations with observer status are guaranteed the right to operate in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has rejected independent arbitration in the case as premature, noting the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> case is under review by a federal court in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. But in its submissions to the court, the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has also said that the anti-terrorist law calls for closing the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mission </ORGANIZATION> `` irrespective of any international legal obligations that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> may have under the Headquarters Agreement.'' The <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> was accorded permanent observer status at the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> in 1974 and has maintained an office in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> since then.
