<HEAD>Lawyer Says He Will Raise Bullet Issue In New Appeal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A bullet lodged in <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Rougeau </PERSON>'s buttocks since a robbery a decade ago is expected to surface again as an issue in attempts to keep <PERSON> Rougeau </PERSON> from being executed. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Monday refused to consider a death row appeal based on prosecutors' remarks about the bullet during <PERSON> Rougeau </PERSON>'s 1978 murder trial, but lawyer <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Thorpe </PERSON> says he will raise the issue again in a different form. <PERSON> Rougeau </PERSON> refused to let doctors remove the slug after the robbery and shooting death. Prosecutors told the jury trying him for capital murder in the death of Deputy Constable <PERSON> A.C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilkins </PERSON> that <PERSON> Rougeau </PERSON> probably feared the bullet would be identified as having come from the dead officer's gun. <PERSON> Thorpe </PERSON> contended in his appeal that state District Judge <PERSON> Jon </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON> violated the defendant's Fifth Amendment right against self-incrimination by permitting the remarks. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> declined to hear those arguments, but <PERSON> Thorpe </PERSON> said he will file a new appeal claiming that the mention of the bullet violated <PERSON> Rougeau </PERSON>'s Fourth Amendment right against unreasonable search and seizure. A 1985 <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling held that suspects have a constitutional right to refuse to have a bullet surgically removed, and in general, prosecutors `` may not use against you the fact that you invoked your constitutional rights,'' <PERSON> Thorpe </PERSON> said. He noted that prosecutors may not tell jurors that a defendant refused to talk to police. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has tried to strike a balance between protecting suspects against deeply intrusive acts such as forced surgery while still allowing police to get the evidence they need by such lesser measures as taking fingerprints or samples of hair, blood or skin, all of which are permitted, <PERSON> Thorpe </PERSON> said. But state Assistant Attorney General <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Walt </PERSON> said federal courts generally will not rehear cases in which appeal is based on search and seizure issues that the defense has had a previous opportunity to raise. <PERSON> Wilkins </PERSON> was working as a security guard at <ORGANIZATION> Houston </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> Jan. 6, 1978, when it was held up by three men. <PERSON> Rougeau </PERSON>'s brother <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON>, 30, was killed in a shoot-out with police. The third man, <PERSON> Gillis </PERSON> <PERSON> Guillory </PERSON>, 27, later pleaded guilty to murder and testified against <PERSON> Rougeau </PERSON> in return for a 40-year sentence. <PERSON> Guillory </PERSON> testified he saw <PERSON> Rougeau </PERSON> standing over <PERSON> Wilkins </PERSON>. `` The officer asked <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> not to shoot him again,'' <PERSON> Guillory </PERSON> said, but <PERSON> Rougeau </PERSON> replied, `` Die like you should'' and pulled the trigger again.
