<HEAD>European Papers Comment on Demjanjuk Death Sentence</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Demjanjuk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s leading newspapers on Tuesday appealed to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to spare the life of <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON>, sentenced to hang for war crimes committed as concentration camp guard `` Ivan the Terrible.'' But two Swiss papers took the opposite line, saying the sentence was justified given the thousands of Jewish deaths ascribed to <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON>. Some European papers highlighted the cheers and singing that broke out in the public gallery when the judges announced the sentence. `` Singing and insults greet <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON> death sentence,'' headlined the Independent in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. Its competitor, The Times, said: `` Cheers and dancing at end of ` Ivan' trial.'' The conservative Times editorialized that the death penalty `` arouses misgivings,'' but said that since `` the sentence appeared to be little more than a formality, it is to the credit of the judges that they deliberated for three hours before pronouncing sentence.'' It added: `` If the <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> authorities could see their way to commuting the death sentence, this would further mark the emergence of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> as the civilized state it aspires to be. There could be few more appropriate ways in which <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> could mark the 40th anniversary of its foundation.'' The conservative <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> commented that in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> `` the trials of war criminals assist an explicitly political and propagandist purpose: to remind the world until the end of time of the nature of the Holocaust, and what was done to the Jewish people.'' It added: `` Yet even for <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, in this 40th year of its existence, there must come a moment when it is time to look forward; not to forget the Holocaust, but to cauterize its terrible wounds.'' The Telegraph said: `` If <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> is convinced of his guilt then let him rot in his cell.'' But it claimed the evidence against <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON> was flawed, and executing him `` could conceivably do as much harm to the Jewish nation today as ` <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> the Terrible' did to individual Jews.'' In <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, the independent <PERSON> Basler </PERSON> <PERSON> Zeitung </PERSON> commented: `` Given the atrocities he has been convicted of, the sentence is of secondary importance. No punishment can render justice in his case.'' The conservative <PERSON> Neue </PERSON> <PERSON> Zurcher </PERSON> <PERSON> Zeitung </PERSON> agreed, saying: `` One could argue that it would be wiser to sentence a person, whose identity is only 99 percent sure, to life imprisonment instead of to death. But there is no third between guilt and innocence ... and the crimes committed ... justify the sentence imposed according to Israeli law.'' <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Emmerlich </PERSON>, a legal expert with <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s opposition <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, told the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Anzeiger </ORGANIZATION> newspaper in <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION> that his party condemns the death penalty in general, including in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. `` There is always the possibility of a mistake, and there is no way to correct such a mistake when the death penalty has been carried out.'' In the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, Rabbi <PERSON> Avraham </PERSON> <PERSON> Soetendorp </PERSON> said he welcomed the death sentence as a symbol but did not want it carried out. `` I face a certain conflict of conscience because I am opposed to capital punishment,'' he told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Soetendorp </PERSON>, a prominent Dutch lobbyist for Jewish causes, said <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON> should be jailed for life. `` It's a good thing the trial's finally over ... and that it's become clear that he -LRB- <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON> -RRB- really is <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> the </PERSON> <PERSON> Terrible </PERSON>,'' he said Reporting from <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> for <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Figaro </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Rene </PERSON> <PERSON> Bauduc </PERSON> wrote that if <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON> lost his appeal to the <ORGANIZATION> Israeli </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, he would hang, `` carrying away with him the memory of the horrors of an epoch, but also the doubts of all those who, looking at this man of peaceful appearance, have difficulty believing he could have committed such crimes.''
