<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> swept to an easy victory over <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> in the <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> presidential caucuses, preparing for today's delegate-rich <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> primary by collecting a large majority of <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>'s 23 Democratic delegates. Unofficial results with 94 percent of the vote counted in Monday night's caucuses showed <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> with 7,550 votes, or 71 percent, compared with 1,682, or 16 percent, for <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. Some 1,231 voters, or 11 percent, were uncommitted. Those percentages would leave <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> with 19 <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> delegates to the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> with four. `` We're really happy,'' said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> state campaign coordinator <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Knoblock </PERSON>. `` It's a long way from home to be winning by this kind of margin. We've been slowly climbing in the West, but this took a quantum leap.'' Complete statewide returns were not expected until late today. Campaign aides touted the victory as another sign that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> had momentum going into today's <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> primary, where 178 delegates are at stake and the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor has been heavily favored in polls. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> supporters, meanwhile, said they were pleased to have come away with any delegates from a state where 93 percent of the population is white and less than 1 percent is black. A candidate must get at least 15 percent of the vote to qualify for a share of the delegates. `` The votes that came in for <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> were certainly not all-inclusive minority votes. I feel very good about what we've done,'' said <PERSON> Jackson </PERS