<HEAD>Dukakis Leads in Ohio and Indiana; Jackson Counts on District of
Columbia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALE LEACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Democratic presidential candidates have left behind <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> but the big industry problems that plague that state follow the campaign into the next round of primaries in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>. Front-runner <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> held solid leads over <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> in polls of voter sentiment leading up to next Tuesday's primaries in those Midwestern states. However, the <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> forces were hoping their candidate would be helped in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> by the efforts of <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Austin </PERSON>, his campaign manager who helped steer the successful campaigns of Gov. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Celeste </PERSON> in 1982 and 1986. The District of <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> also holds its primary next Tuesday, and Mayor <PERSON> Marion </PERSON> <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> predicts <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> could win as much as 70 percent of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> vote in the city that gave <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> one of his few 1984 victories. In <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> were expected to keep hitting hard at such issues as plant closings and a need for government to help create new jobs. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s first appearance in the state was at a steel plant. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, already well ahead of <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> in the delegate count, could add to the increasing sense of inevitability about his nomination if he could win the lion's share of the 159 Democratic delegates at stake in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and the 79 in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>. But <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was beginning a full week of campaigning in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> on Tuesday, and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' aides were speaking as if they were taking nothing for granted. `` We've got a tough job cut out for us in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Drake </PERSON>, director of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> campaign. `` I do n't think there is any way to possibly downplay the effect that <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Austin </PERSON> will have on <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>'s primary.'' <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, a <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> spokeswoman, agreed, saying, `` It's certainly an asset for us because of <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON>'s visibility here in the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> area and his track record with past <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> campaigns. Still, state Rep. <PERSON> C.J </PERSON>. <PERSON> McLin </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Dayton </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> campaign chairman, said, `` I'm not fooling myself. It's going to be difficult. But I still think we have a chance.'' A Gallup Poll conducted April 8-10 showed <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> leading <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, 50 percent to 23 percent. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> also holds a comfortable lead in most recent polls in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>. An <ORGANIZATION> Indianapolis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> survey taken April 17-19 showed him favored by 49 percent to 21 percent for <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> Democratic leaders have generally taken no stands on the race _ unlike four years ago when most endorsed <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON>, only to see <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> win a narrow victory in the primary. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' name will appear on ballots throughout <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. But <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> failed to qualify delegate slates in three of the state's 21 congressional districts: two largely rural districts with few black voters and a district west of <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> Although Democrats hold both <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> seats and virtually every statewide office in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, the state has been friendly territory for <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. In 1984, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> won the state with 59 percent of the vote. <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Asher </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> political science professor, said, `` I think two major things the candidates need to keep in mind are that the state really has eight major media markets. It is a difficult state to campaign in because there is no single dominant area. `` I think the other thing that really is new to the Democrats is that it finally is down to a two-person contest. ... That means, then, that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> are campaigning against each other.'' In the Republican primary, 88 delegates are up for grabs in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and 30 in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, most of them expected to move into Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s column as he smoothly sails toward the GOP convention. In the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, 11 delegates will be directly chosen in the Democratic primary, a contest that <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has virtually nailed down in the heavily black city.
