<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The brother of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> serviceman who died eight years ago in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> in a mission to rescue 52 American hostages remembered the failed attempt with pride, not pain. `` Time is a great healer of pain,'' <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Capt. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON> said Monday at a ceremony honoring the eight men who died in the Iranian desert during the abortive rescue mission on April 25, 1980. `` Those feeling of sorrow have been replaced with feelings of pride,'' said <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON>, the brother of Cpl. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> of Pine Bluff, Ark. The eight died when a helicopter collided with a transport plane after officials decided to abandon the mission before entering <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>. The hostages were freed in January 1981 after 444 days in captivity. Army Secretary <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Marsh </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, former hostages <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Laingen </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Col. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Roeder </PERSON> were among those attending the 30-minute ceremony, held at <ORGANIZATION> Arlington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cemetery </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A congressional watchdog agency says the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> has provided billions of dollars worth of parts and supplies to defense contractors without adequate control over how the material is used. The General Accounting Office, in a report issued Monday, estimated <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> contractors were given more than $ 6 billion in `` government furnished material'' during 1986, the most recent year for which complete statistics are available. That material covers an enormous range of items, from major parts for airplanes and other equipment down to such items as brooms, paint and bolts. Normally, the materials are supposed to be provided by contractors, but the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> has the option of supplying the materials when it is in the government's best interest. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said the service should tighten up its administrative procedures to avoid the problem.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Seven years after it was signed as a teaty, a bill providing for the prompt return of children abducted from a parent and taken to another country has won final approval by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>. The measure, approved on Monday by voice vote, would implement an international treaty on child abduction that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> signed in 1981 and the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> approved five years later. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, which had passed an almost identical bill March 28, approved on Monday a slightly different <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> version giving jurisdiction over international child abduction cases to both state and federal courts. The measure is intended to remove difficult, time-consuming legal issues involved in returning children abducted to another country, often by the other parent, or helping foreign parents recover children wrongfully taken to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Baby Swing Replacements Being Offered</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The manufacturer of baby swings that could collapse is offering free replacements. Involved are 6,562 wooden baby swings sold under the <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Hedstrom </ORGANIZATION> brand names. They were manufactured by <ORGANIZATION> Hedstrom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Bedford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, between April and December 1987, the <ORGANIZATION> Consumer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Product </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> announced Monday. According to the agency, four incidents have been reported in which the swings collapsed because the glue failed to hold the joints between the slats and frame. The models being replaced are <ORGANIZATION> Hedstrom </ORGANIZATION> brand 4-798 and <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> brand 512.70907, the commission said. Consumers should stop using the swing and return it to the place of purchase for replacement. Those needing more information can call <ORGANIZATION> Hedstrom </ORGANIZATION> at 1-800-233-3271. <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> residents should call 1-800-424-9034.
