<HEAD>U.S. Protests Proposed Philippine Anti-Nuclear Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has expressed concern to the <LOCATION> Philippine </LOCATION> government and its congress regarding proposed legislation that would ban nuclear weapons in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. The legislation, on which debate began in <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> this week, would prohibit nuclear weapons at the two major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military bases in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> and would ban port calls by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warships and planes carrying such arms. <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had told the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> that the bill `` would permit no flexibility on nuclear matters and would be incompatible'' with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy. That policy prohibits the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> from revealing whether its ships and planes are carrying nuclear weapons. <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> declined to further discuss the <LOCATION> Philippine </LOCATION> legislation, saying it was still in its early stages. The bill is expected to pass the 23-member <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, but would face strong opposition in the 200-member lower house. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has expressed strong opposition to such bans in other countries. It expelled <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> from a <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> defense alliance with <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> after <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> adopted a nuclear ban, and has protested similar action being considered in <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>.
