<BYLINE>By ARTHUR H. ROTSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Engineers today lifted a giant oven lid to check a mirror that astronomers hope will lead to the next generation of super telescopes, and the huge piece of cooling glass was pronounced `` just fine.'' `` I do n't know how nervous you are, but I'm certainly feeling it,'' <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Strittmatter </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steward </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Observatory </ORGANIZATION>, said Monday after engineers began spin-casting glass into what they hope will become a honeycombed 11-foot mirror, the largest ever to be made in that manner Colleague <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Angel </PERSON> is credited with the idea that he and other Steward astronomers hoped would bear fruit. The first 24 hours, during which the mirror actually is molded, are the most critical, <PERSON> Strittmatter </PERSON> said Monday. He said scientists were lifting the lid today to get a view of a `` red-hot product.'' <PERSON> Strittmatter </PERSON> said today the mirror apparently formed without any problems but that engineers and astronomers will have to wait the six weeks until they know for certain whether the mirror was successfully produced. `` So far, so good,'' <PERSON> Angel </PERSON> said. `` The trick is to get it from this temperature -LRB- about 1470 degrees Fahrenheit -RRB- down to room temperature in one piece.'' The mirror, a prototype for more powerful telescopes than now exist, is to be sited at the <ORGANIZATION> Astrophysical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consortium </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- ARC -RRB- telescope being built in the <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Sun </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Spot </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.M. </LOCATION> ARC is a joint project of five universities _ the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Princeton </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mexico </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>. `` The goal is obviously to make much bigger mirrors than we have ever been able to make before,'' <PERSON> Strittmatter </PERSON> said. Traditional big mirrors have weighed four to five times more than the two tons the finished 11-foot mirror will be, and have required as many as two or three years to grind and polish, he said. In addition, they are slow to adjust to outside air temperature, making for blurred images, and require large support structures and buildings to house them, he said. The new technology offers many advantages, Angel and <PERSON> Strittmatter </PERSON> said. Combined with a new technique for polishing the glass blank with a more deeply curved surface, the mirror being cast and those to follow will have short focal lengths resulting in great cost savings through smaller buildings for the telescopes, they added. Domed telescopes thus could become a thing of the past, said <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> York </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Strittmatter </PERSON> said the advances have spurred renewed worldwide interest in astronomical research, with several new major telescopes planned, including a binocular-like telescope with twin 26-foot mirrors called the Columbus Project that would be the world's most powerful telescope. Collaborators include Italian astronomers, the universities of <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. Mirrors of 26 feet in diameter are considered the current limit, given atmospheric distortion, <PERSON> Strittmatter </PERSON> said. The honeycombed understructure, which makes for lightweight yet rigid construction, helps minimize the distortion, he said. Thermal temperatures of the mirror can be controlled much more effectively than in conventional telescope mirrors, he said. In the <ORGANIZATION> Steward </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mirror </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lab </ORGANIZATION>, beneath the stands of the university's football stadium, the 19-foot furnace began spinning about 8 -LCB- times a minute once its temperature reached 705 degrees Celsius, or about 1,300 degrees Fahrenheit. The furnace began heating late Saturday. Lab workers cast a 4-foot mirror in November with the same spinning furnace.
