<HEAD>Museum Visitor Points Out Error In Remington Work</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The bronze cowboy sculpture `` The Rattlesnake'' by famed Western artist <PERSON> Frederic </PERSON> <PERSON> Remington </PERSON> stopped museum visitor <PERSON> Cy </PERSON> <PERSON> Baumgartner </PERSON> in his tracks _ the cowboy's tiny spurs were on upside down. `` There's no way a cowboy would wear his spurs pointing up like that,'' said <PERSON> Baumgartner </PERSON>, a former rodeo cowboy who now drives a beer truck and raises quarter horses. `` It would be totally out of character.'' <PERSON> Baumgartner </PERSON>, who was touring the Remington exhibit Sunday at the <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Louis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION>, apparently was the first to notice the error. `` I saw it immediately,'' he said. `` I just think it's funny that nobody noticed it before now.'' After <PERSON> Baumgartner </PERSON> pointed out the problem, museum workers checked other bronzes on display. They found that all the spurs on the four horsemen in a casting of `` Coming Through The Rye'' were also upside down. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hassrick </PERSON>, one of the curators of the exhibit, said he has occasionally noticed similar problems with <PERSON> Remington </PERSON> works in private collections. He said he had n't noticed the problem in the <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> exhibit. But that does n't necessarily mean that <PERSON> Remington </PERSON>, the famed sculptor and painter of Western themes who lived from 1861 to 1909, made the error. The spurs on the bronzes and other small pieces were cast separately from the main work and, as a result, it was sometimes left to a foundry worker with little knowledge of a cowboy's gear to attach the spurs to the boots. On other occasions, <PERSON> Hassrick </PERSON> said, the spurs may have been damaged and replacement spurs attached turned the wrong way. `` It's just a silly little thing, but I'm sure Remington wold have liked to have seen them the right way,'' <PERSON> Hassrick </PERSON> said. `` If they were on one of our bronzes, we'd turn them around,'' said <PERSON> Hassrick </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Buffalo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Historical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Cody </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wyo. </LOCATION>, and an authority on <PERSON> Remington </PERSON>. Neither of the works in question, however, is owned by the museum. `` The Rattlesnake'' casting is from a private collection, and the casting of `` Coming Through the Rye'' is on loan from <ORGANIZATION> Princeton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. The exhibit is open in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> through May 22.
