<FIRST>r a AM-SatellitesLaunch     04-26 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Satellites Launch,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Satellites Launched in Brilliant Display Reach Polar Orbit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VANDENBERG AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> navigational satellites that put on a spectacular light show after launch reached their planned circular polar orbit Tuesday, officials at this coastal base said. A <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> consultant at <LOCATION> Vandenberg </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Forney </PERSON>, said the launch aboard a Scout rocket Monday evening went `` by the numbers.'' <PERSON> Forney </PERSON> said solar panels that charge the batteries powering the satellite were deployed on one of the satellites shortly after it reached orbit. The spare satellite will be stored in orbit until needed. The functional satellite will be operational in 10 days. The OSCAR satellites, each weighing 131 pounds, are used as a navigational system for submarines and commercial shipping, as well as in oil and mineral deposit work. Their 6:57 p.m. launch left an exhaust contrail clearly visible from <LOCATION> Malibu </LOCATION>, about 100 miles to the south. The contrail was the result of a `` twilight phenomenon,'' said Master Sgt. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Zielsdorf </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Vandenberg </LOCATION> spokesman. `` It is the result of spent fuel from the booster rocket as it travels through the upper atmosphere. The fuel combines with water droplets that crystallize,'' he said. `` Those crystals are struck by high-altitude sunlight,'' he added. `` It may be dark on Earth, but there's still sunlight above. It causes an aurora borealis effect and is usually visible for 15 to 20 minutes.'' The contrail, which reflected shades of blue and green over <LOCATION> Orange </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, resembled a giant pretzel in that area after it was blown by high-altitude winds.
