<SECOND>AM-Denmark,0699</SECOND>
<HEAD>Danes Told to Choose Between Nuclear Ban and NATO</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY GERBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Political leaders are telling <PERSON> Danes </PERSON> to choose in upcoming elections between <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> allies and the country's longstanding ban on nuclear weapons. Prime Minister <PERSON> Poul </PERSON> <PERSON> Schlueter </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> backer, called the parliamentary elections for May 10, urging voters to `` take a stand'' in favor of the Western military alliance. The sudden storm over <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s role in the 16-nation alliance came as a surprise to many voters. The peacetime ban on nuclear weapons has been in effect for three decades, and a shaky coalition government has been struggling with economic, not military issues. Indeed, some voters say economic troubles remain the chief issue. `` It's not just a question about nuclear weapons but about the way the government runs society,'' said <PERSON> Susane </PERSON> <PERSON> Nielsen </PERSON>, a conservative voter who works in a health insurance office. `` We have to face these economic problems.'' The unexpected showdown began April 14 when the leftist opposition pushed through a parliamentary resolution intended to strengthen the country's ban on peacetime nuclear weapons. The move, which has been delayed pending the election, requires the government to notify individual warships of the country's ban. Parliamentary negotiators have not decided if the ships would then have to respond. Until now, <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> has simply stated its policy to one and all. Some allies reacted sharply to the latest proposal, warning it jeopardizes <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s participation in <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>. A meeting of <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>'s Nuclear Planning Group was rescheduled from <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> called off naval maneuvers in <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>. Some <PERSON> Danes </PERSON> have reacted with resentment to the foreign pressures. `` Has the <PERSON> Danes </PERSON>' national pride deteriorated so much that we will bow to pressure from abroad?'' the left-leaning newspaper Information asked in a front-page editorial. `` The question is the central one in the current debate, and in that sense, the election is the most important since World War II.'' Of course, it did not help matters when <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> joked to reporters that `` Danish means breakfast to me.'' National radio played the English-language tape on the air, an unusual step. `` Reagan Staff Demonstrates its Knowledge of <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>,'' said a sarcastic headline in the liberal Politiken newspaper. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> later apologized. The confrontation comes at a politically unstable time for this country of 5 million people. The last general election in September left <PERSON> Schlueter </PERSON>'s center-right coalition in command of just 70 of parliament's 179 votes _ just enough to command a majority on economic matters. Polls suggest that <PERSON> Danes </PERSON> favor <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> membership. A recently published poll by the Observa organization showed that 66 percent of <LOCATION> Danes </LOCATION> favor staying in <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> and just 16 percent oppose it, the most lopsided margin in years. A Gallup poll said <PERSON> Danes </PERSON> favor membership 59 percent to 16 percent. Another survey, published in the <LOCATION> Boersen </LOCATION> business newspaper, showed that 46 percent of <LOCATION> Danes </LOCATION> believed it was reasonable to ask <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> ships to guarantee they carry no nuclear arms, 36 percent did not and 18 percent were undecided. The responses crossed political lines. Further strains in relations between <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> and its allies could carry strategic implications. <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s low-lying peninsula and islands command approaches to the <LOCATION> Baltic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> strategists envision it as a key supply point in case of invasion from the east. The dispute follows years of contention over <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s declining defense spending, which amounts to 2 percent of its gross national product, among the lowest in the alliance. However, random interviews with window shoppers along <PERSON> Stroeget </PERSON>, a pedestrian street in <LOCATION> Copenhagen </LOCATION>, suggest many people are more worried about the country's weak economy than its military role. Unemployment is running at 9.7 percent, and the national debt has reached $ 43 billion. <PERSON> Joergen </PERSON> <PERSON> Thy </PERSON>, editor and writer for a computer magazine, said he planned to vote against the government because `` I do n't think they have achieved much.'' He calls the nuclear question `` a joke.'' `` That's not the issue,'' he says. Indeed, Danish elections have focused mainly on economic issues since World War II.
