<HEAD>Administration Asks High Court to Scrap Special Prosecutor Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration urged the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday to scrap a federal law used to prosecute several former <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> aides and to investigate Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>. The law gives too much power to people `` totally untethered to any politically responsible person,'' argued Solicitor General <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Fried </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s top courtroom lawyer. Disputed provisions in the Ethics in Government Act of 1978 allow independent counsels, formerly called special prosecutors, to investigate alleged misconduct by key executive-branch officials. Fried said such investigations should be conducted only by officials answerable to the president. Independent counsel <PERSON> Alexia </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON>, defending the law, said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> wanted to `` preclude the appearance or the reality of a conflict of interest'' arising from an administration investigating itself. The high court's decision, expected by July, could help define the nation's political life in future years. The decision also could affect the criminal convictions of former <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> aides <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Deaver </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON> and the Iran-Contra affair prosecutions of <ORGANIZATION> ex-White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> aides <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON> and <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON>. Ms. <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> is investigating allegations that <PERSON> Theodore </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Olson </PERSON>, a former assistant attorney general, lied to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1983 during a dispute over the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>'s cleanup program for toxic waste sites A federal appeals court ruled the independent counsel law is an unconstitutional encroachment on the president's power to enforce criminal laws. Fried urged the justices to uphold the appeals court ruling, saying the law `` strips the president of a purely executive function _ criminal prosecution.'' He said the law also wrongly `` absolves <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> of its weightiest and most painful duty'' _ serving as a watchdog for abuses of executive power. Fried said the proper remedy for such misconduct is impeachment by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Olson </PERSON>'s lawyer, <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, added that the law `` radically alters the structure of how we are governed.'' Joining Ms. <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> in defending the law during a 90-minute argument session was <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Davidson </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s chief lawyer. <PERSON> Davidson </PERSON> fielded questions from several justices who voiced concern about the law's empowering a special court, rather than the president or his subordinates, to appoint special prosecutors. He said such appointment power is a minor aspect of the law. Chief Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON> seemed less than convinced. `` You can not assign to one branch certain functions that inherently belong to the other,'' he said. But <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON> also asked <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, <PERSON> Olson </PERSON>'s lawyer, why the special-prosecutor provision was dissimilar from <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> routinely placing limits on a president's power to remove one of his executive-branch appointees. Justice <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> asked <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, `` Should n't a prosecutor be independent? What's wrong with it?'' The case is being decided by eight justices because Justice <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> has disqualified himself for unexplained reasons. His absence creates the possibility of a 4-4 tie, which would have the effect of automatically upholding the appeals court decision invalidating the law. Asked by reporters whether that possibility concerned her, Ms. <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> would not comment, saying only, `` I will anxiously await the court's ruling.'' <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said he did not expect an evenly divided court. `` I think a consensus will emerge, and I do n't expect a 4-4 split,'' he said. <PERSON> Deaver </PERSON> was convicted of perjury earlier this year for lying to a grand jury and a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee that investigated his lobbying activities. <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON>, <PERSON> North </PERSON> and two others were indicted in special prosecutor <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>'s investigation of the Iran-Contra affair. Independent counsel <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> McKay </PERSON>, who successfully prosecuted <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON> for illegal lobbying, also is investigating <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> in connection with possible financial conflicts of interest.
