<HEAD>San Francisco Rationing Plan Would Limit Use And Raise Rates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An emergency water rationing plan under consideration in the city would close down decorative public fountains and prohibit restaurants from giving water to customers unless they ask for it. The second phase of the proposal by the city's <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> would require each resident and business to pay a higher rate for less water by the end of May. The conservation plan, which will be considered Thursday by the <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utilities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, would begin Sunday. It would allow each home or business a water allocation based on a 25 percent reduction of the amount of water it used in 1987. Washing down sidewalks or patios with drinking water would be prohibited under the plan. Fountains, including those in Civic Center, <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plaza </ORGANIZATION> and the Villiancourt Fountain near the Ferry Building, would be shut off. Washing a car with a hose would be prohibited unless the hose has a shut-off valve. The increase, which has not yet been determined, would accompany penalties for using more water than the allocation. The city will also consider placing flow restrictors on water lines in homes or businesses that do not cut use. Water rationing is necessary because of two dry years in a row, water officials said. Last week's rains did little to increase runoff from melting snow in the <LOCATION> Tuolumne </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> watershed, where the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> area gets most of its drinking water. Runoff was 34 percent of normal as of Monday, officials said. <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> would be the second water system in the area to impose rationing. The <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bay </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Municipal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utility </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> last week adopted a flat daily allocation of 400 gallons for its 1.1 million customers.
