<HEAD>Poison-Laced Grapefruit Spurs Nationwide Seizure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Health officials on Tuesday began seizing all grapefruit on sale in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> after some pieces of fruit believed imported from <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> were found laced with a powerful poison. The <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> ordered the nationwide seizure of all grapefruit on sale and and in warehouses after health officials in the <LOCATION> Lazio </LOCATION> region, which includes <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>, reported that poisoned grapefruit was found in a <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> supermarket. Italian news media said the grapefruit apparently was imported from <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, but officials said they could not immediately confirm where the fruit originated. Last week, an organization that said it supported the Palestinian uprising in the Israeli-occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> claimed to have poisoned Israeli grapefruit on sale in <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION>. It called for a boycott of Israeli products. Laboratory checks at the time found no trace of poison. The claim was made by a caller to a <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> newspaper who said he was speaking on behalf of the `` Organization of Metropolitan Proletarians and Oppressed People,'' a group that was not known to have existed. Of the 12 grapefruit on sale at the <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> supermarket, six were found to have been injected by syringe with a bluish poison. The substance, which was not identified, was so powerful that it killed laboratory mice instantly. The <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rome </ORGANIZATION>'s poison center reported receiving calls from three <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> residents who said they had eaten grapefruit with blue marks on Monday or Tuesday. `` So far none of them has reported any ill effects,'' said Professor <PERSON> Enr