<HEAD>NATO Defense Chiefs to Meet on Nuclear Arms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT J. WIELAARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> defense ministers open a two-day conference Wednesday to keep their policies in line with superpower efforts to cut nuclear weapons. The meeting comes amid internal strains between much of the Western military alliance and <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>, which has moved to strengthen its longstanding ban on peacetime nuclear weapons. This week's talks were originally supposed to take place in <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>, but they were moved to <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION> in reaction to the Danish initiative. In addition, the ministers will grapple with West German fears about <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>'s plan to modernize short-range nuclear arms. The Germans think such a move could make them a more likely target for Soviet aggression. However, this week's <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> meeting is not likely to yield major decisions, alliance officials say. It is instead intended to review long-range nuclear arms planning. It will be the first defense ministers' session since the Dec. 8 signing of the U.S.-Soviet accord to eliminate two classes of ground-launched medium - and shorter-range nuclear missiles The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> is reviewing the treaty. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Defense Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> was expected to brief ministers at the meeting on preparations in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> for an elaborate, 13-year inspection system to check compliance with the treaty. However, ministers will likely discuss the whole range of arms control negotiations, said a <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> official who spoke on condition of anonymity. That would include reviewing superpower efforts to sign another accord to cut their strategic nuclear arms by 50 percent, or 6,000 on each side. Hopes have faded of completing such a treaty by May 29 when President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> meets <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. The defense ministers will review their long-term nuclear arms planning in light of the goals <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> has set for itself in recent years, said allied officials. <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> has 4,600 nuclear warheads in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, down 2,400 since 1983. The stockpile is at its lowest in 20 years, said one <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> official. The alliance is studying adjustments to its nuclear deterrent through modernization and redeployment of arms without raising the total number of warheads. The studies deal with developing a new short-range Lance ground-to-ground missile, a battlefield air-to-ground missile, and improved nuclear artillery shells. The issue of modernizing short-range nuclear arms, most of which are based in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, has also caused internal <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> friction. <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION> fears that as medium-range missiles disappear under the intermediate-range treaty, improved short-range arms would make its soil a greater target for Soviet attack. It prefers short-range nuclear arms talks in tandem with conventional talks, due to start in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> this fall. But its allies say the short-range arms must still be modernized by the mid-1990s. Ministers will also probably discuss <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s proposal to notify individual warships of its longstanding ban on nuclear weapons. <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> ministers have warned that such a move could threaten Danish participation in the alliance. The <PERSON> Danes </PERSON> will vote on a new parliament May 10 in what Prime Minister <PERSON> Poul </PERSON> <PERSON> Schlueter </PERSON> has called a referendum on <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>.
