<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government will put new visa procedures into place to make it faster and easier for foreign entrepreneurs, scientists and technicians to visit the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, an official said Tuesday. The streamlined rules beginning Sunday are part of broader reform of Soviet economic and foreign policy, <PERSON> Oleg </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Avramenko </PERSON>, first deputy chief of the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>'s consular directorate, told a news briefing. `` The new procedure for entry into this country reflects the logic of the course of Soviet foreign policy, which is oriented toward active development of economic, scientific and technical contacts with Western and developing countries,'' he said. Under leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, the Soviets have been wooing foreign investors, proposing joint projects with firms abroad and seeking to use Western capital and expertise to revitalize the state-run economy. For years, securing an entry visa to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has been a time-consuming affair, with delays that often stretched into months. Starting Sunday, however, it will be the practice of Soviet consulates abroad to issue visas within 48 hours to foreign business people, technicians and scientists who already have established contacts with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Avramenko </PERSON> said. He said foreigners would need an invitation from a Soviet firm or governmental agency in order to receive quickest attention. However, others who desire to explore economic or professional opportunities may still gain a visa at Soviet consulates within about five days, <PERSON> Avramenko </PERSON> There will also be a `` maximum broadening'' of the granting of multiple entry visas, documents valid for two or three years that allow bearers to enter and leave the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> as often as they want, the diplomat said.
