ncluding damage to bottoms of numerous pleasure boats, he said. Under state law, <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> could face $ 210,000 in fines _ $ 10 a gallon _ and more if the state attorney general's office files a successful lawsuit. `` The cleanup could continue for days to weeks,'' said <PERSON> Kolb </PERSON>. `` The damage may be there for years.'' <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fish </ORGANIZATION> and Game official <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> said about 200 soiled but living birds have been collected for treatment, and some 75 birds have been found dead. Biologists said the spill also threatened nests. The marshes are home to dozens of species of birds including egrets, avocets, grebes, sandpipers, ducks, herons, teals and the endangered clapper rail bird, as well as salt marsh harvest mice, tortoises, muskrats and otters.
