<HEAD>Ranks Reduced by 19,000 in March</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: FIXES spelling of accommodate in grafs 1 and 6</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The armed forces began slashing active-duty strength in March to accommodate budget cuts, paring almost 19,000 positions from the ranks during the month, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. As of March 31, the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> had 2,143,129 men and women on active duty, down 18,727 from the 2,161,856 reported Feb. 29 and 25,051 below the March 31, 1987, total. All four services reported declines in personnel during March, although the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s drop was relatively minor, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> reported 594,660 personnel on active duty at the end of March, down 8,939 from Feb. 29. The <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> set its strength at 768,211 as of March 31, down 8,202 from February. And the <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> reported 197,127 on active duty, 1,104 less than in February. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>, meantime, reported a decline of 482 men and women in March to 583,131. <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> has ordered a cut of active-duty slots to accommodate spending levels set for fiscal 1989, which begins Oct. 1. He has told <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> he would rather maintain a smaller force that is properly equipped and ready to fight than a larger, but `` hollow,'' force. As a result of that decision, the services must lower their manpower levels to a combined 2,138,327 _ or 35,890 below the total reported at the end of fiscal 1987 last Sept. 30.
