<HEAD>Panel Says Chambers' Farm Should Not Become Historic Landmark</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> farm where the `` pumpkin papers'' that led to the perjury conviction of <PERSON> Alger </PERSON> <PERSON> Hiss </PERSON> were hidden should not be designated as a national historic landmark, an advisory panel said Tuesday. It was the <PERSON> Hiss </PERSON> case in 1948 that vaulted a fairly obscure young congressman named <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> to fame. The recommendation of the <ORGANIZATION> Advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> could be overruled, <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesmen said. The board, meeting in Harpers Ferry, <LOCATION> W. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, made the recommendation on the grounds that 50 years have not elapsed since the events that gave the site significance, said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Berklacy </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> The principal significant event was the retrieval of microfilm from a hollowed-out pumpkin for <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>, then a member of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Un-American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Activities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, by the owner of the farm, a <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> magazine </ORGANIZATION> editor named <PERSON> Whittaker </PERSON> <PERSON> Chambers </PERSON>. Chambers had accused <PERSON> Hiss </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official, of being a fellow member of a communist spy ring. <PERSON> Hiss </PERSON> sued Chambers for libel, but <PERSON> Chambers </PERSON>' production of the filmed <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> documents he said <PERSON> Hiss </PERSON> had given him in 1938 led to <PERSON> Hiss </PERSON>' conviction for perjury for denying to the committee that he had handed over the documents. The park service generally follows a policy of letting a 50-year interval lapse to make sure history has gained enough perspective on events for fair designation of landmarks, <PERSON> Berklacy </PERSON> said. `` It is not a hard and fast rule,'' he said. The secretary of the interior, who makes such designations, has the final say and may overrule the board, <PERSON> Berklacy </PERSON> noted. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Prosperi </PERSON>, spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON>, hinted strongly that <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON> might do just that. It was <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON> who nominated the 390-acre farm at <LOCATION> Westminster </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, some 30 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>, now owned by Chambers' son <PERSON> John </PERSON> `` We're checking into the precedents,'' <PERSON> Prosperi </PERSON> said, adding, `` The secretary has n't pushed it this hard and this far just to leave it here.'' Chambers' testimony before the committee and his 1952 autobiography, `` Witness,'' strongly influenced a generation of conservatives, among them President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, who awarded a posthumous Medal of Freedom to Chambers in 1984. The case was a watershed in American life, with many people becoming convinced by it that communists had targeted American life and institutions for damage, if not for takeovers, and others refusing to concede either a threat from communism or the guilt of <PERSON> Hiss </PERSON>. <PERSON> Hiss </PERSON>, who lives in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, served 44 months in prison. He maintains his innocence. Chambers died in 1961. Designation as a landmark carries no obligation and no reward other than a plaque. Some 1,800 sites nationwide have been made landmarks.
</TEXT>
