<HEAD>UN Says Chemical Warfare Increasing in Iran-Iraq Conflict</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Chemical warfare is being waged on larger scale than ever in the Iran-Iraq war, according to a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> report released Tuesday. The report does not say who has been using the outlawed weapons. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> have accused each other of launching chemical warfare attacks in the 7 -LCB- - year-old war The report could prove a disappointment to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, which has been urging the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> to condemn <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> for practicing chemical warfare. Investigations in past years confirmed that <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> used chemical weapons. In releasing the 26-page report, Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> expressed his `` deep sense of dismay and foreboding at the mission's conclusions that chemical weapons continue to be used in the conflict ... and that their use in recent days has evidently been on an even more intensive scale than before.'' <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> experts examined victims in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and concluded most were suffering from exposure to mustard gas, a World War I-era agent. A few had been exposed to a nerve gas, the experts said. The team said they examined 39 Iraqi victims, all military personnel, and 66 Iranians, both soldiers and civilians. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> claims Iraqi victims were exposed to poisonous gases used by <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> on enemy troops. Dr. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Dominguez </PERSON>, the head of the team, said `` the use of yperite -LRB- mustard gas -RRB- was unmistakably confirmed.'' <PERSON> Dominguez </PERSON> is a colonel in the <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> army who specializes in nuclear, biological and chemical weapons injuries. Even though the report did not lay blame, <LOCATION