<HEAD>Committee Sends Aviation Liability Bill to Senate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> committee on Tuesday approved a measure sought by the small aircraft industry that would place limits on accident liability. The measure, which was approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on a voice vote, would establish a series of federal standards for determining liability in an accident involving aircraft seating less than 20 people and that are not flying scheduled passenger routes. The measure would replace what industry officials and private plane owners complain is a hodge-podge of conflicting state laws. Manufacturers argue that their insurance costs have multiplied by 500 percent since 1981. As a result of that increase and rising court judgments, the number of private planes produced in this country has declined from a record 17,000 in 1979 to 1,085 last year, the industry says. The bill would place no limit on the amount of money a victim could recover in damages. But in perhaps its most controversial provision, it would prohibit accident victims from obtaining damages in most cases in which the aircraft was more than 20 years old. Consumer groups and trial lawyers have opposed the legislation, contending it would make it too difficult for victims to collect damages and thus eliminate an incentive that manufacturers have to make the aircraft safe. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> aviation subcommittee approved a similar bill March 3 that would limit manufacturers' liability to aircraft 12 years old or less. But the measure faces bleak prospects in that chamber because three full committees _ <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Works </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> _ must complete work on the legislation before it reaches the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> panel sent the bill to the full chamber, with Sen. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Packwood </PERSON> objecting. The Oregon Republican complained that the measure would make it too difficult for passengers aboard aircraft involved in accidents to prove the plane was defective. The measure is sponsored by Sen. <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Kassebaum </PERSON>, R-Kan., whose state is home to <ORGANIZATION> Cessna </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Beech </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and other private plane builders
