<HEAD>Two Fugitives Arrested As Result Of TV Shows Not Yet Broadcast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Rival television shows about wanted fugitives have led indirectly to the arrests of one man on <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> embezzlement charges and another on <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> rape-murder charges, and both were ordered held without bond Tuesday. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stark </PERSON>, 40, was arraigned Tuesday in <LOCATION> Ann </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arbor </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, for being a fugitive from justice. He refused to waive extradition to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> officials said they will seek the death penalty on rape and murder charges. <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Riley </PERSON> <PERSON> Hadley </PERSON>, who had been living in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> for three years under the name <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Finley </PERSON>, is charged with embezzling $ 1.1 million in 1983 from the <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deere </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employees </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Waterloo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, where he worked. He appeared before a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> magistrate in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. Asked by <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> police if he was <PERSON> Hadley </PERSON>, `` he answered, ` Yes, I am.' There was a big sigh of relief and then he said, ` I'll cooperate fully however I can,''' said Police Lt. <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> in the <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> suburb of <LOCATION> Friendswood </LOCATION> Both men were arrested Monday, when television programs featuring them had not yet been broadcast. Stark's photograph appeared on television in <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Arbor </PERSON> for 15 seconds Sunday night on a promotion for the April 30 broadcast of <ORGANIZATION> Fox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION>'s `` <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s Most Wanted.'' Five people called police and said they recognized him. <PERSON> Hadley </PERSON> was scheduled to be featured in <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Unsolved Mysteries'' on May 6. The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> said it sent out wanted posters on him to aid authorities in anticipation of public tips and inquiries generated by the program. A copy was seen by <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>, who had had his eye on the free-spending <PERSON> Hadley </PERSON> for some time. `` There was no doubt in my mind it was him when I saw the flier,'' <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> said. `` I was shocked. I probably have 600 pages of reports on this guy from the last three years, and he looks the same.'' Stark was ordered held without bail pending another hearing on May 26. <PERSON> Hadley </PERSON> was ordered held without bail pending a bond hearing Friday. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> authorities had issued warrants charging Stark with the May 1, 1987, slaying of a teen-age hitchhiker in Banning and a Feb. 24 rape in <LOCATION> Hemet </LOCATION>. Stark, formerly of <ORGANIZATION> Yucaipa </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, allegedly shot the still-unidentified teen-age girl when she tried to escape from him at a service station in Banning, 90 miles east of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Riverside </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Sheriff's Detective Sgt. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Rush </PERSON>, whose investigation led to the warrant on the February kidnapping-rape, said <PERSON> Stark </PERSON> had been convicted three times of kidnapping and sexual assault and had spent `` almost all the time between 1971 and 1985 in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> prisons and a mental hospital. He'd get out and do it again.'' <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Arbor </PERSON> police arrested Stark on Monday at his car wash job after the telephone tips. <PERSON> Hadley </PERSON> was reported missing by his wife and family in July 1983, the same time the $ 1.1 million disappeared from the credit union. He called home to alert his wife to a letter he left behind. In part of the letter included in federal court documents, <PERSON> Hadley </PERSON> wrote to his wife, `` If I call you to read this letter, it means that I have successfully left the state with around $ 1 million from the credit union.'' His first wife later divorced him, and he remarried. <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents and police called <PERSON> Hadley </PERSON>, 40, and asked him to come to the police station Monday to discuss a neighborhood juvenile case that <PERSON> Hadley </PERSON> and his new wife had reported, then confronted him with the poster. After arriving in <LOCATION> Friendswood </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Hadley </PERSON> obtained the birth certificate of <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Glen </PERSON> <PERSON> Finley </PERSON>, who died after birth in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> in February 1948, <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> said. With the birth certificate, he got a <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>' drivers license and a passport. The `` Unsolved Mysteries'' segment that led to <PERSON> Hadley </PERSON>'s capture still will be broadcast May 6, and will include an update of his arrest, said <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON> <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON>, field producer with <ORGANIZATION> Cosgrove </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Meurer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Productions </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>.
