<HEAD>Dole Blasts ``Gossip And Nit-Picking'' In Campaign Coverage</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS ``sometime'' to ``something'' in graf 9, bgng
``Something is''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LEE GOULD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sen. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, criticizing news coverage of his unsuccessful campaign for the Republican presidential nomination, said Tuesday that reporters were more interested in `` gossip and nit-picking'' than in covering the issues. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Republican leader, said in a floor speech that overall coverage of the 1988 presidential primaries was `` issueless and negative.'' The senator from <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> said a predominantly liberal press corps gave <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> candidates `` far more negative treatment than the Democratic candidates.'' `` What I witnessed generally on my own campaign plane was an aircraft filled with reporters who became each other's best audience,'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said. `` It was an ultrainsider's game of gossip and nit-picking that turned presidential campaign coverage into ` Trivial Pursuits.''' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> cited a recent <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Today </ORGANIZATION> newspaper study he said showed `` network television coverage of the 1988 presidential campaign has focused 80 percent of its time on everything but issues.'' `` There was coverage of all kinds of gossip and ` horse race' stories, and judging from my own experience, who's on or off the <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> campaign plane, which reporter will find that one person in a friendly audience who can serve up a juicy negative quote, and on and on and on. He said the media were more interested in `` putting political gossip above information, and titilation above education.'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> also said <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> candidates received more negative treatment than Democratic candidates. `` Something is out of whack _ and something is disturbingly unfair _ when news coverage becomes so slanted, and the issues get lost in the daily hype,'' he said. `` Look at the news rooms,'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said. `` Let's face it, they tend to be liberal. In all honesty, how many Republicans are out there covering the candidates? Or Congress? I do n't think I could guess more than a carload.'' `` Reporters try to be objective,'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said. `` But try as they do, they just ca n't help but see the world through liberal colored glasses.'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said his audiences wanted to know where he stood on individual issues. `` Unfortunately, the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people are not getting what they want, at least from the news media,'' he said. `` It's a shame the media ca n't keep up with the people,'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said.
