<HEAD>Ethiopia, Somalia Withdraw Troops from Border</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> said Tuesday its troops and those of neighboring <LOCATION> Somalia </LOCATION> have begun withdrawing from their common border as part of a plan to end a century of hostilities between the East African neighbors. The government-owned newspaper The Ethiopian <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> said a joint military committee monitored the initial withdrawals, which took place from April 15-23. <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Somalia </LOCATION> agreed on April 4 to restore diplomatic relations broken 11 years ago when they went to war over a patch of land. They also agreed to move their forces six to nine miles from the border to ease tensions, with redeployment to be completed by May 15. Neither side has said how many troops were involved. The Somali military, however, had estimated that <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> had 150,000 troops stationed permanently on the Somali front. Marxist <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> has the largest military force in black <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, more than 500,000 members, including local militia. <LOCATION> Somalia </LOCATION> has a military force of 65,000. Border disputes have made <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Somalia </LOCATION> enemies for more than a century. In 1977-78, they fought a full-scale war after <LOCATION> Somalia </LOCATION> invaded the <LOCATION> Ogaden </LOCATION>, a semiarid region of eastern <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> populated by ethnic Somalis. <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> drove back the invaders with the help of thousands of Cuban troops and arms from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>'s chief ally.
