<HEAD>Defense Lawyer Criticizes Prosecutor's Attempt to Limit Access to
Documents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A defense lawyer for Iran-Contra defendant <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON> accused prosecutors Tuesday of violating a court order by trying to limit his client's access to classified documents compiled in the case. The procedures proposed by independent counsel <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> to limit <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON>'s right to see certain highly sensitive government documents `` directly contravene'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Gerhard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON>'s order, defense lawyer <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Janis </PERSON> charged in court papers. <PERSON> Janis </PERSON> said <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>'s proposal also would limit access of retired <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Secord </PERSON>, <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON>'s former business partner who also is charged with participating in the illegal conspiracy to divert U.S.-Iran arms-sale profits to the Nicaraguan Contra rebels. The two brokered the arms sales through a series of Swiss-based companies, which also funneled money to the Contras. Under the proposal by <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>'s office, all classified documents turned over to the defense would be made available to lawyers for <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON> and <PERSON> Secord </PERSON> as well as counsel for the other two defendants: Marine Lt. Col. <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON> and former national security adviser <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON>. North, a fired <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> aide, and <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON>, also would be allowed to review all documents furnished to the lawyers, according to a proposal outlined in a letter sent by <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>'s office this week to defense counsel. Before they left the White House staff in November 1986, both <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON> had security clearances and access to the nation's most well-kept secrets and presumably saw _ or generated _ much of the material collected by <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>'s investigators. But <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>'s proposal said <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON> and <PERSON> Secord </PERSON> would not get automatic access to `` particularly sensitive information.'' This material includes documents whose disclosure would jeopardize the lives of hostages in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> or compromise <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> intelligence methods, `` particularly sensitive military operations'' and `` extremely sensitive foreign policy initiatives,'' according to the letter. <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON>, a native of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> who has <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizenship, has never had access to government documents. <PERSON> Secord </PERSON>, who once held sensitive positions in the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>, held a number of security clearances before his <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> retirement. <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> ordered <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> on April 15 to allow the defense to review some 300,000 pages of classified material to determine if it would help their case. An interagency task force is checking the material before it is turned over to the defendants to see what highly sensitive information is included. The sensitive documents covered by <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>'s proposal comprise between 5 percent and 10 percent of the material reviewed so far, defense lawyers were told at a recent meeting with prosecutors. Under the proposal that <PERSON> Janis </PERSON> contends violates <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON>'s April 15 order, defense lawyers could show <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON> and <PERSON> Secord </PERSON> certain sensitive documents only after obtaining the judge's permission. `` It would be within the court's discretion to solicit the government for its views and to make special arrangements for access as the court deems appropriate,'' associate independent counsel <PERSON> Geoffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> wrote in the letter outlining the proposal to defense counsel. During the hearing, <PERSON> Janis </PERSON> told <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> that <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON> `` has no less a need than the other defendants'' to review the documents. <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> assured <PERSON> Janis </PERSON> that he would not bar defense lawyers from telling their clients anything about the case, including information in classified documents. In his protective order, the judge said the defendants and their lawyers could gain access to the documents if they signed agreements not to disclose the information. <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON>'s order warned that unauthorized disclosure could result in prosecution and he set stringent conditions for working with the documents in a special secure area being constructed by the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Janis </PERSON> said the proposed procedures `` directly contravene the court's protective order, which places only limited conditions on access to classified information, all of which were met by Mr. <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON> and his counsel.'' `` Both judicial precedent and the pronouncements of this court make it clear that the government must now give Mr. <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON> access to the information in its possession or face dismissal of the indictment against Mr. <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Janis </PERSON> said. Under the Classified Information Procedures Act, classified documents deemed relevant to the case could only be introduce as evidence by either side if they are declassified by the government. At the April 12 hearing, <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> warned that he would be forced to dismiss the case if <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> were unable to get relevant documents declassified. `` The classification system must be adjusted to the needs of the case or the case will collapse,'' <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> said.
