<DATELINE>RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> accused <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> of `` terrorism and subversion'' and broke relations Tuesday, ordering all Iranian diplomats to leave the kingdom within a week. A statement broadcast by state-run television and distributed by the official <ORGANIZATION> Saudi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> cited a riot by Iranians during a pilgrimage to Mecca last year in which hundreds of people died, a subsequent attack on the <ORGANIZATION> Saudi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> and attacks on commercial shipping in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>. On Sunday, Iranian speedboats attacked a Saudi-owned tanker in the Strait of Hormuz hours after President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> warned <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> to stay clear of neutral ships. An informed source in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> said privately that the Saudi council of ministers decided Monday night to end diplomatic relations with <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s revolutionary regime. <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> and most other Arab countries support <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> in its war with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, which began in September 1980. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> is a Moslem nation but its people are Persian, not Arab. The Saudi statement said that King <PERSON> Fahd </PERSON>'s government exercised self-restraint and prudence for a long time, despite Iranian practices that `` run counter to norms and diplomatic traditions,'' before deciding on the break. A memorandum about the decision was handed to the Iranian charge d'affaires in <LOCATION> Riyadh </LOCATION>, the news agency reported. According to the published statement, `` The government of <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> has decided to sever its ties with the government of the <LOCATION> Islamic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and asked all personnel of the Iranian Embassy in <LOCATION> Riyadh </LOCATION> and the consulate general in <LOCATION> Jiddah </LOCATION> to leave the kingdom within a week.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> warned <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> on Saturday, five days after the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> sank or disabled six Iranian naval vessels, against continuing attacks on neutral shipping. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> have made virulent statements about each other since riots in Mecca on July 31, 1987, that killed 275 Iranian pilgrims and the subsequent sacking of the Saudi Embassy in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>. A Saudi diplomat died of injuries suffered in the attack. Saudi security officials said 402 people were killed in a stampede after an Iranian political demonstration in <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION> turned violent. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> said <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> police caused most of the casualties by shooting into the crowd. Mecca, birthplace of the prophet <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Medina </PERSON>, site of his tomb, are the holiest places for the world's 850 million Moslems. They are in a region of western Saudi Arabian called Hijaz. Iranian leaders, who often threaten to export their fundamentalist revolution to <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> and other gulf nations, exhorted the world's Moslems after the Mecca riots to overthrow the <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> royal family, seize its vast wealth and take away custodianship of the Islamic shrines. Officials of the pro-Western kingdom accused <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> of terrorism. Two weeks ago, <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> said 150,000 Iranian pilgrims would travel to <