<HEAD>Revamp Airline, Highway Programs, Federal Official Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A restructuring of federal airline and interstate highway programs would eliminate bureaucratic practices that interfere with aviation safety and road improvements, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Transportation Secretary <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Burnley </PERSON> said Tuesday. When the interstate highway system is completed in the next few years, the states should assume responsibility for their roads because that way, the projects with the most merit would get top priority, <ORGANIZATION> Burnley </ORGANIZATION> said. `` Costly and extraneous federal requirements now imposed on the use of funds could be virtually eliminated, ensuring a greater transportation return on every dollar spent,'' he told a convention of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Automobile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. `` We are looking at ways to encourage and promote innovative financing mechanisms'' such as permitting the use of tolls on highways built with federal funds, he said. <LOCATION> Burnley </LOCATION>, who has proposed a reshaping of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, told reporters that the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> has never done an adequate job of safety regulation and enforcement of the airline industry because it is subjected to the federal budgetary process and is operated through a maze of federal laws and rules. There is a `` morass of inhibitions on its growth and proper management,'' said <PERSON> Burnley </PERSON>, who took over as transportation secretary from <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> in December. He has described the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> as a `` hybrid'' agency that combines safety regulation and enforcement duties with the nuts-and-bolts operation of running the air-traffic control system. <LOCATION> Burnley </LOCATION> would like to separate the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>'s safety role from its operational functions, and there is a move afoot in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to separate the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> from the <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Burnley </LOCATION> indicated he agreed with efforts to do so. He did n't say how this should be done, but he said he would oppose turning air traffic functions over to a privately run company. On airline safety, <ORGANIZATION> Burnley </ORGANIZATION> said, `` We've tried to toughen up inspections across the board,'' pointing to the current investigation of <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>. The 30-day, plane-by-plane inspection of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s fleet, which began April 13, is evaluating <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s ability to comply with <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> safety standards and has resulted in a proposed $ 823,000 in fines against the airline. <LOCATION> Burnley </LOCATION>, who flew to <LOCATION> Orlando </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> on <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, said the airline is `` one of the safest, if not the safest, airlines in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> because of the attention it has received. ... I flew it with extreme confidence today.'' A similar inspection is also going on at <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>, another <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary. The transportation secretary said the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> investigation was under way before <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s pilots began a postcard campaign detailing alleged maintenance and safety violations. `` I really resent the leadership of the union and the company ... using safety issues as a weapon against each other,'' <ORGANIZATION> Burnley </ORGANIZATION> told a press conference. He said the two sides `` could duke it out'' without resorting to safety allegations. In his luncheon speech to the AAA convention, <ORGANIZATION> Burnley </ORGANIZATION> said the 1987 traffic fatality rate was the lowest in history, with 2.4 deaths per 100 million miles traveled. `` There were just over 46,000 Americans killed on our highways last year, which is tragic by any standard,'' he said. `` But if fatalities were still occurring at the 1980 rate, the death toll would have been 17,000 higher. Both numbers are mind-boggling.'' He credited the reduction in highway accidents to the crackdown on drunken - and drugged-drivers, the greater use of seat belts and new safety rules affecting trucks <ORGANIZATION> Burnley </ORGANIZATION> said it was too early to say what effect the new 65 mph speed limit on rural interstate highways was having on safety.
