<HEAD>Brazil Hires U.S. Firm to Fight Oil Well Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government said Tuesday it has hired the firm of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> oil-well firefighter <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> `` Red'' <PERSON> Adair </PERSON> to put out a blaze at the country's largest offshore oil field. <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinto </PERSON>, spokesman for the government oil firm <ORGANIZATION> Petrobras </ORGANIZATION>, said two employees of the Adair company, based in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, arrived in <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> early Tuesday. He said they went directly to the Enchova oil field in the <LOCATION> Campos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Basin </LOCATION>, 120 miles east of <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION>, where a fire has been burning out of control at an offshore rig since Sunday. The Enchova field and four connected fields have been shut down, cutting <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s oil production by 71,000 barrels a day. The country's daily production is 615,000 barrels. <PERSON> Pinto </PERSON> said the fire started with a gas leak at an oil rig 50 miles off the coast and all 250 workers were evacuated unharmed. Four ships with water cannons sprayed the rig around the clock to minimize damage but could not put out the blaze, according to <PERSON> Pinto </PERSON>. `` There are two possibilities for putting out the fire,'' he said. `` One is to dig a parallel well and draw off the oil and gas feeding the fire. The other is the Americans' way, with an explosion that uses up oxygen and kills the fire.'' <ORGANIZATION> Petrobras </ORGANIZATION> plans to import an additional 60,000 barrels of oil a day at a cost of about $ 1 million to cover most of the loss of production from <LOCATION> Enchova </LOCATION>. `` The platform itself cost $ 330 million and is covered by insurance. A few towers fell down, but apparently it will not be destroyed by the fire,'' <PERSON> Pinto </PERSON> said. The Campos basin is <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s richest oil region and has produced 370,000 barrels daily. But <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> still needs more oil, and imports in the first quarter averaged 718,000 barrels per day.
