<HEAD>Soviet-Canadian Ski Team Reaches North Pole</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES throughout to CORRECT that radio marriage proposal
not made Tuesday</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nine Soviet and four Canadian skiers arrived Tuesday at the North Pole, their first major objective in an attempt to become the first expedition to cross the Arctic on foot. `` Everybody is in great spirits, all hale and hearty,'' said expedition radioman <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Atkins </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>. `` It's a personal victory. They're more than halfway.'' Organizers revealed that wedding bells rather than jingle bells were ringing for one jubilant skier as the group approached the pole earlier this month. <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Buxton </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Calabogie </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION>, in a radio message relayed by a Soviet air base in <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION>, asked his steady back home, <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Burton </PERSON>: `` Will you marry me?'' `` It's so much like <PERSON> Max </PERSON>, he has to do everything different,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Burton </PERSON>, a dental hygienist in <LOCATION> Ottawa </LOCATION>. Her answer, relayed to <PERSON> Buxton </PERSON>, was yes. The team set out from the northernmost tip of <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION> on March 3 and hopes to complete the 1,100-mile trek through some of the world's most hostile terrain by reaching <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, on <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Ellesmere </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, in early June They arrived at the geographic North Pole at 3:20 a.m. EDT Tuesday, the 55th day of their adventure. Soviet explorer and folk hero <PERSON> Dmitri </PERSON> <PERSON> Shparo </PERSON>, Anglican priest <PERSON> Laurie </PERSON> <PERSON> Dexter </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, and the other skiers planned two days of rest before continuing the `` Polar Bridge'' expedition. From the pole, they sent a short radio message: `` The first span of the bridge is complete.'' The team seeks to become the first to make the transcontinental trip across the Arctic without using vehicles or sled dogs. Bad weather prevented a group of Canadian dignitaries from reaching the pole in time to welcome the skiers, <PERSON> Atkins </PERSON> said. Because of poor visibility at Alert, a refueling stop on the northern tip of <LOCATION> Ellesmere </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, the Canadians were stranded at <LOCATION> Eureka </LOCATION>, 300 miles south. Their final destination was a floating Soviet ice station within helicopter range of the North Pole, <PERSON> Atkins </PERSON> said. He said a group of Soviet dignitaries, including former hockey star <PERSON> Vladislav </PERSON> <PERSON> Tretiak </PERSON>, made it to the pole, where the temperature was about 22 degrees below zero. Supplies were flown to the Soviet ice station Tuesday. Each member of the expedition carries a 100-pound backpack with such high-protein, high-fat food as bacon and dried fish to maintain energy and body heat. The Soviet team has government sponsorship and the Canadians found commercial backers. The Soviets proposed the expedition to demonstrate benefits of world cooperation and peace.
