<HEAD>Text on Saudi Statement Breaking Ties With Iran</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Iran-Saudi</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Following is a translation by The Associated Press of the Saudi Arabian government's memorandum on the rupture of ties with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>: In view of the Iranian hostile attitude toward the kingdom of <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, the premeditated offenses to basic Saudi interests and as a result of the Iranian government attitude that runs counter to the principles of international law and diplomatic traditions; On account of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s violation of the principles of good neighborliness and mutual respect, as exemplified in the attempt to smuggle explosives into the Kingdom during the pilgrimage season of the year 1406 -LRB- 1986 -RRB- to imperil the safety of pilgrims and the sacred places; Because of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s manipulation of religious rituals and its instigation of dissent and unrest among the sons of the Islamic nation; Due to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s repeated attempts to harm the basic interests of the kingdom, and its obstruction of free navigation by raiding ships sailing to and from <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, in addition to other forms of terrorism and subversion; The kingdom has resorted to the attitude of self-restraint and prudence required between two neighboring Islamic countries. It tried through various channels to explain to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> that the kingdom was eager to normalize relations on the basis of mutual respect: But the kingdom's positive stance gained no response whatever from the Iranian side, which persisted in perpetrating hostile practices; Foremost among these practices was the ransacking of the <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> embassy of -LRB- King Fahd -RRB- the custodian of the two holy shrines. One Saudi diplomat was killed, embassy documents were looted and its property destroyed in that attack. In addition, the Iranian authorities had failed to provide adequate security for the embassy personnel, who were perpetually harassed, forcing them all to leave <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>: Therefore, the government of <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> decided to break its ties with the <LOCATION> Islamic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and asked all personnel of the Iranian Embassy in <LOCATION> Riyadh </LOCATION> and consulate general in <LOCATION> Jiddah </LOCATION> to leave the kingdom within a week.
