<FIRST>r a AM-SovietSuit     04-26 0573</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Suit,0588</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attorney Claims State Department Made `Backroom Political Deal'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The attorney for an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> businessman who claims the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> libeled him Tuesday criticized the filing of a brief by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> in defense of the Soviets' position. Attorney <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Kroll </PERSON> said he believes the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has `` made a deal _ a backroom political deal'' with the Soviets to avoid further conflict in the 3 -LCB- - year-old case involving <PERSON> Raphael </PERSON> <PERSON> Gregorian </PERSON> `` They've swapped an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> citizen's rights for what the Soviets want,'' said <PERSON> Kroll </PERSON>, who seeks payment of both a libel judgment and the cost of medical supplies which Gregorian sold to Soviet hospitals before he was expelled from that country. `` Gregorian's life-saving medical equipment is being used in hospitals in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and the American government is trying to help the Soviets weasel out of paying,'' said <PERSON> Kroll </PERSON>. `` This case has gone beyond being a simple trade case.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s legal brief, filed last week in the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> 9th </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>, seeks to reopen a case which led to an award to Gregorian for the loss of more than $ 200,000 worth of medical supplies. <PERSON> Kroll </PERSON>, meanwhile, is seeking to reopen the libel portion of the case, which was thrown out by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Kenyon </PERSON>. <PERSON> Gregorian </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Palo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alto </LOCATION>, did business in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> for 14 years. He was operating a $ 10 million a year medical supply company in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> when he was abruptly expelled in November 1984. <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> printed an article alleging he was a spy and <PERSON> Gregorian </PERSON> decided to sue. In the opening rounds of his litigation, <PERSON> Gregorian </PERSON> won by default when the Soviets failed to come to court. But when <PERSON> Kroll </PERSON> began seizing Soviet assets to satisfy the damage judgment, the Soviets began to fight back, seeking a hearing in federal court. After long months of litigation, <PERSON> Kenyon </PERSON> reversed himself and threw out the libel award, but the judge ruled that <PERSON> Gregorian </PERSON> must be compensated for the medical supplies he left behind. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s 49-page brief backs <PERSON> Kenyon </PERSON>'s conclusion that the Soviets should be immune from libel suits, and also argues that they should be allowed to mount a full defense on the issue of paying for medical supplies. In its brief and accompanying documents, the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> contended that the <PERSON> Gregorian </PERSON> case `` has become a significant issue in bilateral <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States-Soviet </ORGANIZATION> relations.'' <PERSON> Kroll </PERSON> labeled that argument `` ridiculous.'' `` We fail to see how forcing the Soviets to pay for medical supplies will start World War III,'' the attorney said. <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Letter </PERSON>, an appellate staff attorney with the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, said he would not comment further on