<HEAD>Senators Request Ethics Review of SDI Research Contracts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES HANNAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two senators Tuesday asked the head of the Office of Government Ethics to determine whether any laws were violated in the award of government research contracts to a company with employees who served on a federal advisory committee. Sens. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>, D-Mich., said a recent hearing by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> turned up possible conflicts of interest Those conflicts involved two members of the <ORGANIZATION> Eastport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, an eight-member panel that gives advice on computer and battle management issues to the federal agency managing the nation's `` Star Wars'' missile defense program Those two <ORGANIZATION> Eastport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> members, whose names were not immediately available, are employed by <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, which has won two SDI contracts. In a letter to <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Nebeker </PERSON>, director of the Office of Government Ethics, <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> and <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> said the two multimillion-dollar contracts at issue pay for research directly related to recommendations made by the <ORGANIZATION> Eastport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>. `` In fact, the first contract was based on an unsolicited proposal by <ORGANIZATION> ISI </ORGANIZATION>, submitted within two weeks of the -LRB- committee -RRB- report recommending such research,'' <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> and <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> said in their letter. `` Both contracts were awarded under questionable circumstances.'' When questioned about the contracts, the senators said, the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> ended the first contract earlier than planned and announced it would reopen negotiations on the second. The senators said the Federal Advisory Committee Act requires agencies to impose management controls on advisory committees and that <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> conflict-of-interest rules require committee members to follow certain ethical standards and file financial disclosure forms. They asked <PERSON> Nebeker </PERSON> whether the committee members were subject to federal standards of conduct at the time of the contract awards, whether any laws or regulations governing ethical conduct were violated and whether the matter should be referred to the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> for investigation. <ORGANIZATION> ISI </ORGANIZATION> is a research group affiliated with the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Biller </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> ISI </ORGANIZATION>'s vice president for external affairs, said the institute welcomes the review by the Office of Government Ethics. `` We do n't believe there is anything that represents an ethical concern ... or a legal problem,'' said <PERSON> Biller </PERSON>. `` We believe everyone has acted in good faith.''
