<HEAD>Television Shows First Pictures of Ethnic Protests in Caucasus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet television broadcast film Tuesday of chanting crowds of thousands in two <LOCATION> Caucasus </LOCATION> republics, the first scenes it has shown of ethnic unrest two months ago that led to at least 32 deaths. A 90-minute special about the trouble in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> included criticism of the official press and appeared to be an acknowledgment that reporting on the unrest was slow and incomplete. The host was <PERSON> Genrikh </PERSON> <PERSON> Borovik </PERSON>, a journalist and head of the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. The show laid much of the blame for rioting on rumors, but also indicated silence by the media did nothing to squelch the rumors. Such a program could not have been appeared before Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s program of `` glasnost,'' or greater openness. It was called `` <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> _ Reflection on Rumors'' and began with a woman from <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION>, capital of <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, criticizing lack of information from the media. `` I myself am not satisfied with the mass media, which incorrectly reflected the events that took place in <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>,'' said the woman, who was not identified. `` Central television also was silent about what happened there.'' <PERSON> Borovik </PERSON>'s broadcast, which preceded the main news program Vremya, showed black-and-white film of thousands of chanting people jamming open areas in <LOCATION> Stepanakert </LOCATION>, capital of the <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> region of <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>. Signs visible in the crowd demanded that the region, three-fourths of whose people are ethnic Armenians, be annexed to <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> was assigned to <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> in 1923. Protesters also demanded improved cultural and economic conditions in <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Borovik </PERSON> did not reveal the origin of the film. He said protests began in <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> in mid-February, leading to demonstrations in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> by hundreds of thousands of people who heard rumors that protesting Armenians had been killed. More demonstrations followed in <LOCATION> Baku </LOCATION>, capital of <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>, he said. Soviet officials have rejected the demand that <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> be annexed to <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, but offered a long-term program to improve the area's economic and cultural life. About 15 minutes of film showed demonstrations in <LOCATION> Stepanakert </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Baku </LOCATION>. It also showed broken windows and damaged buildings in <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION>, the city in <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> where the deaths occurred. The number of injured at <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION> was given as 200, much higher than the 81 reported April 13 by the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>. Officials told the program more than 80 people were under arrest on charges of murder or participating in the `` massive disorder in <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Borovik </PERSON> criticized <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION> officials for negligence and said some lived in <LOCATION> Baku </LOCATION> rather than the city they governed. He did not identify them, but the city <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief, mayor and police chief were fired after the rioting. According to the program, 50 people were hurt in <LOCATION> Agdan </LOCATION>, a town in <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Borovik </PERSON> said a criminal spread a rumor in <LOCATION> Agdam </LOCATION> that a 12-year-old boy had been killed by Armenians in <LOCATION> Stepanakert </LOCATION>. A young man interviewed by <PERSON> Borovik </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> criticized <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> media for not providing information sooner on those killed in the ethnic rioting. Reports several weeks afterward said the dead were 26 Armenians and six Azerbaijanis.
