<HEAD>Parents, School Dispute Drug Use For HyperActive Third-Grader</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 7th graf, `Outside the...'., to UPDATE
with later testimony from boy's second-grade teacher. Picks up 8th
graf pvs, `Ritalin is...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTHA ENGLERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The drug Ritalin turned a difficult, hyperactive 9-year-old boy into `` a zombie,'' the boy's parents charged as they appealed to state school officials Tuesday not to force him to take the medicine. <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> <PERSON> Jesson </PERSON>'s parents appealed to a state education department hearing officer, and said they will go to court if necessary to override the <LOCATION> Derry </LOCATION> school district's order that he go back on drug Ritalin, or another medication, before he is allowed back in his third-grade class. `` We stopped the pills after my husband suggested that he should get in the car with <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> and drive until they hit a wall,'' said <PERSON> Casey </PERSON>'s mother, <PERSON> Valerie </PERSON>. `` Life had become that much hell. Everything was coming apart.'' State school hearing officer <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Falkenham </PERSON> did not indicate when he would rule on the <PERSON> Jessons </PERSON>' appeal of the school district requirement that he take the medication. The child is currently being taught by a tutor provided by the school system, pending the outcome of the hearing. Both sides agree <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> has serious behavior problems, but no one has pinpointed the cause. With medication, <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> is manageable, school officials said in testimony submitted earlier. Without it, they said, he is disruptive and insults school officials, and refuses to follow the simplest of classroom instructions. Outside the hearing, <ORGANIZATION> Derry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> Superintendent <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said that <PERSON> Casey </PERSON>'s teacher sometimes had to call the principal to the class to physically remove <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> from the room when he refused to go out for lunch. <PERSON> Rachel </PERSON> <PERSON> Cobban </PERSON>, <PERSON> Casey </PERSON>'s second-grade teacher, testified Tuesday that when the boy quit taking <PERSON> Ritalin </PERSON>, he `` did n't stay in his seat and pestered other children. I got no work from him.'' `` He could n't sit still even to do a five-minute reading task,'' she said, adding that <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> began having temper tantrums, tipped over his desk and ate pencils and erasers. Ritalin is a stimulant, but paradoxically it can calm hyperactive children, many experts say. <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> began taking Ritalin in the first grade when behavior problems surfaced and continued taking it before school and during the day for 18 months until the spring of last year. Off Ritalin, <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> has gained weight, sleeps better and looks healthier, said his father, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON>. But he still does not know right from wrong, has a very short attention span and, in general is a `` bright but very trying child,'' <PERSON> Jesson </PERSON> said. On Ritalin, <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> looked and acted like a drug addict with facial twitches, pale skin, little appetite and insomnia, his parents said. He would sit for hours in front of the television and rock back and forth, his mother said. Late in the afternoon, when the drug began to wear off, he would begin to kick, scream, cry for hours, remain awake until after midnight, refuse to eat, make repetitive animal noises and stare transfixed at the faces he would make in a mirror, his parents said. `` He was a child in the driver's seat,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Jesson </PERSON>. `` If we had a good day, it was because <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> let us have a good day. He was full of rage and it demanded our constant attention.'' The <PERSON> Jessons </PERSON> rejected suggestions that they increase the amount of Ritalin to keep <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> medicated at night. `` The stuff made him a zombie. I could n't do that to him,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Jesson </PERSON>. The alternative to Ritalin is <LOCATION> Cylert </LOCATION>, which can cause an enzyme buildup in the liver and would require <PERSON> Casey </PERSON>'s blood to be checked periodically, according to testimony from doctors who evaluated <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> at <ORGANIZATION> Children </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. Since taking <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> <PERSON> off </PERSON> <PERSON> Ritalin </PERSON>, the <PERSON> Jessons </PERSON> have experimented with their son's diet, trying to see what food substances or additives affect his behavior. Some experts have linked hyperactivity to a child's diet. `` We know he craves sugar and feels better when amounts of it are kept to the absolute minimum,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Jesson </PERSON>. The Jessons have rejected the school district's proposal to put <PERSON> Casey </PERSON>, provided he goes back on medication, in a program of counseling and behavior therapy. His parents want the school district to offer <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> a educational curriculum that includes counseling, behavior modification, and more focus on the needs of hyperactive children, such as special dietary needs _ but no medication. `` This kid had problems to begin with and then was blown apart by Ritalin,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Jesson </PERSON>. `` This family is through with drugs. We need answers without drugs.''
