<HEAD>Byrd Puts Brakes on Trade Bill as Demos Scramble for GOP Support</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS grafs 4-5 pvs, `Byrd also ... this year,' with 2 grafs
to explain delay and UPDATE with quote from Reagan's letter to
Dole; MOVES UP 18th graf pvs bgng, `The centerpiece,' which becomes
new 6th graf; INSERTS 2 grafs after 17th graf pvs bgng, `It's a
tempest,' to UPDATE with lawmakers meet and administration confirms
oil provision in US-Canada pact; TRIMS last 2 grafs pvs to EDIT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Democratic leaders put the brakes on a major trade bill Tuesday, postponing a vote on final passage while they scrambled for enough Republican support to override a threatened presidential veto. Provisions that would limit export of Alaskan oil became a critical stumbling block as leaders campaigned to line up enough votes to make President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> think twice before reaching for his veto pen. <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, postponed until Wednesday or possibly even Thursday a vote on the 1,000-page bill <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> opposes because it would require all but the smallest employers to give notice of plant-closings and major The delay gave <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> leaders more time to beat the bushes for Republican support. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> again signaled that he would veto the measure as it stands, saying in a letter to <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Minority Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, R-Kan., that lawmakers should `` finish the trade bill process in a way that serves <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s interests _ not special interests. The centerpiece of the bill would streamline the system under which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> imposes import restrictions to retaliate against international trade violations and aid <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industries threatened by stepped up foreign competition. <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, said he was searching for ways to take care of complaints from <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s senators that the bill was too restrictive of their state's oil exports Party leaders figured that <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> need 14 Republican votes to demonstrate the two-thirds support needed to override a veto. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> did not tip his hand by offering a specific count. He again said it was close. Both parties were bidding for support from <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> senators, <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> and <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Murkowski </PERSON>, who reported themselves incensed over the oil exports provision. `` This legislation discriminates very violently against my state,'' <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. `` It is a concept that I am unable to accept.'' Currently it is illegal to export any oil from the <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> oil pipeline, but the state does export about 4,000 barrels a day from <LOCATION> Cook </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Inlet </LOCATION>. The trade bill would limit export of refined oil from a new installation at <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION> to 70,000 barrels a day and 50 percent of output. The limit would apply statewide and thus act as a cap on any additional refineries built. Another provision would require that crude oil exports to <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> of 50,000 barrels a day envisioned under a pending trade pact would have to be transported first to some point in the lower 48 states, presumably <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, before being sent back north of the border. <PERSON> Murkowski </PERSON> said it was unconstitutional to discriminate against one state in legislation applying to the entire country. The crude oil provision had been sought by the maritime industry, which currently transports the oil to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> ports and would lose jobs if it were merely piped over the border to <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Murray </PERSON>, press secretary to Rep. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonker </PERSON>, D-Wash., said <PERSON> Bonker </PERSON> and other lawmakers had drawn the provision requiring shipment of crude to the lower 48 states before export to <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> He said it merely echoed provisions already in the pending U.S.-Canada free trade agreement. He said <PERSON> Bonker </PERSON> supported the provision because he feared maritime unions would scuttle the free trade agreement without it and because he was concerned about dwindling employment in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> maritime industry. `` It's a tempest in a teapot,'' he said. He said criticism of the provision contained political overtones for <PERSON> Bonker </PERSON>, who is currently running for a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> seat against former GOP Sen. <PERSON> Slade </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorton </PERSON>. `` This has a lot to do with <PERSON> Slade </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorton </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Murray </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bonker </PERSON> later met with <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> and <PERSON> Murkowski </PERSON> and issued a statement afterward saying he believed it would be possible to reach a compromise. He added: `` I do n't think anybody in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> or <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> wants to scuttle the entire bill on a single issue like <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> oil.'' The provision requiring a stopoff in a <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> port for <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> crude exports does appear in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> free trade agreement, confirmed <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON>, a press aide to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Trade Representative <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON>. He said it was placed in the pact at the urging of maritime interests. Sen. <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Gramm </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Texas </LOCATION>, said he would vote against the bill. He said the savings and loan industry in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and numerous other industries would be crippled by the plant-closings provision. He acknowledged a political risk in opposing the bill because it also calls for the repeal of the windfall profits tax on oil companies _ a move favored by the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> oil industry.
