mixed-race <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION>. In other developments: _ The Weekly Mail, an anti-apartheid publication, received a warning from Home Affairs Minister <PERSON> Stoffel </PERSON> <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> that it could soon be closed for publishing material he considers subversive. <PERSON> Irwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Manoim </PERSON>, the newspaper's co-publisher, said the warning meant <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> could act within three weeks to install an in-house censor or close the paper for three months. The New Nation, another anti-apartheid newspaper, has been closed for three months and several other publications have received warnings from <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>. He has censorship authority under the state of emergency imposed by the white-controlled government. _ Civil rights workers said the government has declared the black township of <PERSON> Oukasie </PERSON> `` an emergency camp.'' The government is trying to relocate the township's residents and thousands are refusing to move. The civil rights workers of the <ORGANIZATION> Transvaal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> said the emergency-camp designation meant that <PERSON> Oukasie </PERSON>, near the northeastern city of Brits, was no longer governed by regular municipal laws and could be abolished. About 5,000 <PERSON> Oukasie </PERSON> residents have complied with government directions and moved to an area 15 miles away, but 8,000 have defied the government and refused to leave. Opponents of the relocation said the government wants to demolish <PERSON> Oukasie </PERSON> because of complaints from white residents in Brits who say the township is too close to their neighborhoods. By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s racial classifications include whites, blacks, Asians and people of mixed race.
