<HEAD>Acreage Near Chernobyl Reactor To Be Planted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Officials have decided it is safe to cultivate about 74,000 acres of land near the Chernobyl plant back two years after the world's worst nuclear power accident, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. The Soviet news agency said in a report from <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> that radiation levels around the power plant in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION> are well within internationally accepted norms. In a separate report, Soviet television showed film of a memorial gathering of relatives of those killed in the explosion and fire at the plant's No. 4 reactor on April 26, 1986. At least 31 people were killed by the blast and the release of radiation, and a cloud of radiactive material circled the Earth. <PERSON> Alexei </PERSON> <PERSON> Denisenko </PERSON>, deputy chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Ukraine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agro-Industrial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, told <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> the land to be brought back into cultivation lies within the 18-mile zone around the plant that was evacuated after the accident. It said scientists are working in <LOCATION> Pripyat </LOCATION>, the former home of 49,000 people located three miles from the plant, to see if any long-term damage was done to plant life. `` So far we have not detected any mutations or changes in the chromosome systems of plants,'' said laboratory director <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> Arkhipov </PERSON>. `` The research shows that the level of its contamination with radionuclides does not exceed the international medical norm for foodstuffs.'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said the radiation level near the plant's first reactor is about 0.5 milliroentgen an hour, and about four milliroentgen near the second reactor. A milliroentgen is one-thousandth of a roentgen, the standard measure of ionizing radiation. Experts say exposure to 50 roentgens or more per year is dangerous and 400 roentgens per year can be fatal. The news agency said a power plant worker would have to stay on the site for 50 years to receive the dosage of radiation considered the maximum allowable by international standards. Soviet news media generally have given a positive picture of work at the Chernobyl plant in a series of reports dedicated to the anniversary of the accident. But on Sunday, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> newspaper Pravda blasted sloppy repairs, drunkenness and nepotism at the plant. It said managers there act `` as though there has n't been an accident.''
