<HEAD>U.N. Honing Plans For Refugee Return</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERT one graf after 6th graf pvs, Officials of ... UPDATING
with secretary-general's announcement on Soviet withdrawal
monitoring. Pick up 7th graf pvs, Faubert said ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY CZUCZKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> officials are putting the finishing touches on a return program for more than 5 million Afghan refugees, potentially one of the biggest <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> operations ever. The prospect of continued civil war in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> makes a swift refugee return seem unlikely, but the world body is preparing for several possibilities. Envoys of the Office of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> High Commissioner for Refugees have begun talks on repatriation with the governments of the three countries involved _ <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Carrol </PERSON> <PERSON> Faubert </PERSON>, head of the Afghan repatriation unit at <ORGANIZATION> UNHCR </ORGANIZATION>, said plans for returning the refugees are `` almost final _ and provisional, of course, because we do n't know when, how many and in what time frame people will move.'' `` We're trying to be ready for quick action if there is more rapid movement than some expect,'' he added. Also, the refugee situation differs in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, two border nations harboring the displaced Afghans. Officials of various <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> agencies will meet in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Thursday to distribute tasks in the repatriation, said <ORGANIZATION> UNHCR </ORGANIZATION> sources, who spoke on the condition of anonymity. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> is expected to appoint a special program coordinator shortly, as was done during the African drought emergency. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> told a news conference Tuesday that <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> observers will soon be deployed to monitor withdrawal of Soviet troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and a political settlement. He said the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> authorized him to proceed with the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> mission. `` Our operation will be very much on in the next few days,'' he said. <PERSON> Faubert </PERSON> said in an interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> that <ORGANIZATION> UNHCR </ORGANIZATION> intends to supervise protection for the returnees, organize transportation back to their place of origin, and oversee the initial distribution of food, seeds and agricultural tools after they return. A communications network to monitor the different parts of the program must also be built. The effort is expected to cost hundreds of millions of dollars if all Afghans return, <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> refugee commissioner <PERSON> Jean-Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Hocke </PERSON> has said. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> is expected to launch an appeal for money soon. `` Our people are drawing up a number of scenarios that go from a massive rush to people not moving very quickly. In <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, there are about 20 different scenarios,'' <PERSON> Faubert </PERSON> said. He said it is also difficult to predict whether the refugees will return to several areas simultaneously or move region by region. Apart from logistics, <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> officials are evaluating what aid is needed to rebuild roads and dwellings and restore land in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. More than a third of the population fled during 10 years of civil war. Official figures list 3.1 million Afghan refugees in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and 2.4 million in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. Under a U.N.-sponsored agreement signed April 14, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> pledged to withdraw its troops backing the Afghan government, starting May 15. <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> agreed to ensure the safe and voluntary return of refugees. Not signing were Moslem Afghan guerrillas, who say they will continue fighting to overthrow the communist <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> government. <ORGANIZATION> UNHCR </ORGANIZATION> officials in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> met with the resistance shortly before the pact's conclusion, apparently aiming to draw them into the repatriation plans. <PERSON> Faubert </PERSON> refused to reveal the outcome of the talks but said they will continue. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> plans must also take into account the differences between government policy and the composition of the refugee population in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. Most Afghans in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> are displaced farmers, housed in 320 refugee villages within about 60 miles of the border. They own about 4,000 private trucks, so there could be sizeable, unsupervised returns. In <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, about 60 percent of the Afghan refugees are in cities relatively far from the border. Many are said to have found menial jobs. They may wait for years to return, <PERSON> Faubert </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, which did not take part in the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> negotiations, and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> both pledge not to expel refugees. But Pakistani officials make clear they would welcome a quick return home of the Afghans. Many Pakistanis blame the refugees for a wide range of the country's social and economic problems.
