<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 At one point in <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` The Richest Man in the World: The Story of <PERSON> Aristotle </PERSON> <PERSON> Onassis </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Winston </PERSON> <PERSON> Churchill </PERSON> asks <PERSON> Ari </PERSON> how he thinks history will remember him. <PERSON> Onassis </PERSON> demurs, but he could have predicted that he would be immortalized in lame, exploitative made-for-TV movies to run in sweeps months on <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> networks. This latest airs Sunday and Monday. What starts as inconsequential pulp basically stays that way, although, when <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Julia </PERSON> takes over the title role late in the first half, it threatens to become an interesting character study of a powerful man who knew exactly what he wanted and just could n't quite get it This is a sympathetic portrait of <PERSON> Onassis </PERSON>, as well as <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Callas </PERSON>, played by <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Seymour </PERSON>. <PERSON> Jackie </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Francesca </PERSON> <PERSON> Annis </PERSON> -RRB- and the rest of the <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> clan come off as a bunch of money-grubbing ugly Americans. The movie, based on the best-selling biography `` <PERSON> Ari </PERSON>,'' by <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, is n't the first TV treatment of the Greek shipping magnate's life <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Quinn </PERSON> portrayed a character obviously based on Onassis in the TV movie `` The Greek Tycoon'' several years ago. This time, he plays <PERSON> Onassis </PERSON>' father, a thankless role that has him alternately fuming and spouting fortune-cookie proverbs. <PERSON> Quinn </PERSON>'s son, <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>, incidentally, plays <PERSON> Onassis </PERSON>' son, <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON>. <PERSON> Elias </PERSON> <PERSON> Koteas </PERSON> is adequate as the young <PERSON> Ari </PERSON>, though his role lasts too long, and he does n't in the least resemble <PERSON> Julia </PERSON>, whose droopy eyelids and languid sensuality are perfect for playing <PERSON> Onassis </PERSON>, who in real life was n't exactly a matinee idol. The movie begins with <PERSON> Onassis </PERSON> as a youth in <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> where his father was a tobacco dealer. When the Turks begin rounding up Greeks, attractive young <ORGANIZATION> Aristo </ORGANIZATION> avoids being sent to a labor camp by having an affair with a Turkish colonel, no doubt with the words of his father _ `` A wise man does what is necessary'' _ ringing in his ears. But his father does n't appreciate the way <ORGANIZATION> Aristo </ORGANIZATION> has won the family's freedom, so <PERSON> Ari </PERSON> moves to <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> where he sells cigarettes and begins a habit of seducing opera stars. <PERSON> Julia </PERSON> shows up as <PERSON> Ari </PERSON> at 46, when he marries <PERSON> Tina </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Beatie </PERSON> <PERSON> Edney </PERSON> -RRB-, the 17-year-old daughter of a shipping competitor -LRB- <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Zerbe </PERSON> -RRB-. Now the luscious trashiness begins in earnest. After having two children, <PERSON> Tina </PERSON>, who may be young but is not stupid, notices her husband's philandering and leaves. <PERSON> Ari </PERSON> continues his pursuit of the volatile <PERSON> Callas </PERSON> while wining and dining jet-setters like <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Radziwill </PERSON>, and the powerful of the world, including <PERSON> Churchill </PERSON>. <PERSON> Through </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, he meets her sister, the delicate wife of an up-and-coming <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> senator. The short, stocky <PERSON> Onassis </PERSON> probably would have been delighted at a yacht scene in which <PERSON> Julia </PERSON> towers over the actor playing <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>. <PERSON> Annis </PERSON> plays <PERSON>