<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 1336EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv27   04-26 0543</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 27 ,0559</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv 27</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Wednesday April 27</NOTE>
<HEAD>Crises By Forecast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Every day since the stock market crash a half-year ago, an economic crisis of one sort or another has been forecast _ in trade, credit, stocks, bonds, car sales and more. Oddly, and offering a flash of insight about our times, none of the `` crises'' has arrived. They fade quietly, no apologies from their creators, and are replaced by vitally fresh hair-raisers. Are mortgage rates headed higher? Will the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> clamp down on the money supply? Can the dollar be saved? Economically speaking, the six months since the great stock market crash have been unusually calm. The economy has neither boomed nor busted. The jobless rate has trended lower. Securites have been fairly stable. It has not been that way in the forecasts. Had they been right, securities would be deeply depressed, unemployment would have soared, home mortgages would have been unattainable, plants and factories would be shutting down. In short, the economy as forecast would be in ruins. While forecasters suggest it is a miracle their worst estimates have n't come true, it is equally amazing to others that some forecasters wo n't give up. In almost every economic forecast there remains a sense of punishment due. Good economic news is seldom accepted for what it is; instead, it provokes forecasts of worse to come. Poor economic news is almost welcomed. The contrast between forecast and performance is especially obvious in the stock market, where it has become axiomatic that a pervading bearishness in the forecasts indicates, of all things, a higher market to come. Whatever the reasons, the persistent sense of fear in the forecasts has created the impression that the past six months have been ones of turmoil, whereas they have been closer to tranquillity. Why then do the fears linger? A sense of guilt, perhaps. If the stock market crashed why should n't a recession follow?. Recessions almost always follow, so why not now? A recognition that deep, and largely unresolved problems remain. The trade and budget deficits, Third World loans, a high level of credit at every level of the economy, the threat of trade wars, the volatility of markets. But that does n't fully explain why the good news is discounted. The economy, for example, has been neither strong nor weak, and either one could cause trouble; inflation in one instance, recession in the other. Jobs are being created. Inflation remains in check. Interest rates, though edging higher, have n't been jumping around as they once did. Exports are improving. Eventually there will be a recession, because if there is one clearly demonstrable trait of economies is that they run in cycles. Sooner or later expansions get out of hand, inflation begins, recession ensues. While recession is viewed as an event to avoid, it can be argued that it is necessary for clearing the way for the next expansion. But to view it that way might be more than the human mind can accept. No less acceptable, however, than the reign of terror in the forecasts of things to come that destroy the calm of the present.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Wednesday April 27</NOTE>
</DOC>
