<HEAD>Doo-wop Lives in Philly</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The sound can still be heard in the city: four or five voices working on a street corner, in a resonant subway tunnel, maybe up on the roof. Doo-wop crested 25 or 30 years ago, with hits such as `` Earth Angel,'' `` Under the Boardwalk'' and <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>'s own Silhouettes singing `` Get a Job,'' but it's never gone away. `` In the early'60s, this music was disappearing as a trend. But for the past four or five years it's coming back as an underground situation,'' said <PERSON> Stan </PERSON> <PERSON> Weaver </PERSON>, tenor with the Zip Codes. The hopping and bobbing doo-wop sound now turns up in commercials for <ORGANIZATION> McDonalds </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Kentucky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fried </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicken </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Levi </PERSON>'s blue jeans. But <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>'s street corners can still attract some harmony on a warm evening with a group of guys with nothing but a pitch pipe to get started on the right key. Doo-wop was city music _ <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> _ and that's where it survives. In <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> <PERSON> Horner </PERSON>'s `` Rhythm and Blues Show'' on WXPN-FM keeps the flame alive. About 30 singers, who could n't afford instruments as teen-agers and do n't want them now, were in the studio recently to help <PERSON> Horner </PERSON> celebrate his 13th year on the air <PERSON> Horner </PERSON> travels 75 miles from his album-packed home in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bound </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brook </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, to west <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> to `` spin the sides'' every Saturday afternoon. `` It's like having a a second job, but a good portion of my paycheck goes into records,'' said <PERSON> Horner </PERSON>, a chemist. With tens of thousands of records stacked on the floor, couch and tables of his <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> apartment, <PERSON> Horner </PERSON> has plenty of tunes from which to choose. And with a man who spends every spare moment and all his spare change on this music, do n't call them oldies or nostalgia; they're terms that make <PERSON> Horner </PERSON> wince To him, these songs are n't locked in the past, or symbols of a lost era. `` The type of music we play on the air is mostly from the'50s, but that's just an accident of time,'' he said. <PERSON> Horner </PERSON> started in college as a deejay on <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s student-run radio station, then moved on to <ORGANIZATION> WXPN </ORGANIZATION> He has n't found any reason to leave a microphone that puts him at the center of doo-wop singers and fans in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. During his radio show, <PERSON> Horner </PERSON> fields telephone calls from singers who recorded the 30 - or 35-year-old records he plays Occassionaly, he finds himself as the middleman in a reunion. The Keystoners credit <PERSON> Horner </PERSON> with bringing the group back together after 25 years of estrangement. Five years ago they sang in public for the first time since 1958 and are back recording, hoping to relive the success of their regional hit, `` Magic Kiss.'' Most singers, though, realize doo-wop stands little chance of ever being more than a hobby for them. `` You have to love to sing, because you're not going to get rich off it,'' <PERSON> Horner </PERSON> said. `` We're looking forward to something very serious,'' said <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Shipman </PERSON>, baritone with <ORGANIZATION> Choice </ORGANIZATION>, a group that traveled from northern <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> to sing live on <PERSON> Horner </PERSON>'s show during the anniversary special. While doo-wop bears the imprint of church choirs and of mellow quartets such as the <ORGANIZATION> Mills </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Horton </PERSON> says the specific doo-wop sound can be traced to <PERSON> Sonny </PERSON> <PERSON> Til </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> Orioles </ORGANIZATION>, whose 1948 hit, `` It's Too Soon to Know,'' inspired black teen-agers to sing on the street corners, <PERSON> Horner </PERSON> said. `` He was to blacks what <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinatra </PERSON> was to whites at the time,'' <PERSON> Horner </PERSON> said. Til's group was among the first to use a wordless falsetto, with other parts singing nonsensical syllables to round out the chord. Doo-wop legend has it that The <ORGANIZATION> Ravens </ORGANIZATION>' bass singer, <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Ricks </PERSON>, mistakenly started singing his part a few notes early one night, drawing a gleeful and raucous response from the crowd at the Apollo Theater in <LOCATION> Harlem </LOCATION>. The doo-wop bass lead was born. With <PERSON> Ricks </PERSON> singing lead, the group scored a hit with `` Old Man River.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Orioles </ORGANIZATION>' 1949 hit, `` Do n't Tell Me So,'' reached No. 1 on the rhythm and blues charts, while `` Crying in the Chapel'' hit No. 11 on the pop charts, making it one of the first R & amp; B songs to cross over into the white market. `` For black kids, it was something they heard all their lives. It was white <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> that suddenly turned on to it in the mid -'50s,'' <PERSON> Horner </PERSON> <PERSON> Horner </PERSON> is n't sure when it happened, but at some point he turned from a fan to a historian of vocal harmony. With <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Caplan </PERSON>, he is working on a book about the <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rhythm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boys </ORGANIZATION>, whose style was more an extension of jazz than rhythm and blues. The Delta Rhythm Boys went to <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION> in 1960 when their popularity in this country waned. `` The sad thing is, a lot of forms of American music, while they have die-hard fans, need mass appeal. It's unfortunate a lot of black musicians have to go to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>,'' he said. Lee Gains of the <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rhythm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boys </ORGANIZATION>, `` probably one of the best bass singers in the history of the planet'' in <PERSON> Horner </PERSON>'s estimation, died July 15, 1987. Seven days later, while singing a spiritual at the funeral, <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON> suffered a fatal heart attack. With two members of the group dead, <PERSON> Horner </PERSON> is more determined to chronicle the music and its influences. `` People may not appreciate it -LRB- the music -RRB- now, but might in 2050 and wo n't know anything about it. I'm trying to preserve the history of this music before its lost,'' <PERSON> Horner </PERSON> said.
