<HEAD>Prize For Moslem Leader Delayed For Inquiry At His Request</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Officials say the postponement in giving the 1988 Templeton Prize for progress in religion to Moslem leader <PERSON> Inamullah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> was at his request after some Jewish leaders accused him of anti-Semitism. `` He himself asked for the delay so assurances could be given that the charges were not valid,'' says the Rev. <PERSON> Wilbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Forker </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Nassau </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION>, vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Templeton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>. `` Board members are now looking into it in this country and abroad.'' He said the postponment was ordered April 5 and the inquiry was not likely to be concluded until mid-summer. Charges that <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> was anti-Semitic came after he was named in March to receive the $ 390,000 prize for advancing cooperation among Moslems, Christians and Jews. It had been scheduled for presentation May 10 in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Khan </PERSON>, 73, of <LOCATION> Karachi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, secretary-general of the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Moslem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, said in a letter to the prize office: `` I request that the prize ceremony be delayed, if necessary for several months, to allow full assurances to be given to the <LOCATION> Templeton </LOCATION> judges and the public to clear away untruthful accusations and misunderstandings.'' The criticisms were raised by the Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith, which alleged past anti-Jewish comments by <ORGANIZATION> Moslem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> officers and in its newsletter. <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> says, `` The allegation that the World Moslem Congress ever issued or mailed from its office any anti-Semitic literature is a palpable falsehood.'' He also said in a lengthy memorandum, answering questions relayed to him by the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Times: `` I can never support anti-Semitic feelings because I am myself a decendant of Semitic ancestors from the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> ... I respect Jews as ` People of the Book'; I respect <PERSON> Moses </PERSON> as a prophet of God.'' However, mentioning a point that outrages Jews _ the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> classifying of Zionism -LRB- Jewish nationalism -RRB- as racism _ <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> added: `` My difference is with the Zionists because the <ORGANIZATION> UN </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> has declared Zionism a racist creed.'' He also said the common Arab description of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> as the `` Zionist entity'' has no significance. Jews, however, overwhelmingly resent it. Noting that he is a president of the interfaith <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Religion </ORGANIZATION> and Peace, he said, `` I have consistently preached inter-religious concord and understanding and promoted interfaith meetings.'' <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, associate general secretary of the interfaith conference, observed of the controversy: `` The prize is not because the winner is a saint but because he has made some religious progress. <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> has made some remarkable strides toward greater openness to other religions and respect for them.'' <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> had been accused by <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Foxman </PERSON>, national director of the <ORGANIZATION> ADL </ORGANIZATION>, of denying <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s right to exist. However, <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> said he backs <ORGANIZATION> UN </ORGANIZATION> resolution 242, which supports a secure <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, and also Palestinian statehood. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> said a <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> newsletter in the 1970's advertised the `` Protocols of the Elders of Zion,'' a anti-Jewish forgery, and carried other anti-Jewish tracts _ not mentioned in questions to <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> <PERSON> Foxman </PERSON> said <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> `` may have changed somewhat but not sufficiently to set him up as a model of interreligious understanding and reconciliation.'' Particularly criticizing <PERSON> Khan </PERSON>'s reference to Zionism as racism, <PERSON> Foxman </PERSON> said, `` It reflects a mindset that has n't changed that much.'' <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, a Jewish leader acquainted with <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> through the interfaith conference, said he `` has kept open paths of communication with other religions.'' But she said he also has shown what Jews see as `` strongly anti-Semitic views,'' by disparaging Zionism as distinct from Judaism. He reflects a `` very difficult mixture of right and wrong,'' added Ms. <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, executive director emeritus of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> Sisterhoods. Much of the criticism of <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> involved alleged <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> newsletter items a decade or more ago. But <PERSON> Foxman </PERSON> also cited a June, l986, item about a dinner <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> hosted for <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> black Moslem leader <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrakhan </PERSON>. <PERSON> Farrakhan </PERSON> has called <ORGANIZATION> Judaism </ORGANIZATION> a `` dirty religion.'' <PERSON> Foxman </PERSON> also criticized <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> for a 1985 letter of appreciation to The Spotlight, a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, newsletter of the <ORGANIZATION> Liberty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lobby </ORGANIZATION>, which <PERSON> Foxman </PERSON> describes as virulently anti-Jewish. <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> said his `` innocuous'' letter mentioned no religion. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, general secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> on Religion and Peace, said the letter was merely a courteous response to solicited comment. `` Almost identical letters were written by Jewish personalities before knowing the anti-Semitic qualities of the publication,'' <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. `` Most of the accusations against <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> do not reflect personally on him, but on the distant history of organizations and others ... He distances himself from these institutional aberrations. `` <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> has stuck his neck out in some very unfriendly climate to build bridges of dialogue with Jews, Christians, Hindus and others. He has risked unpopularity in his own circles to do it.''
