<SECOND>BC-Gauguin Exhibit, Adv 01,0839</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv01</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 1, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>The Most Comprehensive Look in 30 Years at the Mysterious Gauguin</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lurking among the canvases of langorous Polynesian nudes in the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gallery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION>'s new exhibition of the works of <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Gauguin </PERSON> is a curious surprise, a wood carving that tells much about the enigmatic French artist. It is an elaborate door frame that <PERSON> Gaugin </PERSON> sculpted from redwood to decorate the entrance to the `` House of Pleasure,'' his primitive hut on the remote Marquesan island of <LOCATION> Hivaoa </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Seas </LOCATION> where he spent the last three years of his life. Carved on both sides of the base, amid a tangle of nude figures, tropical fruits, animals and leafy garlands, are the two simple commandments that seemed to frame <PERSON> Gauguin </PERSON>'s own scandalous life. Inscribed in French, one reads: `` Be amorous and you will be happy.'' The other is `` Be mysterious.'' They were obeyed with joyous abandon by <PERSON> Gauguin </PERSON>, who renounced his family and his prosperous career as a <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> stockbroker to pursue an artistic vision that led him to <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Brittany </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Martinique </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tahiti </LOCATION> and, finally, the <LOCATION> Marquesas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>, where he died in 1903 at the age of 55. The art of <PERSON> Gauguin </PERSON> as the post-impressionist master and the legend of <PERSON> Gauguin </PERSON> as the free-spirited libertine are inseparable in the National Gallery's latest blockbuster, the first major exhibition of <PERSON> Gauguin </PERSON>'s works in nearly 30 years and the most comprehensive ever held. The show, which took five years to assemble, opened Sunday for a three-month engagement before traveling to the <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION>, where it will be on view from Sept. 17 through Dec. 11, and the <LOCATION> Grand </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Palais </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, Jan. 10 through April 20 next year. Admission at the National Gallery is free, but passes are required in anticipation of heavy crowds. The exhibition is underwritten by <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and by <ORGANIZATION> Olivetti </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. The curators focused on the depth and range of <PERSON> Gauguin </PERSON>'s art rather than the `` romantic mythology'' surrounding his remarkable personal life. <PERSON> Gauguin </PERSON>'s abstract images, flattened sense of space and daring use of color, which he called `` a profound, mysterious language, a language of the dream,'' clearly inspired <PERSON> Picasso </PERSON>, <PERSON> Matisse </PERSON> and other 20th century modernists. `` You'll find <PERSON> Gauguin </PERSON> to be a fabulous and satisfying artist and an enigmatic one,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Brettell </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Dallas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> and one of the principal curators of the exhibition. The 243 objects in the show include paintings, sculpture, ceramics, prints and drawings on loan from museums and private collections around the world, from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Brettell </PERSON> said Soviet authorities were `` wonderfully cooperative'' in lending 11 paintings from their country's <PERSON> Gauguin </PERSON> collection _ the most important in the world. Many of the drawing and pictures, including the Soviet entries from the Hermitage Museum at <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Pushkin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, have never before been displayed in a major exhibition, even in the slightly larger <LOCATION> Gauguin </LOCATION> memorial show that his friends mounted in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> in 1906. But <PERSON> Brettell </PERSON> said two of <PERSON> Gauguin </PERSON>'s largest and most highly prized paintings, which the curators `` wanted desperately'' for the National Gallery show, will be absent because they are too fragile to travel. Both painted in <LOCATION> Tahiti </LOCATION> in 1898, they are `` <PERSON> Rupe </PERSON>, rupe -LRB- Gathering Fruit -RRB-'' at the Hermitage and `` Where do we come from? What are we? Where are we going?'' which remains at the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION>. A personal favorite of gallery director <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> is `` The Siesta,'' which is owned by American publisher <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Annenberg </PERSON> and has not been exhibited publicly for a quarter-century. <PERSON> Brettell </PERSON> and <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stuckey </PERSON>, curator of 20th century art at the Art Institute of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, flew to <LOCATION> Tahiti </LOCATION> to select two wood carvings by <PERSON> Gauguin </PERSON> from a small museum bearing his name. One was a bowl for eating poi, a fruit paste. The other was the missing section of the decorative door frame which is housed in the Museum d'Orsay in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. From <LOCATION> Tahiti </LOCATION>, the two curators chartered a two-engine propeller-driven plane for a harrowing, seven-hour flight through tropical storms at low altitudes across more than 900 miles of the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> to the Marquesas. <PERSON> Bretell </PERSON> calls them `` the most remote islands on earth, the end of civilization in the tropics.'' There they found <PERSON> Gauguin </PERSON>'s burial site on the outskirts of a village on <LOCATION> Hivaoa </LOCATION>, the artist's final refuge from the civilizing influence of <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> bureaucrats and missionaries who had occupied his beloved <LOCATION> Tahiti </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gauguin </PERSON>, it seems, had carefully cultivated his popular image even to the grave. The headstone he sculpted for himself was his poetic image of an ancient Polynesian spirit called `` Oviri,'' which means `` savage.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 1</NOTE>
