<HEAD>Domestic Auto Makers Report Modest Mid-April Sales Increase</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Domestic auto sales rose slightly during mid-April, although among the biggest automakers only <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> recorded car sales gains in the period. Sales of U.S.-made cars and light trucks totaled 353,314 from April 11-20, up from 308,240 a year earlier, a 1.9 percent gain in daily sales, domestic automakers reported Monday. There were eight sales days in the period this year and nine days in the period last year. The percentage changes compare average daily sales, not straight totals. The daily sales rate for light trucks rose 3.2 percent, while car sales rose 1.2 percent. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> posted a 21.4 percent increase in car sales from a soft performance in the year earlier period. Car sales declined 4.4 percent at <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and 2.6 percent at <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> from strong mid-April 1987 periods. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> car sales totaled 112,344 in mid-April, compared with <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s 65,626 and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s 33,842 `` I think that April is going to be a month in which you are going to see auto sales go back to some sort of sustainable rate,'' said <PERSON> Jeanette </PERSON> <PERSON> Garretty </PERSON>, an industry analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. She said the easing sales were not surprising after automakers' incentives kept sales brisker than expected for most of the first quarter <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Windecker </PERSON>, an analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>, said sales incentives had pushed industry sales to a 7.6 million seasonally adjusted annual rate in April 1987, a year that ended up averaging a 7.1 million rate. This year's mid-April sales were at a 7.5 million seasonally adjusted annual rate. `` These are good substantial sales, against very strong sales last year,'' <PERSON> Windecker </PERSON> said. `` It's differences in timing of incentives more than anything else.'' Among foreign manufacturers making cars in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> plants, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION>, which moved more production to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, sold 10,738 of its U.S.-made cars in the period, up from 6,488 a year earlier. <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION>'s sales of 2,950 U.S.-made cars represented a 19.3 percent drop in daily sales; <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> sold 1,396, a 17.7 percent increase; and <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION> sold 1,375, a 4.7 percent increase. Sales of imported cars and trucks are reported at the end of each month.
