<HEAD>Belo Reports 59 Percent Earnings Drop In First Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> A.H. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Belo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said Monday its earnings declined by 59 percent in the first quarter of 1988 from the same period last year, due to higher operating costs and weak advertising demand. The media company posted a profit of $ 896,000, or 9 cents per share, on revenue of $ 87.3 million during the three months ended March 31. That compared with earnings of $ 2.2 million, or 20 cents per share on revenue of $ 87.5 million in first quarter 1987. Excluding revenue from two <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> radio stations sold in 1987, first quarter revenue would have been up by $ 1.9 million from a year earlier, <PERSON> Belo </PERSON> stated. The company attributed the profit decline to higher broadcast programming costs, higher newsprint costs and weak advertising demand. <PERSON> Belo </PERSON> owns The <ORGANIZATION> Dallas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Dallas-Fort </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Worth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Suburban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspapers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, publisher of seven community newspapers. It also owns and operates five network-affiliated television stations. The Dallas Morning News' publishing revenue dipped to $ 50.7 million from $ 50.9 million a year earlier due to a sharply lower volume of advertising, <PERSON> Belo </PERSON> stated. Broadcasting revenue rose only slightly during the quarter, but was up 6.1 percent if revenue from the divested radio stations was excluded, the company said.
