<HEAD>Boeing Profit Up 15 Percent In First Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said Monday its first quarter profit rose by 15 percent from a year earlier, aided by reduced spending on research, development and new business expenses. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> had net earnings of $ 136 million, or 89 cents a share, on sales of $ 3.61 billion in the quarter ended March 31. That compared with a profit of $ 118 million, or 76 cents a share, on sales of $ 3.76 billion for the first quarter of 1987. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Shrontz </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>'s chairman and chief execurive, said the increase in first quarter profits was due primarily to lower levels of research, development and other expenses for new commercial jetliners, future military and space programs, and computer and electronics work. A lower federal income tax rate and increases in other income also helped, he said. <PERSON> Shrontz </PERSON> said the lower expenses were offset partly by higher research, development and production costs for commuter aircraft, performance problems on military aircraft work and a higher share of costs on government contracts. During the first quarter, <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> received orders for 129 commercial jets and six de Havilland turboprop planes, with a total value of $ 4.7 billion. That compares with orders totaling $ 3.5 billion in first-quarter 1987. On Monday, <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> announced a $ 1.4 billion order by <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leisure </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, the parent company of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Europe </ORGANIZATION>, for 30 <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> jetliners. That order includes 22 757-200s and eight 737-400s, subject to the completion of financing, and was scheduled for delivery beginning in 1989. Government and foreign military sales fell $ 200 million to $ 1.1 billion for the quarter, but <PERSON> Shrontz </PERSON> said military sales for the year were expected to be slightly higher than in 1987. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> had a backlog of $ 38 billion in unfinished orders at the end of the first quarter, up from $ 33.2 billion at the end of 1987.
