<SECOND>PM-Continental Trial,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Argues Bank Policy, Not Scheme, Caused Continental Loan
Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government's case against three men accused of defrauding <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> is as shaky as a broken three-legged stool, a defense attorney contends. `` If any leg is missing, it wo n't stand up, and at any point in this case, one or more of the legs are missing.'' said attorney <PERSON> Burck </PERSON> <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON>, who represents <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON>, former head of oil and gas lending at the failed <ORGANIZATION> Penn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Square </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. The government charged that <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON> joined with <LOCATION> Tulsa </LOCATION> oil driller <PERSON> Jere </PERSON> <PERSON> Sturgis </PERSON> and another bank officer, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lytle </PERSON>, in a scheme to defraud the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> bank. The three men pleaded innocent to charges of fraud and misapplication of funds. Closing arguments in the 6 -LCB- - week trial before <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> <PERSON> Shadur </PERSON> were expected to be completed today before the case goes to the jury In his closing argument Monday, <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON> contended that <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> was saddled with troublesome oil and energy loans because of an aggressive lending policy, not because of a fraud scheme. Between July 1981 and 1982, when the alleged fraud scheme took place, `` there was the widely held view that oil and gas prices would rise so quickly that time would take care of any problems with these loans,'' <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Lytle </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> vice president, was accused of taking kickbacks in exchange for fundin