<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Early contract negotiations between <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> have soured but remain alive, despite a `` no-show'' protest by union representatives and other frictions inside and outside of actual bargaining. <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> negotiators and union leaders scheduled to begin this week's meetings with <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> on Monday morning instead met privately for four hours and debated whether to continue the talks, said <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Barbee </PERSON> While <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s team cooled its heels, union negotiators discussed the rank-and-file's angry reaction to several announcements last week _ such as disclosure of <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> chairman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON>'s eight-figure wages for 1987 _ that seemed timed to doom the talks. `` The talks may be in fatal trouble already but it's a little too early to tell,'' said <PERSON> Harley </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaiken </PERSON>, labor and technology expert at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>. The union and the No. 3 automaker are negotiating a replacement for a contract expiring Sept. 14. The contract covers at least 66,000 active and laid-off workers in 15 states and 65,000 retirees. Angering the rank and file were revelations of executive compensation for 1987 that included nearly $ 18 million for <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON>, and the planned transfer of waning K-car production from two <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> plants to one in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> in 1989. The union will urge <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> to keep producing K-cars _ the <ORGANIZATION> Dodge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aries </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Plymouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reliant </ORGANIZATION> _ at its <LOCATION> Jefferson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Avenue </LOCATION> plant in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> vice president and head of the union's <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> department. The Jefferson Avenue plant produces four-door K-cars while a <LOCATION> Toluca </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> factory produces two-door models. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> is scheduled to move <LOCATION> Omni </LOCATION> and Horizon production from a plant it is closing in <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> to the Jefferson Avenue Plant this summer and said last week it would consolidate K-car production in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> said union officials think the plant can produce both cars. `` We would urge the corporation to change its plan,'' he said. At the bargaining table, talks that were supposed to last two to three weeks as the two sides fit an industry-pattern contract to <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> began to drag as <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> made proposals guaranteed to be rejected. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> Vice President <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON> has publicly said he will work within the job-protecting pattern contract already in force at <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, but union officials say <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> bargainers are strongly resisting it. `` They have not come up with any pattern proposals. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s first offer is garbage _ all take-aways We're not going to take any concessions,'' said <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> DeFrancesco </PERSON>, an official at <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> Local 624 in <LOCATION> Syracuse </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION> <PERSON> DeFrancesco </PERSON> was among nearly 100 officials of local unions at <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> plants nationwide who gathered in <LOCATION> Huntsville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, Thursday night and Friday. At the meeting, the local leaders heard and booed company proposals and urged bargainers to break off talks, according to <PERSON> DeFrancesco </PERSON> and others who attended. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Northard </PERSON> said he still believed the two sides would reach an early settlement, which had been intended to mend their damaged relationship. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> seeks a minimum age for early retirement instead of the current `` 30-and-out'' provision, which is the right to retire after 30 years in the factory regardless of age. It wants workers to take vacations only when plants are shut down, or lose them and wants workers who do n't join pre-paid health plans to pay $ 35 a month in insurance fees. The automaker also wants widespread adoption of Japanese-style plant work agreements at a time when some plants that have accepted them are hitting snags in putting the so-called Modern Operating Agreements into practice. Workers who made deep sacrifices that helped save <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> in the early 1980s expected a return to normality once <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> returned to profitability. Instead, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> early this year announced plans to close a 5,500-worker former <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> assembly plant in <LOCATION