<TEXT>
 Stock prices pushed ahead today, extending their advance of the past three sessions. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which rose more than 20 points on Monday, was up another 16.91 points at 2,052.88 after 90 minutes of trading. Gainers outnumbered losers by 3 to 1 in the overall tally of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 940 up, 303 down and 491 unchanged. Volume on the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> came to 50.58 million shares as of 11 a.m. on Wall Street. Before trading started, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported that the the economy grew at a 2.3 percent annual rate in the first three months of 1988. That was down from growth of 4.8 percent in the October-December quarter, but was in line with most economists' forecasts for the January-March period. The report also said the rate of inflation had slowed, with a price measure tied to the GNP rising at an annual rate of 2.4 percent, down from a 2.7 percent increase in the fourth quarter. Analysts said the report contained little that was unexpected, and said it had little effect on the movement of stock prices. But by the same token, the report failed to dampen recent expectations that the economy continues to show signs of strength despite earlier fears that it would bog down after last October's market crash Stock prices have also benefitted in recent days from some strong earnings reports. Among the actively-traded issues on the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Tandem </ORGANIZATION> was up 1 ~ at 19 -LRB-, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Telegraph was unchanged at 27 \ and <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> was up | at 114 Lucky Stores was up 1 -LRB- at 55 -LRB- after a