<FIRST>u f PM-EarnsOil     04-26 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Earns Oil,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texaco Says 1st Quarter Earnings Doubled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's third-largest oil company, today announced that its first-quarter earnings rose by 105 percent compared with the same period last year. The <LOCATION> White </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, N.Y.-based company said it earned $ 242 million, or $ 1.00 per share, on $ 8.7 billion of revenue, vs. $ 118 million, or 49 cents per share, on $ 8.5 billion in 1987 first-quarter sales. The latest earnings included a $ 66 million gain on the sale of <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s interest in an offshore <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> joint venture, as well as $ 29 million gain on foreign currency transactions, which compared with a $ 7 million loss in the same period last year, the company said. It also included an increase of corporate and nonoperating charges to $ 249 million from $ 100 million in the 1987 first quarter. That hike was due in part `` to the recognition in the 1987 quarter of $ 73 million in nonrecurring benefits relating to prior years income tax adjustments,'' <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> said. `` The legal and related costs associated with the bankruptcy proceedings and the financing expenses incident to the company's ultimate emergence from Chapter 11 also contributed to the increase in corporate expenses,'' the company said Otherwise, <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kinnear </PERSON> said its performance was helped by improved domestic refining and marketing margins and strong petrochemical results. Slumping crude prices were offset by improved earnings from natural gas operations due to settlement of certain take-or-pay issues and higher natural gas sales prices and volumes, the company said. <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> emerged from Chapter 11 earlier this month in a reorganization that included a $ 3 billion payment to <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> to settle a $ 10.3 judgment held against <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> by <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> resulting from a jury's decision that <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> had improperly interfered with a <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> acquisition of part of <ORGANIZATION> Getty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>.
