<HEAD>Pilots Union Sues United Airlines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> pilots are suing the airline, its parent, <ORGANIZATION> Allegis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, and the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union in an effort to strike down contract provisions they say could block an employee takeover of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION>. The lawsuit was filed Monday in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> by the <ORGANIZATION> Airline </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Hank </PERSON> <PERSON> Krakowski </PERSON>, a union spokesman. The suit challenges two provisions in a November agreement between <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union, <PERSON> Krakowski </PERSON> said. `` We want a judgment from the court to declare that these provisions are illegal, so we can move forward in our attempts to affect employee ownership of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>,'' he said. One provision prohibits the union from participating in an employee ownership plan unless the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union agrees to the terms. The other contested provision would give the Machinists the option of receiving substantial pay increases, reopening their contract or striking in the event of a change in control of <ORGANIZATION> Allegis </ORGANIZATION>. The pilots' lawsuit alleges that the provisions, called `` protective covenants,'' are part of an illegal campaign by <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> directors to `` entrench themselves in office at the expense of <ORGANIZATION> Allegis </ORGANIZATION> shareholders,'' the union stated. `` We have n't seen the suit so we have no comment,'' said <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON>. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheehy </PERSON>, another <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, said the provisions addressed in the suit are part of a three-year agreement between the company and the union regarding work and wage rules. `` Details of it are n't for public consumption,'' he said. A spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union could not be reached for comment Monday night. United pilots have been working toward an employee takeover for about a year, but the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union has opposed the plan. United pilots made an unsuccessful $ 4.5 billion bid for the airline last April, opposing <ORGANIZATION> Allegis </ORGANIZATION>' diversification into a travel services conglomerate. The offer led to a proxy fight by a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> investor group, <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION>, to unseat <ORGANIZATION> Allegis </ORGANIZATION> directors, and <ORGANIZATION> Allegis </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferris </PERSON> later resigned. <ORGANIZATION> Allegis </ORGANIZATION> directors agreed to sell the company's hotel and rental car businesses and to drop the <ORGANIZATION> Allegis </ORGANIZATION> name as part of a $ 3.65 billion restructuring plan.
