<FIRST>r f AM-ManufacturingEmployment Bjt   04-26 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Manufacturing Employment, Bjt,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>Manufacturing Employment Plummets, Some Business Buck Trend</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release at 6:30 p.m. EDT; Manufactures is cq in 3rd graf.
A version moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The number of Americans manufacturing things for a living has fallen in this decade, although such areas as transportation equipment, plastics and furniture are bucking the trend, the <ORGANIZATION> Census </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> reported Tuesday. Overall, employment in manufacturing businesses fell by 731,900 between 1982 and 1986, the bureau said. That represented a decline of 4 percent, to 17,086,200 workers, according to preliminary statistics from the 1986 Annual Survey of Manufactures. More recently, however, manufacturing employment has been increasing as the devalued dollar boosts sale of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> goods abroad. According to the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, manufacturing jobs rose by 400,000 between June 1987 and March 1988, a period not covered by the <ORGANIZATION> Census </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION>'s survey. Between 1982 and 1986, the hardest-hit sector was machinery manufacturing, which lost 325,700 jobs. Imports were a major reason for the 15 percent decline to 1,863,000 employees in businesses making heavy industrial and construction machinery, said <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Census </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> analyst. Another area affected by imported products in recent years _ apparel and textile products _ saw employment fall 14 percent to 1,016,500 in 1986. That represented a loss of 172,500 jobs, the report said. Primary metal industries also suffered, losing 164,900 jobs to fall to a total of 689,200 in 1986. Manufacture of leather goods saw a loss of 70,000 jobs, representing a 35 percent decline to 1986 employment of 129,800. Tobacco products suffered a 20 percent job loss between 1982 and 1986, with employment falling to 46,100 in the continuation of a 20-year trend. On the positive side, companies making transportation equipment added 173,600 workers over the period, an 11 percent increase to 1,769,500. Transportation equipment is a wide-ranging field including aircraft, trucks and trailers, automobiles, ships, motor homes and even some defense equipment such as missiles, <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> said. Computer products have helped boost employment in electronic industries slightly, the study showed. That area employed 1,941,400 people in 1986, up 26,900 from 1982. Printing and publishing added 84,400 people over the period and wood products and furniture-making also showed growth. Nationally, while total employment in manufacturing fell between 1982 and 1986, payroll was up from $ 204.5 billion to $ 231.7 billion. Here is a rundown of industry groups, employment in 1986 and change from 1982: _ All industries: 17,086,200, down 731,900 Gainers: _ Transportation equipment, 1,769,500, up 173,600 _ Printing and publishing, 1,376,200, up 84,400 _ Rubber and plastics products, 741,300, up 59,600 _ Lumber and wood products, 619,500, up 43,100 _ Furniture and fixtures, 466,700, up 30,700 _ Electric and electronic equipment, 1,941,400, up 26,900 Losers: _ Machinery, except electrical, 1,863,000, down 325,700 _ Apparel and other textile products, 1,016,500, down 172,500 _ Primary metal industries, 689,200, down 164,900 _ Food and kindred products: 1,408,900, down 78,800 _ Textile mill products, 644,300, down 73,100 _ Chemicals and allied products, 801,600, down 71,000 _ Leather and leather products, 129,800, down 70,000 _ Miscellaneous manufacturing, 326,100, down 56,500 _ Fabricated metal products, 1,419,500, down 40,200 _ Instruments and related products, 585,400, down 38,200 _ Petroleum and coal products, 124,500, down 27,100 _ Stone, clay and glass products, 514,100, down 17,400 _ Tobacco products, 46,100, down 11,800 _ Paper and allied products, 602,600, down 3,000
</TEXT>
