<HEAD>Takeover Fight Involves Court, Advertising, Proxies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> investor and television game show magnate <PERSON> Burt </PERSON> <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON>, whose sucesses include `` The Dating Game,'' wants a match that will last with <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. But the family that controls the media empire through a special class of stock hopes shareholders will give <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON>'s $ 1.6 billion takeover bid the cutoff treatment accorded many contestants on another <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON> program _ `` The Gong Show.'' The takeover fight under way in advance of <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION>'s May 20 shareholders meeting has been waged on three fronts _ in court, in proxy materials and in newspaper advertisements. The battle is being monitored closely by major publishers including the <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, among other media companies that have dual classes of stock intended to keep control in the hands of a few people. The <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> family is seeking to tighten its grip on <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> with a charter change to be voted on next month in reaction to the bid for Media General. <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON>, through two companies he heads, offered in February to pay $ 61.50 a share for the nearly 90 percent of Media General stock he does not control. But the family of Media General Chairman <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tennant </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> declined the offer, expressing a desire to keep the Richmond-based company independent. <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON> controls just over 10 percent of the 28 million shares of <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION>'s Class A common stock. But the <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> family owns 71 percent of the more powerful 559,168 outstanding Class B shares, which elect seven of the company's 10 directors. In lawsuits filed last month in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Court in <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, Media General accused <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON> of inciting speculation in the company's stock. Management also wants the court to order <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON> to sell his shares. <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON>, meanwhile, asked the court to allow <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> shareholders to vote as a single class on his offer and maintained only the three Class A directors should be allowed to consider the buyout. Media General's management contends the buyout requires approval of two-thirds of each class voting separately, but <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON> says a majority vote of the combined Class A and B shares is all that is necessary for ratification. A hearing is set for Wednesday in the court dispute. After the suits were filed, <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON> placed full-page ads in The Wall Street Journal and two Media General daily newspapers, the Richmond Times-Dispatch and The Richmond News Leader. The ads criticized the company's two-tier stock arrangement and asked shareholders not to vote on management's proxy statement until receiving <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON>'s proposals. <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON> also is seeking to be elected to <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION>'s board along with his allies, <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> billionaire <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSO