ler </ORGANIZATION> would be a strong provider of jobs. At the national contract negotiations, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> continued talking Tuesday in an atmosphere that improved after a protest Monday by <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> bargainers, who boycotted the talks for several hours. Union bargainers had debated whether to break off the early negotiations because of what they considered disruptive announcements the previous week, including <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON>'s $ 18 million 1987 earnings. Rank-and-file members also were angered by <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s decision to halt <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> production of its Dodge Aries and <ORGANIZATION> Plymouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reliant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> K-cars </ORGANIZATION> at the end of the year and fill 1989 orders by increasing production at a Mexican plant. On Thursday and Friday, local union leaders received detailed reports of <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s initial contract proposals, which veered sharply from a job-protecting industry-pattern pact established last fall at <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The contract, which covers 66,000 active and laid-off workers in 15 states and 65,000 retirees, expires Sept. 14. The two sides agreed to early talks to prevent further deterioration in their damaged relationship. Workers already angered by the <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION> decision threatened to cripple <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> with plant-by-plant strikes and general non-cooperation when it attempted to sell its 28,000-worker <ORGANIZATION> Acustar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> parts subs