 <ORGANIZATION> Procter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gamble </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday its fiscal third quarter profit jumped 40 percent over a year ago, boosted by a lower federal tax rate. The consumer products giant said it netted $ 263 million, or $ 1.53 a share, for the three months ended March 31, compared with earnings of $ 188 million, or $ 1.10 a share, last year. Worldwide sales also rose, to $ 4.8 billion from $ 4.2 billion. For the first nine months of the company's 1987-88 fiscal year, net income totaled $ 880 million, or $ 5.14 a share, on sales of $ 4.86 billion. That compared with earnings of $ 651 million, or $ 3.82 a share, and $ 4.22 billion in sales. <ORGANIZATION> Procter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gamble </ORGANIZATION> attributed its improved third quarter results largely to a lower tax rate. <ORGANIZATION> Procter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Gamble </ORGANIZATION> produces a variety of consumer goods, including laundry and cleaning products, personal card products, pharmaceuticals, food and beverage products. The Cincinnati-based company had sales of $ 17 billion in its last fiscal year.
