<FIRST>u f AM-Panama-FreeZone Bjt   04-26 0815</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama-Free Zone, Bjt,0842</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colon Free Zone: Crisis Delivers Sharp Setback</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLON FREE ZONE, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Colon Free Zone, normally one of the world's busiest trading centers, is unusually quiet these days. Huge container trucks stand unused in the zone's narrow streets, empty cardboard boxes are piled on the sidewalks and workers sit idle, waiting for something to do. <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s political and economic crisis has dealt a severe blow to the Colon Free Zone, considered the second largest in the world after <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>. Since the deepening of the nation's woes in late February, trade has slowed dramatically, small firms have shut their doors, and employees have been placed on unpaid leave. `` The situation could n't be worse,'' said <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Colon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Users </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which represents businesses here. <PERSON> Jaime </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mizrachi </PERSON>, manager of <LOCATION> Mizratex </LOCATION>, said, `` We've never seen a situation like this, ever.'' And a truck driver, who refused to give his name for fear of reprisals, said, `` There's nothing to do.'' He's had little work in nearly two months, he said. There are few buyers purchasing goods that need to be hauled outside the zone. The total value of trade in the center was $ 205.4 million in March, a 36.1 percent drop from March 1987, according to the zone's administrative office Broken down, the figures show that the value of goods imported to the zone plunged 54.9 percent last month. Exports were off 17.4 percent. <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> expects an even worse trade picture this month. He projects a decline of 50 percent or more in the total value of commerce. `` The current situation puts in imminent danger the existence of the firms and the 8,000 permanent -LRB- jobs -RRB- of Panamanians who work in -LRB- the zone -RRB-,'' the users association said recently. The contraction comes after businesses rang up $ 4.33 billion in trade in all of last year, the highest since the 94-acre center was created in 1948. Before the crisis virtually paralyzed the nation's economy, government officials had been projecting another banner year in 1988. Latin American countries, the zone's target group, have shaken off some of their economic woes and been more flush with cash in recent years. Located in the city of Colon at the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> entrance to the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION>, the free zone acts as a channel for trade. Such consumer goods as televisions, jewelry, cosmetics, clothing, liquor and pharmaceuticals flow into the zone from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> and elsewhere. Once in the zone, the products are stored, repackaged, taken apart or put together and sent on to buyers mostly in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. If bound for other countries, goods are free of duties, assessments and fees. Profits are taxed at low rates. More than 700 companies have set up shop in the zone and hundreds more are represented here. But with the nation's latest troubles, businessmen say some small firms have already packed up and left. `` If you take a walk, you can see a lot of places that say, ` For Rent'' or ` For Sale,''' said <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>. `` Two months ago, you could n't get 50 meters of space in here to rent out.'' He is worried that, `` Those that go are not going to come back and it's going to be very difficult to get new business.'' The key problem for the zone was the government's March 3 closure of the nation's international banking center. The banks suffered a cash squeeze aggravated by the freezing of official Panamanian deposits in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks. The shortage prevented the government from providing <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s dozen locally owned and operated banks with enough money to cover a run on deposits that began Feb. 26, when military strongman, Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, ousted the president, <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON>. Since then, the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has imposed sweeping sanctions on <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> in an effort to force the removal of <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, who is under indictment in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on drug trafficking charges. `` The closing of the banks has been the most damaging single effect on the free zone,'' said <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Maduro </PERSON>, general manager of the firm <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Toledano </PERSON>. The trade center is highly dependent on credit. Money is lent to firms in the zone to buy imports and to Latin American buyers who then purchase those goods for re-export. `` Ninety-five percent of the business in the free zone -LRB- involves -RRB- banking,'' said <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>. `` We do it through banks. We do n't use cash at all.'' The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, the government's bank regulatory agency, has recently permitted the nation's approximately 120 banks to resume limited operations Late Monday, the commission announced the banks could resume, with certain restrictions, handling letters of credit, an instrument widely used in the free zone to guarantee payment. Businessmen doubted the step would have much impact on their trade because of the restricted service and uncertainty about the nation's future.
</TEXT>
