<HEAD>Poloroid Reports Drop In Quarterly Profit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday that its first quarter profit slipped nearly 50 percent from a year ago despite a moderate rise in worldwide sales. The company blamed part of the poor performance on higher tax rates and a sharp increase in expenditures linked to the planned introduction of a new instant camera line next month. For the first three months of the year, net income totaled $ 12.8 million, or 21 cents a share, on sales of $ 410.1 million. That compared with earnings of $ 24.6 million, or 40 cents a share, and sales of $ 381.1 million in 1987. <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> said profits from operations fell to $ 26.2 million for the period from $ 30.1 million during the first quarter last year. <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Yanes </PERSON> said expenditures associated with the introduction of the Impulse instant camera hurt earnings. <PERSON> Yanes </PERSON> said some of the first quarter costs involved marketing geared toward clearing inventory of existing cameras and promotion of the two Impluse cameras, scheduled to be introduced in stores nationwide on May 9. <PERSON> Yanes </PERSON> said other expenditures included research and development. The cameras, unveiled to the media in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> earlier this month, are listed to sell at $ 89 and $ 69. The company also noted foreign currency exchange losses and a 30 percent increase in worldwide tax payments compared with the first quarter of 1987 contributed to the profit and earnings decline.
