<HEAD>GE Shareholders To Vote On Abortion Proposal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA STOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FAIRFIELD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> stockholder is asking the company's shareholders to vote on `` refraining from support of any organizations that counsel or perform abortion.'' The company, whose annual meeting is Wednesday in <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION>, says in its proxy statement that it recommends a vote against the proposal. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Jamison </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION>, said the company `` does n't knowingly support any organization that is pro- or anti-abortion. The proposal is being offered in the name of <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Leschin </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Marshalltown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, but he referred questions to his wife, <PERSON> Shirley </PERSON>, who said she had `` nothing to say other than what is worded in the resolution.'' The proposal said the `` the cumulative demographic facts of abortion on demand ... have now begun to impact on the American society.'' It said abortion's consequences include `` the closing of schools due to an absence of children, the ongoing expansion of nursing care facilities of the elderly, and the future lack of younger workers to sustain the Social Security system and the defense of our nation.'' In the proxy statement, <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION> said its `` board opposes this proposal because the company does not adopt positions unrelated to business interests ... the company has adopted no position on the abortion issue.'' When asked if the company offers charitable contributions to groups on either side of the abortion issue, <PERSON> Jamison </PERSON> said, `` Not that we know of.'' <PERSON> Ned </PERSON> <PERSON> Raynolds </PERSON>, a senior vice president of the public relations firm <ORGANIZATION> Hill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Knowlton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said the anti-abortion proposal reflects `` the basic phenomenon where people like to use the proxy machinery to express an opinion on something.'' `` This woman has an anti-abortion point of view, apparently,'' he said. <PERSON> Raynolds </PERSON>, who said he has supervised studies of company annual reports, said `` there are all kinds of things'' showing up on proxy statements ranging from experimental tests with animals to protesting <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> holdings. Shareholders of <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, for instance, defeated a resolution on Monday that would have prohibited company benefit payments for abortions and related services and required management to disclose to shareholders any information about research and testing on animals. `` Nothing really surprises me in a proxy statement anymore,'' <PERSON> Raynolds </PERSON> said. `` This is a trend documented in lots of places where institutions used to sell stock if they did n't like management, but now they want to own stock and stay in, but get their point of across.''
