<HEAD>First RepublicBank Reports $1.5 Billion Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ailing <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> RepublicBank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, confirming an earlier announcement, reported Tuesday a $ 1.5 billion loss for the first quarter of 1988 and attributed much of it to heavy real estate loan losses. The amount is the sixth-largest quarterly loss by a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corporation and is triple the amount of corporate projections. A preliminary announcement of the earnings loss on April 12 followed a $ 1 billion emergency loan extended by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deposit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> to the Dallas-based holding company on March 19. In 1987, bank officials reported a loss of $ 656 million. Company officials said the first quarter loss primarily is the result of a $ 1.4 billion loan loss in its real estate loan portfolio and $ 126 million of losses and write-downs of assets. Earlier this month, Comptroller of the Currency <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Clarke </PERSON> urged <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> RepublicBank </ORGANIZATION> to begin restructuring and change its leadership. <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fronterhouse </PERSON>, former chairman and chief executive officer, resigned April 12, when the huge loss was first indicated. He was the second top executive to leave the firm during the management shake-up arranged by federal regulators. Other top officials followed Fronterhouse's departure. Fronterhouse was replaced by <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Casey </PERSON>, 68, former chairman of the board of <ORGANIZATION> AMR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, parent company of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>. `` The actions taken in the first quarter are consistent with our intention that the company move ahead with its plan to restructure and to recapitalize operations,'' <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> said in a statement Monday. First RepublicBank, the nation's 13th largest bank holding company, included $ 235 million in its loan-loss provision for Third World countries, increasing the provision to $ 612 million or 50 percent of the bank's $ 1.2 billion of outstanding debt to these countries. The total loan loss provision exceeded what the company already had written off in loan losses by $ 1.1 billion. The bank reported total non-performing assets increased from $ 543 million in the fourth quarter of 1987 to $ 4.5 billion in the first quarter of 1988 ending March 31. Eighty-five percent of the non-performing assets increase was attributed to real estate-related assets, the bank said.
